{"title_page": "Terry Lamb", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name            = Terry Lamb\n|fullname        = Terence John Lamb\n|image           = Terry Lamb.jpg\n|image_size      = \n|caption         = \n|position        = {{rlp|FE|HB}}\n|birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1961|9|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|height          = {{convert|166|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name = \"Bulldogs\" />\n|weight          = {{convert|80|kg|stlb|0|abbr=on}}<ref name = \"Bulldogs\" />\n|retired         = yes\n|club1           = [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Western Suburbs]]\n|year1start      = 1980\n|year1end        = 83\n|appearances1    = 88\n|tries1          = 41\n|goals1          = 11\n|fieldgoals1     = 7\n|points1         = 163\n|club2           = {{nowrap|[[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury Bulldogs]]}}\n|year2start      = 1984\n|year2end        = 96\n|appearances2    = 262\n|tries2          = 123\n|goals2          = 375\n|fieldgoals2     = 37\n|points2         = 1279\n|teamA           = [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n|yearAstart      = 1981\n|yearAend        = 89\n|appearancesA    = 8\n|triesA          = 0\n|goalsA          = 0\n|fieldgoalsA     = 0\n|pointsA         = 0\n|teamB           = [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia]]\n|yearBstart      = 1986\n|yearBend        =  \n|appearancesB    = 7\n|triesB          = 0\n|goalsB          = 0 \n|fieldgoalsB     = 0 \n|pointsB         = 0\n|coachteam1      = [[Wests Tigers]]\n|coachyear1start = 2001\n|coachyear1end   = 02\n|coachgames1     = 50\n|coachwins1      = 16\n|coachdraws1     = 0\n|coachlosses1    = 34\n|source          = <ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com/players/Terry-Lamb/summary.html Rugby League Project]</ref><ref>[http://www.yesterdayshero.com.au/PlayerProfile_Terry-Lamb_4717.aspx Yesterday's Hero] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005035248/http://www.yesterdayshero.com.au/PlayerProfile_Terry-Lamb_4717.aspx |date=5 October 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/coaches/terry-lamb/summary.html Rugby League Project Coaches]</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Terry Lamb''' [[Order of Australia|OAM]], (born 15 September 1961), also known by the [[nickname]] of '''\"Baa\"''', <ref>[http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/beaver-raises-the-baa/story-e6frep9o-1111117663838 \"Beaver raises the Baa\"] By David Riccio ''[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph]]'' 5 October 2008</ref> is an Australian former [[rugby league]] footballer and coach. He played 350 games, with the [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] (1980\u20131983) and [[Bulldogs Rugby League Football Club|Canterbury]] (1984\u20131996). Lamb was known for his support of the ball-carrier - his ability to be in the right place at the right time netted him 164 [[Try (rugby)|tries]]. This earned him the moniker of \"The Back-up Man\". He also kicked 386 [[Goal (sport)#Rugby football|goal]]s and 44 [[drop goal|field goal]]s, for 1,442 points in first grade. He played for [[New South Wales]] in [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]]. Lamb holds the distinction of being the only player to appear in every match of a [[Kangaroo Tour]].\n\n==Junior career==\nLamb grew up in [[Chester Hill, New South Wales|Chester Hill]], a suburb in the [[City of Bankstown|Bankstown]] area and attended [[Sefton High School]]. Lamb played all his junior rugby league for the Chester Hill Hornets club during the years 1967&ndash;1979 where he won multiple Best and Fairest awards. {{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} He only played in one Grand Final when he filled in for a side above his age group. Lamb is the only International to come from the Chester Hill Hornets club and the ground is now named the [[Terry Lamb Complex]] in his honour. Lamb represented Canterbury in junior representative sides, but signed his first professional contract with [[Western Suburbs Magpies]].\n\n==Western Suburbs Magpies career==\nLamb was a non-playing reserve for the [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]] Third Grade side in 1979 and was hopeful of a contract with his junior side in 1980. Lamb was told the best he could hope for was a position in the Presidents Cup (Under 21s) side. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nOn 18 May [[1980 NSWRFL season|1980]], Lamb made his first grade premiership debut for [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Western Suburbs]] against [[Balmain Tigers]] at [[Lidcombe Oval]]. Lamb scored two tries in the Magpies' comprehensive 26-4<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/games/1980/198005180324.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007193818/http://www.stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/games/1980/198005180324.html |archivedate=7 October 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> victory. Lamb scored 9 tries in his debut season and was edged out for the inaugural Dally M Rookie of the Year award by teammate [[Jim Leis]] who would go on the Australian 1980 Tour of New Zealand. Lamb formed a great scrumbase combination that season with [[Alan Neil]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nLamb's form in the early stages of the [[1981 NSWRFL season|1981 season]] was outstanding and he was selected in the [[New South Wales state rugby league team|NSW State of Origin side]]. Lamb was called in at the last moment for a very ill [[Mick Pattison]] {{citation needed|date=March 2017}} and only arrived in [[Brisbane]] on the day of the match (when Pattison took ill, NSW coach [[Ted Glossop]] initially wanted to move [[Steve Rogers (rugby league)|Steve Rogers]] from the centres to five-eighth and play whoever the league gave him as a replacement back from the bench but was overruled by the [[NSWRL]]. Lamb, who at the time worked as a linesman for [[Telstra|Telecom]], was literally found up a telegraph pole and had to make a rushed flight to Brisbane). {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Lamb met his halves partner, young [[Parramatta Eels|Parramatta]] halfback [[Peter Sterling (rugby league commentator)|Peter Sterling]], for the first time only two hours before kickoff. Lamb made his Origin debut at [[Lang Park]] playing opposite another young player on the rise, [[Queensland Maroons|Queensland]] captain [[Wally Lewis]] who had made his test debut against [[France national rugby league team|France]] only a few weeks earlier. NSW led 15-5 at half time mostly due to the Parramatta connection of Sterling, [[Ray Price (rugby)|Ray Price]], [[Michael Cronin (rugby league)|Michael Cronin]] and [[Eric Grothe Sr.|Eric Grothe]] who picked up a loose [[Greg Conescu]] pass to race 90 metres to score in the first half. But the Maroons, led by Lewis and man of the match [[Chris Close]], came back strong in the second half to win 22-15.\n\nThe [[1982 NSWRFL season|1982 season]] was a successful one for Wests and Lamb where his end of season form caught the eyes of the [[Australian Rugby League|Australian]] selectors and he was selected for the [[1982 Kangaroo tour]]. Lamb ruled himself out of the tour as he already planned to marry his partner Kim. [[Australian Kangaroos|The Kangaroos]] swept all before them on the tour going through undefeated for the first time and becoming known as \"[[The Invincibles (rugby league)|The Invincibles]]\".\n\nLamb's final season with Wests was in [[1983 NSWRFL season|1983]] where the Magpies won the dreaded [[Australian rugby league wooden spooners|wooden spoon]] prize. In spite of this, he was awarded the [[Dally M Player of the Year Award]]. His prize winnings of $9,000 that night was $500 more than his contract that season. {{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nTerry Lamb made 88 appearances for Wests, Lamb was later named as halfback in the Western Suburbs Magpies Team of the Eighties.<ref>{{cite web|title=VEST, KEATO, COGGER ALL HONOURED|url=http://www.weststigers.com.au/default.aspx?s=article-display&id=30925&title=vest,-keato,-cogger-all-honoured|accessdate=30 September 2010|website=weststigers.com.au|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227200942/http://www.weststigers.com.au/default.aspx?s=article-display&id=30925&title=vest%2C-keato%2C-cogger-all-honoured|archivedate=27 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Joining the Bulldogs and early success==\nThe news that Lamb's Dally M winnings was more than his contract ensured that he would be in hot demand from the richer Sydney clubs now that he was out of contract and that [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] were at first expelled from the premiership. [[Sydney Roosters|Easts]] and [[Balmain Tigers|Balmain]] both showed interest but eventually Lamb chose the Bulldogs, joining in 1984.<ref name = \"Bulldogs\" >[http://thebulldogs.com.au/sportal.php?page=player&id=477 Bulldogs.com.au - Terry Lamb]</ref>\n\nLamb settled nicely into Canterbury under the coaching of [[Warren Ryan]] and playing outside [[Steve Mortimer]]. Lamb's arrival did cause initial controversy when long-serving five-eighth [[Garry Hughes]] was dropped to reserve grade in what was to be his final season. Lamb's ability to back up the ball-carrier came to the fore as he was the Sydney Premiership's joint leading tryscorer with 17.<ref>http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/NSWRL_1984/summary.html</ref> Lamb won a recall to the [[New South Wales Rugby League|New South Wales]] [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] side for the 2nd match. He played well enough to be retained for the 3rd match despite the Blues losing, but withdrew due to injury. Lamb never won a junior premiership and he was closing in on one at senior level when the Bulldogs made the 1984 Grand Final against arch-rivals [[Parramatta Eels]] who were looking to win their fourth successive title. Canterbury took out the Grand Final 6\u20134 in a bruising game of football. Lamb was replaced with five minutes remaining due to a nasty gash above his eye.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/league_of_legends/100_years_of_the_game/slideshow_11_4.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201112051/http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/league_of_legends/100_years_of_the_game/slideshow_11_4.html |archivedate=1 December 2008 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Lamb played 22 games for the Bulldogs, but was forced to miss the 1985 Grand Final due to a groin injury. [[Michael Hagan]] was named as his replacement.<ref>http://thebulldogs.com.au/sportal.php?page=player&id=477</ref> Canterbury defeated [[St. George Dragons]] 7\u20136 to make it back-to-back titles.\n\n1986 was an eventful year for Lamb. He played much of the opening rounds at halfback with captain [[Steve Mortimer]] suspended, and was recalled to the [[New South Wales Rugby League|New South Wales]] [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] side. He was selected in all three matches from the bench and went on to be selected in the [[Australian national rugby league team|Australian]] Test side for the opening match against New Zealand. Lamb came on from the bench as a replacement for [[Dale Shearer]]. Lamb got more time in the 3rd Test when he came as a replacement for the injured [[Wayne Pearce]] playing lock forward. His good form at Canterbury continued with the Bulldogs making a third successive Grand Final, once again playing [[Parramatta Eels]]. Lamb was the leading pointscorer for the season, and he would end up scoring 210 points.<ref>http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/NSWRL_1986/summary.html</ref> However, he missed a difficult penalty goal attempt in the final three minutes of the 1986 Grand Final. The Eels won 4-2. Lamb was then selected to go on the [[Kangaroo Tour]].\n\nIn March 1987, Lamb scored all of Canterbury's 26 points as they beat Wests 26-16 in round 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/players/T/Terry_Lamb.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204013207/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/players/T/Terry_Lamb.html |archivedate=4 February 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lamb's points haul were made up of four tries and five goals. He again finished the season as the leagues leading try-scorer<ref>http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/NSWRL_1987/summary.html</ref> however, the club failed to make the finals, finishing 6th in what would prove to be Warren Ryan's last season as coach.\n\n[[Warren Ryan]] departed Canterbury at the end of 1987 with reserve grade coach [[Phil Gould (rugby league)|Phil Gould]] taking over the reins in a caretaker role with [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Chris Anderson]] being groomed for the top position.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bulldogs.rleague.com/reviews/1988review.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425015122/http://bulldogs.rleague.com/reviews/1988review.php |archivedate=25 April 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 1988 season was Lamb's fifth at Canterbury and the first he wouldn't cross the line at least 10 times. Lamb played a very important role in Canterbury's season as former captain [[Steve Mortimer]] missed a large chunk of the season due to injuries. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n==Hanley incident and the World Cup==\nCanterbury played the 1988 Grand Final against [[Balmain Tigers|Balmain]], a game which the Bulldogs won 24-12. As well as scoring a try, Terry Lamb was involved in a first-half tackle, along with [[Andrew Farrar]], which resulted in the concussion of influential Balmain star, [[Ellery Hanley]]. Hanley was sent to the head bin, and although he managed to return to the field before half-time, he did not appear fully aware of his surroundings, and was replaced at half-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/south-west/nrl-grand-final-top-5-grand-final-moments-for-canterbury-bulldogs/news-story/2c7fb1748fad22e5b177c4dc92a0daaa |title=NRL grand final: Top 5 grand final moments for Canterbury Bulldogs |last=Murray |first=Oliver |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=30 September 2014 |access-date=9 June 2019}}</ref> Lamb says that there was no malice, and Hanley was not deliberately targeted.<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Peter Sterling (Presenter) |date=July 24, 2016 |title=On the Couch with Sterlo |medium=Documentary |location=Sydney |publisher=Fox Sports}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1988 World Cup Final against New Zealand, Lamb was named as a substitute. He was called into action in the first half after [[Wally Lewis]] broke his arm in a tackle.\n\n==Captain of the Bulldogs==\nOne of the first jobs that new coach [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Chris Anderson]] did was appoint Lamb as captain ahead of [[Paul Langmack]] and [[Andrew Farrar]], who were commonly the deputies when [[Peter Tunks]] (who joined [[Penrith Panthers]] in 1990) was unavailable.\n\nThe Bulldogs lost Paul Langmack, Andrew Farrar, [[David Gillespie]] and [[Joe Thomas (rugby league)|Joe Thomas]] to [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] under former dual premiership-winning coach [[Warren Ryan]]. The club also lost [[Paul Dunn (rugby league)|Paul Dunn]] to [[Penrith Panthers|Penrith]] and Jason Alchin to [[St. George Dragons|St George]].\n\nLamb made himself unavailable for the [[1990 Kangaroo Tour]] despite the controversial omission of [[Wally Lewis]]. Cliff Lyons and Kevin Walters were both selected once Lamb confirmed his unavailability. {{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nA chronic groin injury would dog Lamb for the next few seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=9468 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405153005/http://www.leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=9468 |archivedate=5 April 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lamb would be a week-to-week proposition throughout the 1990s.\n\nDespite the departures from Canterbury at the end of the season, in 1991 they qualified in equal 5th position but went down 19-14 against arch-rivals [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]]. The club under the leadership of Lamb developed as a competitive force. Lamb  was captain to a new generation of players coming through the club who would play a big part in the club's successful years ahead including [[Darren Smith (rugby league)|Darren Smith]], [[Dean Pay]], Simon Gillies, Matthew Ryan and 1991 Rothmans Medal Winner [[Ewan McGrady]]. The 1991 season was the only time Lamb would be suspended throughout his career when he was sent off for an alleged headbutt on [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly's]] [[Geoff Toovey]]. He received four weeks for the offence. {{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nLamb missed the first five matches in 1992 but when he returned he enjoyed one of his finest individual seasons where Canterbury started to be tagged a 'one-man team'. {{citation needed|date=December 2017}} Lamb lifted the Bulldogs to the brink of the semi-finals before once again making himself unavailable as the 1992 World Cup loomed. Lamb came 2nd in the Dally M Awards for 1992.\n\nA new wave of signings joined the Bulldogs in 1993 and the team that Lamb and [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Anderson]] moulded was coming to fruition. The Bulldogs won the Minor Premiership with Lamb making it a hat-trick of Dally M Five-Eighth of the Year awards and Anderson winning Dally M Coach of the Year. Canterbury crashed out in the semi-finals but it was a great effort by the club to get to a position of strength after being warm favourites for the 1991 Wooden Spoon.\n\nLamb broke his arm in 1994 when playing his 299th first grade match against [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]]. Lamb would return to play his 300th match against [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|Souths]] playing at Concord Oval and wearing the No.55 jumper. Concord was only used for three League games and Lamb wore No.55 as he was a late inclusion into the side. Lamb broke the record previously held by [[Geoff Gerard]] in the final round, which ironically was against his former club [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] at Campbelltown with both [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]] and [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] jointly celebrating the occasion. Canterbury with their victory in Lamb's 304th first grade game won the Minor Premiership and defeated [[Canberra Raiders|Canberra]] in the Major Semi-Final. The Raiders however won the Grand Final 36-12.\n\n==1995 Grand Final==\nThe 1995 season was to be Lamb's last season and the Bulldogs were keen to send him out a winner but it all went wrong early when the Bulldogs were caught up in the firing line of the [[Super League War]]. Lamb's strength and character as a captain shone through when he held the club together and rallied everyone (bar one) in the latter half of the season. Canterbury qualified in 6th position for the [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]] Finals Series. The Bulldogs defeated [[St. George Dragons|St George]], [[Brisbane Broncos|Brisbane]] and defending premiers [[Canberra Raiders|Canberra]] to make the Grand Final against [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly]].\n\nCanterbury were never headed in the Grand Final defeating [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly]] 17-4 in the decider with Lamb plotting a crucial drop-goal to give them a seven-point lead. Lamb spent 10 minutes in the sin bin {{citation needed|date=August 2017}} but that didn't stop his performance as he steered Canterbury to an impressive victory.\n\nIt was a sweet moment for Lamb and coach [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Chris Anderson]] after five years of planning went into this moment. The 1995 Grand Final was also the swansong for Chief Executive [[Peter Bullfrog Moore|Peter Moore]] who retired from his post after 26 years of service. Moore would remain a member of the [[Canterbury Leagues Club]] board until 1998.\n\nLamb's planned retirement was shelved as he helped his beloved club for one more season to get through a sudden player departure caused by the [[Super League War]]. Lamb didn't seek the captaincy with Simon Gillies taking on that role and when Gillies was injured for the second half of the season, Lamb again opted not to be captain with [[Darren Britt]] taking the reins (in a sign of things to come). Lamb's career wound down on 25 August 1996, when Canterbury defeated [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] 50-22 at [[Belmore Sports Ground]]. Lamb scored two tries an that the start and end of his career saw him score a double.\n\nThe finest support player the game has seen played a record 350 first grade games (88 at [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Western Suburbs]], 262 at [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury-Bankstown]]). He also scored 164 first grade tries, a mark bettered only by [[Andrew Ettingshausen]] (165), [[Steve Menzies]] (180) and [[Ken Irvine]] (212).\n\nIn a strange twist, with [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly]] having reached (and won) the 2008 [[NRL Grand Final]], Menzies ended his career in Australia having equalled Lamb's league record of 349 games in his last match. The 34-year-old veteran of 15 NRL seasons then signed a contract to play the 2009 season and beyond with [[Super League]] club, the [[Bradford Bulls]].\n\nIn anticipation of equalling Lamb's record with his final appearance, Manly was reported to have made Menzies an offer to make a cameo appearance in 2009 to break the record. Menzies' response confirmed his and Lamb's standing among the greats:\n\n\"I wouldn't consider coming back for one game and cheapening the record or anything,\" said Menzies.\n\n\"If I fell one short or equalled it or whatever then that's my career and the way it finishes.\n\n\"(Lamb) was such a great player ... I'm very honoured to stand next to him.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.smh.com.au/sport/beaver-happy-to-leave-tied-with-lamb-20080929-4qbc.html| work=The Sydney Morning Herald| first1=Todd| last1=Balym| first2=Cameron| last2=Tomarchio| title=Beaver happy to leave tied with Lamb| date=29 September 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522042819/http://news.smh.com.au/sport/beaver-happy-to-leave-tied-with-lamb-20080929-4qbc.html| archivedate=22 May 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nLamb set many records at Canterbury with the last one, a landmark of 123 tries being broken by winger [[Hazem El Masri]], against the [[Newcastle Knights]] in 2006.\n\nLamb would be acknowledged in 2004 as the Canterbury {{rlp|fe}} and captain in their 70-years greatest side. {{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==349 or 350?==\nIn August 2011, [[Darren Lockyer]] played his 350th game and was awarded with breaking the record (349 games, jointly held by Lamb, according to the NRL) for most games played. However a website which compiles player and team statistics, [http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com RugbyLeagueProject] has checked the list of games played and found that while the numbers for Wests tally, it appears that Lamb played an additional game in 1986 in Round 1, where he came off the bench to play. Official records in those days were erratic regarding interchange players and it was this match that had been overlooked. After working with the NRL, [http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com RugbyLeagueProject] submitted all their evidence and the official record was changed to show that Lamb had indeed become the first player to reach 350 Premiership games.\n\n==Coaching career==\n{{Expand section|date=August 2017}}\n[[File:TERRY LAMB (former rugby league footballer and coach).jpg|thumb|right|Lamb in 2012]]\n\n==Achievements and Honours==\n*1983 Dally M Player of the Year (1st Runner Up in 1984, 1987, 1992. 2nd Runner Up in 1986)\n*1984 Rothmans Medal Best & Fairest Winner\n*Three times winner of the Dally M Players Player of the Year (1984, 1986, 1995)\n*Record seven times Dally M Five-Eighth of the Year Award (1983, 1984, 1986, 1987, 1991, 1992, 1993)\n*Won a record total of 18 Dally M Awards.\n*NSWRL Premiership Leading Tryscorer in 1984 (17) and 1987 (16)\n*NSWRL Premiership Leading Pointscorer in 1986 (210)\n*Member of 1984, 1988 and 1995 Canterbury Premiership Winning Teams\n*1995 Canterbury Premiership Winning Captain\n*Only player to play every match on a full [[Kangaroo Tour]]. Lamb played in all 20 matches: 15 tour matches and 5 Tests on the 1986 Tour of Great Britain and France.\n*Leading Tryscoring with 19 on [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia's]] 1986 [[Kangaroo Tour]]\n*Member of Australia's successful 1988 World Cup Final Squad\n*Played in [[New South Wales Rugby League|NSW's]] first State of Origin cleansweep in 1986\n*Scored two tries in his first Premiership match playing for [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] against [[Balmain Tigers|Balmain]] in 1980 and his last Premiership match playing for [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]] against [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] in 1996\n*Awarded keys to [[City of Canterbury, New South Wales]] in 1995 along with [[Peter Bullfrog Moore|Peter Moore]]\n*Awarded an [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) for services to [[rugby league]]\n*[[Australian Sports Medal]] recipient, 24 October 2000.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=972395&search_type=simple&showInd=true It's an Honour - Australia Celebrating Australians]</ref>\n*In February 2008, Lamb was named in the list of Australia's [[List of Australian rugby league's 100 greatest players|''100 Greatest Players'']] (1908&ndash;2007) which was commissioned by the [[National Rugby League|NRL]] and [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]] to celebrate the code's centenary year in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[National Rugby League|NRL]] & [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]]|title=Centenary of Rugby League - The Players|url=http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/the-players.aspx?cat=3&list=true|accessdate=2008-02-23|date=23 February 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20080226180521/http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/the-players.aspx?cat=3&list=true|archivedate=26 February 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Terry Lamb Complex]]\n*[[List of players who have played 300 NRL games]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://thebulldogs.com.au/sportal.php?page=player&id=477 Canterbury Bulldogs profile]\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/30years/audio/roy_hg_1988.mp3 Roy and HG remember the Hanley punch]\n*[http://www.stateoforigin.com.au/SOOgame/PlayerDetails.aspx?Pid=186 State of Origin Official website Rugby League Player Stats]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061113211411/http://www.eraofthebiff.com/p38a.html Terry Lamb at eraofthebiff.com]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n before = [[Wayne Pearce]]<br>2000|\n after = [[Tim Sheens]]<br>2003-2012|\n title = Coach<br>[[Wests Tigers]]|\n years = 2001-2002|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{1986 Kangaroo Tour squad}}\n{{Australia squad - 1985-88 World Cup champions}}\n{{Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs squad 1984 NSWRL premiership}}\n{{Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs squad 1988 NSWRL premiership}}\n{{Sydney Bulldogs squad 1995 ARL premiership}}\n{{Dally M Medallists}}\n{{Rothmans Medallists}}\n{{National Rugby League top try scorers}}\n{{National Rugby League top points scorers}}\n{{Rugby league footballers with 300 NRL games}}\n{{Rugby league footballers with 150 NRL tries}}\n{{Western Suburbs Magpies Team of the Eighties}}\n{{Wests Tigers Coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamb, Terry}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:New South Wales City Origin rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Western Suburbs Magpies players]]\n[[Category:Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs players]]\n[[Category:Australia national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Rugby League State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league coaches]]\n[[Category:Wests Tigers coaches]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby league halfbacks]]\n[[Category:Rugby league five-eighths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name            = Terry Lamb\n|fullname        = Terence John Lamb\n|image           = Terry Lamb.jpg\n|image_size      = \n|caption         = \n|position        = {{rlp|FE|HB}}\n|birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1961|9|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|height          = {{convert|166|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name = \"Bulldogs\" />\n|weight          = {{convert|80|kg|stlb|0|abbr=on}}<ref name = \"Bulldogs\" />\n|retired         = yes\n|club1           = [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Western Suburbs]]\n|year1start      = 1980\n|year1end        = 83\n|appearances1    = 88\n|tries1          = 41\n|goals1          = 11\n|fieldgoals1     = 7\n|points1         = 163\n|club2           = {{nowrap|[[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury Bulldogs]]}}\n|year2start      = 1984\n|year2end        = 96\n|appearances2    = 262\n|tries2          = 123\n|goals2          = 375\n|fieldgoals2     = 37\n|points2         = 1279\n|teamA           = [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n|yearAstart      = 1981\n|yearAend        = 89\n|appearancesA    = 8\n|triesA          = 0\n|goalsA          = 0\n|fieldgoalsA     = 0\n|pointsA         = 0\n|teamB           = [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia]]\n|yearBstart      = 1986\n|yearBend        =  \n|appearancesB    = 7\n|triesB          = 0\n|goalsB          = 0 \n|fieldgoalsB     = 0 \n|pointsB         = 0\n|coachteam1      = [[Wests Tigers]]\n|coachyear1start = 2001\n|coachyear1end   = 02\n|coachgames1     = 50\n|coachwins1      = 16\n|coachdraws1     = 0\n|coachlosses1    = 34\n|source          = <ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com/players/Terry-Lamb/summary.html Rugby League Project]</ref><ref>[http://www.yesterdayshero.com.au/PlayerProfile_Terry-Lamb_4717.aspx Yesterday's Hero] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005035248/http://www.yesterdayshero.com.au/PlayerProfile_Terry-Lamb_4717.aspx |date=5 October 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/coaches/terry-lamb/summary.html Rugby League Project Coaches]</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Terry Lamb''' [[Order of Australia|OAM]], (born 15 September 1961), also known by the [[nickname]] of '''\"Baa\"''', <ref>[http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/beaver-raises-the-baa/story-e6frep9o-1111117663838 \"Beaver raises the Baa\"] By David Riccio ''[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph]]'' 5 October 2008</ref> is an Australian former [[rugby league]] footballer and coach. He played 350 games, with the [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] (1980\u20131983) and [[Bulldogs Rugby League Football Club|Canterbury]] (1984\u20131996). Lamb was known for his support of the ball-carrier - his ability to be in the right place at the right time netted him 164 [[Try (rugby)|tries]]. This earned him the moniker of \"The Back-up Man\". He also kicked 386 [[Goal (sport)#Rugby football|goal]]s and 44 [[drop goal|field goal]]s, for 1,442 points in first grade. He played for [[New South Wales]] in [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]]. Lamb holds the distinction of being the only player to appear in every match of a [[Kangaroo Tour]].\n\n==Junior career==\nLamb grew up in [[Chester Hill, New South Wales|Chester Hill]], a suburb in the [[City of Bankstown|Bankstown]] area and attended [[Sefton High School]]. Lamb played all his junior rugby league for the Chester Hill Hornets club during the years 1967&ndash;1979 where he won multiple Best and Fairest awards. {{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} He only played in one Grand Final when he filled in for a side above his age group. Lamb is the only International to come from the Chester Hill Hornets club and the ground is now named the [[Terry Lamb Complex]] in his honour. Lamb represented Canterbury in junior representative sides, but signed his first professional contract with [[Western Suburbs Magpies]].\n\n==Western Suburbs Magpies career==\nLamb was a non-playing reserve for the [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]] Third Grade side in 1979 and was hopeful of a contract with his junior side in 1980. Lamb was told the best he could hope for was a position in the Presidents Cup (Under 21s) side. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nOn 18 May [[1980 NSWRFL season|1980]], Lamb made his first grade premiership debut for [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Western Suburbs]] against [[Balmain Tigers]] at [[Lidcombe Oval]]. Lamb scored two tries in the Magpies' comprehensive 26-4<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/games/1980/198005180324.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007193818/http://www.stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/games/1980/198005180324.html |archivedate=7 October 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> victory. Lamb scored 9 tries in his debut season and was edged out for the inaugural Dally M Rookie of the Year award by teammate [[Jim Leis]] who would go on the Australian 1980 Tour of New Zealand. Lamb formed a great scrumbase combination that season with [[Alan Neil]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nLamb's form in the early stages of the [[1981 NSWRFL season|1981 season]] was outstanding and he was selected in the [[New South Wales state rugby league team|NSW State of Origin side]]. Lamb was called in at the last moment for a very ill [[Mick Pattison]] {{citation needed|date=March 2017}} and only arrived in [[Brisbane]] on the day of the match (when Pattison took ill, NSW coach [[Ted Glossop]] initially wanted to move [[Steve Rogers (rugby league)|Steve Rogers]] from the centres to five-eighth and play whoever the league gave him as a replacement back from the bench but was overruled by the [[NSWRL]]. Lamb, who at the time worked as a linesman for [[Telstra|Telecom]], was literally found up a telegraph pole and had to make a rushed flight to Brisbane). {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Lamb met his halves partner, young [[Parramatta Eels|Parramatta]] halfback [[Peter Sterling (rugby league commentator)|Peter Sterling]], for the first time only two hours before kickoff. Lamb made his Origin debut at [[Lang Park]] playing opposite another young player on the rise, [[Queensland Maroons|Queensland]] captain [[Wally Lewis]] who had made his test debut against [[France national rugby league team|France]] only a few weeks earlier. NSW led 15-5 at half time mostly due to the Parramatta connection of Sterling, [[Ray Price (rugby)|Ray Price]], [[Michael Cronin (rugby league)|Michael Cronin]] and [[Eric Grothe Sr.|Eric Grothe]] who picked up a loose [[Greg Conescu]] pass to race 90 metres to score in the first half. But the Maroons, led by Lewis and man of the match [[Chris Close]], came back strong in the second half to win 22-15.\n\nThe [[1982 NSWRFL season|1982 season]] was a successful one for Wests and Lamb where his end of season form caught the eyes of the [[Australian Rugby League|Australian]] selectors and he was selected for the [[1982 Kangaroo tour]]. Lamb ruled himself out of the tour as he already planned to marry his partner Kim. [[Australian Kangaroos|The Kangaroos]] swept all before them on the tour going through undefeated for the first time and becoming known as \"[[The Invincibles (rugby league)|The Invincibles]]\".\n\nLamb's final season with Wests was in [[1983 NSWRFL season|1983]] where the Magpies won the dreaded [[Australian rugby league wooden spooners|wooden spoon]] prize. In spite of this, he was awarded the [[Dally M Player of the Year Award]]. His prize winnings of $9,000 that night was $500 more than his contract that season. {{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nTerry Lamb made 88 appearances for Wests, Lamb was later named as halfback in the Western Suburbs Magpies Team of the Eighties.<ref>{{cite web|title=VEST, KEATO, COGGER ALL HONOURED|url=http://www.weststigers.com.au/default.aspx?s=article-display&id=30925&title=vest,-keato,-cogger-all-honoured|accessdate=30 September 2010|website=weststigers.com.au|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227200942/http://www.weststigers.com.au/default.aspx?s=article-display&id=30925&title=vest%2C-keato%2C-cogger-all-honoured|archivedate=27 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Joining the Bulldogs and early success==\nThe news that Lamb's Dally M winnings was more than his contract ensured that he would be in hot demand from the richer Sydney clubs now that he was out of contract and that [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] were at first expelled from the premiership. [[Sydney Roosters|Easts]] and [[Balmain Tigers|Balmain]] both showed interest but eventually Lamb chose the Bulldogs, joining in 1984.<ref name = \"Bulldogs\" >[http://thebulldogs.com.au/sportal.php?page=player&id=477 Bulldogs.com.au - Terry Lamb]</ref>\n\nLamb settled nicely into Canterbury under the coaching of [[Warren Ryan]] and playing outside [[Steve Mortimer]]. Lamb's arrival did cause initial controversy when long-serving five-eighth [[Garry Hughes]] was dropped to reserve grade in what was to be his final season. Lamb's ability to back up the ball-carrier came to the fore as he was the Sydney Premiership's joint leading tryscorer with 17.<ref>http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/NSWRL_1984/summary.html</ref> Lamb won a recall to the [[New South Wales Rugby League|New South Wales]] [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] side for the 2nd match. He played well enough to be retained for the 3rd match despite the Blues losing, but withdrew due to injury. Lamb never won a junior premiership and he was closing in on one at senior level when the Bulldogs made the 1984 Grand Final against arch-rivals [[Parramatta Eels]] who were looking to win their fourth successive title. Canterbury took out the Grand Final 6\u20134 in a bruising game of football. Lamb was replaced with five minutes remaining due to a nasty gash above his eye.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/league_of_legends/100_years_of_the_game/slideshow_11_4.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201112051/http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/league_of_legends/100_years_of_the_game/slideshow_11_4.html |archivedate=1 December 2008 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Lamb played 22 games for the Bulldogs, but was forced to miss the 1985 Grand Final due to a groin injury. [[Michael Hagan]] was named as his replacement.<ref>http://thebulldogs.com.au/sportal.php?page=player&id=477</ref> Canterbury defeated [[St. George Dragons]] 7\u20136 to make it back-to-back titles.\n\n1986 was an eventful year for Lamb. He played much of the opening rounds at halfback with captain [[Steve Mortimer]] suspended, and was recalled to the [[New South Wales Rugby League|New South Wales]] [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] side. He was selected in all three matches from the bench and went on to be selected in the [[Australian national rugby league team|Australian]] Test side for the opening match against New Zealand. Lamb came on from the bench as a replacement for [[Dale Shearer]]. Lamb got more time in the 3rd Test when he came as a replacement for the injured [[Wayne Pearce]] playing lock forward. His good form at Canterbury continued with the Bulldogs making a third successive Grand Final, once again playing [[Parramatta Eels]]. Lamb was the leading pointscorer for the season, and he would end up scoring 210 points.<ref>http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/NSWRL_1986/summary.html</ref> However, he missed a difficult penalty goal attempt in the final three minutes of the 1986 Grand Final. The Eels won 4-2. Lamb was then selected to go on the [[Kangaroo Tour]].\n\nIn March 1987, Lamb scored all of Canterbury's 26 points as they beat Wests 26-16 in round 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/players/T/Terry_Lamb.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204013207/http://stats.rleague.com/rl/scorers/players/T/Terry_Lamb.html |archivedate=4 February 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lamb's points haul were made up of four tries and five goals. He again finished the season as the leagues leading try-scorer<ref>http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/NSWRL_1987/summary.html</ref> however, the club failed to make the finals, finishing 6th in what would prove to be Warren Ryan's last season as coach.\n\n[[Warren Ryan]] departed Canterbury at the end of 1987 with reserve grade coach [[Phil Gould]] taking over the reins in a caretaker role with [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Chris Anderson]] being groomed for the top position.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bulldogs.rleague.com/reviews/1988review.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425015122/http://bulldogs.rleague.com/reviews/1988review.php |archivedate=25 April 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 1988 season was Lamb's fifth at Canterbury and the first he wouldn't cross the line at least 10 times. Lamb played a very important role in Canterbury's season as former captain [[Steve Mortimer]] missed a large chunk of the season due to injuries. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n==Hanley incident and the World Cup==\nCanterbury played the 1988 Grand Final against [[Balmain Tigers|Balmain]], a game which the Bulldogs won 24-12. As well as scoring a try, Terry Lamb was involved in a first-half tackle, along with [[Andrew Farrar]], which resulted in the concussion of influential Balmain star, [[Ellery Hanley]]. Hanley was sent to the head bin, and although he managed to return to the field before half-time, he did not appear fully aware of his surroundings, and was replaced at half-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/south-west/nrl-grand-final-top-5-grand-final-moments-for-canterbury-bulldogs/news-story/2c7fb1748fad22e5b177c4dc92a0daaa |title=NRL grand final: Top 5 grand final moments for Canterbury Bulldogs |last=Murray |first=Oliver |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=30 September 2014 |access-date=9 June 2019}}</ref> Lamb says that there was no malice, and Hanley was not deliberately targeted.<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Peter Sterling (Presenter) |date=July 24, 2016 |title=On the Couch with Sterlo |medium=Documentary |location=Sydney |publisher=Fox Sports}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1988 World Cup Final against New Zealand, Lamb was named as a substitute. He was called into action in the first half after [[Wally Lewis]] broke his arm in a tackle.\n\n==Captain of the Bulldogs==\nOne of the first jobs that new coach [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Chris Anderson]] did was appoint Lamb as captain ahead of [[Paul Langmack]] and [[Andrew Farrar]], who were commonly the deputies when [[Peter Tunks]] (who joined [[Penrith Panthers]] in 1990) was unavailable.\n\nThe Bulldogs lost Paul Langmack, Andrew Farrar, [[David Gillespie]] and [[Joe Thomas (rugby league)|Joe Thomas]] to [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] under former dual premiership-winning coach [[Warren Ryan]]. The club also lost [[Paul Dunn (rugby league)|Paul Dunn]] to [[Penrith Panthers|Penrith]] and Jason Alchin to [[St. George Dragons|St George]].\n\nLamb made himself unavailable for the [[1990 Kangaroo Tour]] despite the controversial omission of [[Wally Lewis]]. Cliff Lyons and Kevin Walters were both selected once Lamb confirmed his unavailability. {{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nA chronic groin injury would dog Lamb for the next few seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=9468 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405153005/http://www.leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=9468 |archivedate=5 April 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lamb would be a week-to-week proposition throughout the 1990s.\n\nDespite the departures from Canterbury at the end of the season, in 1991 they qualified in equal 5th position but went down 19-14 against arch-rivals [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]]. The club under the leadership of Lamb developed as a competitive force. Lamb  was captain to a new generation of players coming through the club who would play a big part in the club's successful years ahead including [[Darren Smith (rugby league)|Darren Smith]], [[Dean Pay]], Simon Gillies, Matthew Ryan and 1991 Rothmans Medal Winner [[Ewan McGrady]]. The 1991 season was the only time Lamb would be suspended throughout his career when he was sent off for an alleged headbutt on [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly's]] [[Geoff Toovey]]. He received four weeks for the offence. {{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nLamb missed the first five matches in 1992 but when he returned he enjoyed one of his finest individual seasons where Canterbury started to be tagged a 'one-man team'. {{citation needed|date=December 2017}} Lamb lifted the Bulldogs to the brink of the semi-finals before once again making himself unavailable as the 1992 World Cup loomed. Lamb came 2nd in the Dally M Awards for 1992.\n\nA new wave of signings joined the Bulldogs in 1993 and the team that Lamb and [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Anderson]] moulded was coming to fruition. The Bulldogs won the Minor Premiership with Lamb making it a hat-trick of Dally M Five-Eighth of the Year awards and Anderson winning Dally M Coach of the Year. Canterbury crashed out in the semi-finals but it was a great effort by the club to get to a position of strength after being warm favourites for the 1991 Wooden Spoon.\n\nLamb broke his arm in 1994 when playing his 299th first grade match against [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]]. Lamb would return to play his 300th match against [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|Souths]] playing at Concord Oval and wearing the No.55 jumper. Concord was only used for three League games and Lamb wore No.55 as he was a late inclusion into the side. Lamb broke the record previously held by [[Geoff Gerard]] in the final round, which ironically was against his former club [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] at Campbelltown with both [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]] and [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] jointly celebrating the occasion. Canterbury with their victory in Lamb's 304th first grade game won the Minor Premiership and defeated [[Canberra Raiders|Canberra]] in the Major Semi-Final. The Raiders however won the Grand Final 36-12.\n\n==1995 Grand Final==\nThe 1995 season was to be Lamb's last season and the Bulldogs were keen to send him out a winner but it all went wrong early when the Bulldogs were caught up in the firing line of the [[Super League War]]. Lamb's strength and character as a captain shone through when he held the club together and rallied everyone (bar one) in the latter half of the season. Canterbury qualified in 6th position for the [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]] Finals Series. The Bulldogs defeated [[St. George Dragons|St George]], [[Brisbane Broncos|Brisbane]] and defending premiers [[Canberra Raiders|Canberra]] to make the Grand Final against [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly]].\n\nCanterbury were never headed in the Grand Final defeating [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly]] 17-4 in the decider with Lamb plotting a crucial drop-goal to give them a seven-point lead. Lamb spent 10 minutes in the sin bin {{citation needed|date=August 2017}} but that didn't stop his performance as he steered Canterbury to an impressive victory.\n\nIt was a sweet moment for Lamb and coach [[Chris Anderson (rugby league)|Chris Anderson]] after five years of planning went into this moment. The 1995 Grand Final was also the swansong for Chief Executive [[Peter Bullfrog Moore|Peter Moore]] who retired from his post after 26 years of service. Moore would remain a member of the [[Canterbury Leagues Club]] board until 1998.\n\nLamb's planned retirement was shelved as he helped his beloved club for one more season to get through a sudden player departure caused by the [[Super League War]]. Lamb didn't seek the captaincy with Simon Gillies taking on that role and when Gillies was injured for the second half of the season, Lamb again opted not to be captain with [[Darren Britt]] taking the reins (in a sign of things to come). Lamb's career wound down on 25 August 1996, when Canterbury defeated [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] 50-22 at [[Belmore Sports Ground]]. Lamb scored two tries an that the start and end of his career saw him score a double.\n\nThe finest support player the game has seen played a record 350 first grade games (88 at [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Western Suburbs]], 262 at [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury-Bankstown]]). He also scored 164 first grade tries, a mark bettered only by [[Andrew Ettingshausen]] (165), [[Steve Menzies]] (180) and [[Ken Irvine]] (212).\n\nIn a strange twist, with [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly]] having reached (and won) the 2008 [[NRL Grand Final]], Menzies ended his career in Australia having equalled Lamb's league record of 349 games in his last match. The 34-year-old veteran of 15 NRL seasons then signed a contract to play the 2009 season and beyond with [[Super League]] club, the [[Bradford Bulls]].\n\nIn anticipation of equalling Lamb's record with his final appearance, Manly was reported to have made Menzies an offer to make a cameo appearance in 2009 to break the record. Menzies' response confirmed his and Lamb's standing among the greats:\n\n\"I wouldn't consider coming back for one game and cheapening the record or anything,\" said Menzies.\n\n\"If I fell one short or equalled it or whatever then that's my career and the way it finishes.\n\n\"(Lamb) was such a great player ... I'm very honoured to stand next to him.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.smh.com.au/sport/beaver-happy-to-leave-tied-with-lamb-20080929-4qbc.html| work=The Sydney Morning Herald| first1=Todd| last1=Balym| first2=Cameron| last2=Tomarchio| title=Beaver happy to leave tied with Lamb| date=29 September 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522042819/http://news.smh.com.au/sport/beaver-happy-to-leave-tied-with-lamb-20080929-4qbc.html| archivedate=22 May 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nLamb set many records at Canterbury with the last one, a landmark of 123 tries being broken by winger [[Hazem El Masri]], against the [[Newcastle Knights]] in 2006.\n\nLamb would be acknowledged in 2004 as the Canterbury {{rlp|fe}} and captain in their 70-years greatest side. {{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==349 or 350?==\nIn August 2011, [[Darren Lockyer]] played his 350th game and was awarded with breaking the record (349 games, jointly held by Lamb, according to the NRL) for most games played. However a website which compiles player and team statistics, [http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com RugbyLeagueProject] has checked the list of games played and found that while the numbers for Wests tally, it appears that Lamb played an additional game in 1986 in Round 1, where he came off the bench to play. Official records in those days were erratic regarding interchange players and it was this match that had been overlooked. After working with the NRL, [http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com RugbyLeagueProject] submitted all their evidence and the official record was changed to show that Lamb had indeed become the first player to reach 350 Premiership games.\n\n==Coaching career==\n{{Expand section|date=August 2017}}\n[[File:TERRY LAMB (former rugby league footballer and coach).jpg|thumb|right|Lamb in 2012]]\n\n==Achievements and Honours==\n*1983 Dally M Player of the Year (1st Runner Up in 1984, 1987, 1992. 2nd Runner Up in 1986)\n*1984 Rothmans Medal Best & Fairest Winner\n*Three times winner of the Dally M Players Player of the Year (1984, 1986, 1995)\n*Record seven times Dally M Five-Eighth of the Year Award (1983, 1984, 1986, 1987, 1991, 1992, 1993)\n*Won a record total of 18 Dally M Awards.\n*NSWRL Premiership Leading Tryscorer in 1984 (17) and 1987 (16)\n*NSWRL Premiership Leading Pointscorer in 1986 (210)\n*Member of 1984, 1988 and 1995 Canterbury Premiership Winning Teams\n*1995 Canterbury Premiership Winning Captain\n*Only player to play every match on a full [[Kangaroo Tour]]. Lamb played in all 20 matches: 15 tour matches and 5 Tests on the 1986 Tour of Great Britain and France.\n*Leading Tryscoring with 19 on [[Australian national rugby league team|Australia's]] 1986 [[Kangaroo Tour]]\n*Member of Australia's successful 1988 World Cup Final Squad\n*Played in [[New South Wales Rugby League|NSW's]] first State of Origin cleansweep in 1986\n*Scored two tries in his first Premiership match playing for [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests]] against [[Balmain Tigers|Balmain]] in 1980 and his last Premiership match playing for [[Canterbury Bulldogs|Canterbury]] against [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] in 1996\n*Awarded keys to [[City of Canterbury, New South Wales]] in 1995 along with [[Peter Bullfrog Moore|Peter Moore]]\n*Awarded an [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) for services to [[rugby league]]\n*[[Australian Sports Medal]] recipient, 24 October 2000.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=972395&search_type=simple&showInd=true It's an Honour - Australia Celebrating Australians]</ref>\n*In February 2008, Lamb was named in the list of Australia's [[List of Australian rugby league's 100 greatest players|''100 Greatest Players'']] (1908&ndash;2007) which was commissioned by the [[National Rugby League|NRL]] and [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]] to celebrate the code's centenary year in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[National Rugby League|NRL]] & [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]]|title=Centenary of Rugby League - The Players|url=http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/the-players.aspx?cat=3&list=true|accessdate=2008-02-23|date=23 February 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20080226180521/http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/the-players.aspx?cat=3&list=true|archivedate=26 February 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Terry Lamb Complex]]\n*[[List of players who have played 300 NRL games]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://thebulldogs.com.au/sportal.php?page=player&id=477 Canterbury Bulldogs profile]\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/30years/audio/roy_hg_1988.mp3 Roy and HG remember the Hanley punch]\n*[http://www.stateoforigin.com.au/SOOgame/PlayerDetails.aspx?Pid=186 State of Origin Official website Rugby League Player Stats]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061113211411/http://www.eraofthebiff.com/p38a.html Terry Lamb at eraofthebiff.com]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n before = [[Wayne Pearce]]<br>2000|\n after = [[Tim Sheens]]<br>2003-2012|\n title = Coach<br>[[Wests Tigers]]|\n years = 2001-2002|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{1986 Kangaroo Tour squad}}\n{{Australia squad - 1985-88 World Cup champions}}\n{{Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs squad 1984 NSWRL premiership}}\n{{Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs squad 1988 NSWRL premiership}}\n{{Sydney Bulldogs squad 1995 ARL premiership}}\n{{Dally M Medallists}}\n{{Rothmans Medallists}}\n{{National Rugby League top try scorers}}\n{{National Rugby League top points scorers}}\n{{Rugby league footballers with 300 NRL games}}\n{{Rugby league footballers with 150 NRL tries}}\n{{Western Suburbs Magpies Team of the Eighties}}\n{{Wests Tigers Coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamb, Terry}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:New South Wales City Origin rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Western Suburbs Magpies players]]\n[[Category:Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs players]]\n[[Category:Australia national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Rugby League State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league coaches]]\n[[Category:Wests Tigers coaches]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby league halfbacks]]\n[[Category:Rugby league five-eighths]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toPhilip Gould (disambiguation)(link changed toPhil Gould (rugby league)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terry_Lamb"}
{"title_page": "Dene Halatau", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Dene Halatau\n|fullname       = Dene La Halatau\n|nickname       = \n|image = DENE HALATAU (11915694236).jpg\n|caption        = <small>Halatau in 2014</small> \n|position       = {{rlp|SR|LK|HK|CE}}\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|1|27}}\n|birth_place   = [[Invercargill, New Zealand]]\n|height         = {{convert|178|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|95|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|retired = no\n|club1          = [[Wests Tigers]]\n|year1start     = 2003\n|year1end       = 09 \n|appearances1   = 128\n|tries1         = 17 \n|goals1         = 0 \n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 68\n|club2          = [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury Bulldogs]]\n|year2start     = 2010\n|year2end       = 13\n|appearances2   = 69\n|tries2         = 4\n|goals2         = 0 \n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 16\n|club3          = [[Wests Tigers]]\n|year3start     = 2014\n|year3end       = 16\n|appearances3   = 52\n|tries3         = 4\n|goals3         = 0 \n|fieldgoals3    = 0\n|points3        = 16\n|teamA          = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearAstart     = 2004\n|yearAend       = 09 \n|appearancesA   = 15\n|triesA         = 0 \n|goalsA         = 0 \n|fieldgoalsA    = 0 \n|pointsA        = 0\n|updated        = 1 August 2015\n|source         =<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/dene-halatau/summary.html|title=Dene Halatau \u2013 Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Dene Halatau''' (born 27 January 1983) is a New Zealand former professional [[rugby league]] footballer who previously played for the [[Wests Tigers]] and the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]] of the [[National Rugby League]]. Halatau was part of the Wests Tigers team that won the [[2005 NRL Premiership]]. Halatau is [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand national]] representative who was part of their [[2008 Rugby League World Cup]] winning squad.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Invercargill, New Zealand]], Halatau moved to Australia as a 4-year-old and played his junior rugby league for the Merrylands Rams and North Ryde Hawks before being signed by the Wests Tigers. Halatau was educated at [[Westfields Sports High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://westfieldsports.nsw.edu.au/PAGES/hnrspg2.html|title=Westfields Sports High School, Australia's First Sports High School|publisher=Westfieldsports.nsw.edu.au|date=16 July 2002|accessdate=9 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125014953/http://westfieldsports.nsw.edu.au/PAGES/hnrspg2.html|archivedate=25 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He is of Niuean descent.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=5905| work=League Unlimited| title=Anderson expects a lot from his players| date=10 November 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225121608/http://leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=5905|archive-date=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===2003===\nIn Round 13 of the [[2003 NRL season]], Halatau made his [[NRL]] debut for the [[Wests Tigers]] against the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] at [[Leichhardt Oval]] off the interchange bench in the Tigers 38\u201330 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2003-06-08/sea-eagles-edge-tigers/1867068|title=Sea Eagles edge Tigers|publisher=abc.net.au|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> In Halatau's third match in Round 18 against the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]] at Leichhardt Oval, he scored his first and second tries in the 44\u201312 win.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Mascord|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/07/13/1058034882776.html|title=Tigers find something to play for as Sharks sink to new low|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 July 2003|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> He finished his debut year in the NRL with him playing in 9 matches and scoring 3 tries.\n\n===2004===\nHalatau finished the [[2004 NRL season|year]] with 22 matches and 4 tries. In November, he was selected for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team]] making his test debut at {{rlp|hk}} against [[France national rugby league team|France]] in the 24\u201320 win at [[Stade d'Albert Domec]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/11/12/1100131165356.html?from=storylhs|title=Plucky French give Kiwis a scare \u2013 League|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=12 November 2004|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2005===\n[[File:Dene Halatau.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Halatau at the [[RLWC]] in 2008]]\nHalatau played off the interchange bench for New Zealand in the 2005 ANZAC Test at [[Suncorp Stadium]], as the Kiwis lost 32\u201316.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/League/Its-a-runaway-success/2005/04/22/1114152329006.html|title=It's a runaway success \u2013 League|author=Steve Mascord|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau said, \"I've grown up going to Australian schools and most of my friends are Aussies, but I've always held my New Zealand passport and I've never got Australian citizenship. I don't know why, but other than my immediate family, all of my other relatives live in New Zealand.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| title=Tiger cubs have bloodlines to be star Kiwis| author=Brad Walter| url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=dene+halatau&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH050413NE4T51VP6I4|accessdate=30 August 2016|date=13 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nLater in the season Halatau was moved from the interchange bench to {{rlp|lk}} forward for the finals campaign. Halatau was awarded the Man of the Match for his two try effort against [[St George Illawarra Dragons]] in the Preliminary Final 20\u201312 victory <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/league/dragons-dream-over-as-tigers-roll-on/2005/09/24/1126982272190.html|title=Dragons dream over as Tigers roll on|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=24 September 2005|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> and a week later in the [[2005 NRL Grand Final]], he played at lock in the Wests Tigers 30\u201316 win over the [[North Queensland Cowboys]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/league/fairytale-for-wests-tigers/2005/10/02/1128191609599.html|title=Fairytale for Wests Tigers|author=Greg Prichard|publisher=The Age|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau finished the [[2005 NRL season|year]] with 4 tries from 22 matches.\n\n===2006===\nPlaying in 14 NRL matches in [[2006 NRL season|2006]], Halatau also played 3 matches at hooker for New Zealand in the [[2006 Rugby League Tri-Nations|Tri-Nations]].\n\n===2007===\nHalatau was selected to play for New Zealand at hooker in the 2007 [[ANZAC Test]] in the Kiwis 30\u20136 loss at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Steven|url=http://leagueunlimited.com/news/australia-win-anzac-test-in-late-blitz|title=Australia win Anzac Test in late blitz|publisher=League Unlimited|date=20 April 2007|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau finished [[2007 NRL season|2007]] with one try from 21 matches. He also went on the [[2007 All Golds tour]], playing at hooker in all the 5 matches.\n[[File:Dene Halatau (26 October 2008).jpg|thumb|left|150px|Halatau playing for New Zealand at the 2008 RLWC.]]\n\n===2008===\nIn Round 15 against the [[Brisbane Broncos]] at Suncorp Stadium, Halatau played his 100th NRL career match and scored a try in the Tigers 19\u201318 loss.<ref>{{cite news| work= Fox Sports| title=Broncos hold off fighting Tigers| author= Wayne Heming| url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/broncos-hold-off-fighting-tigers/story-e6frf3pc-1111116694074|accessdate=23 April 2011|date=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau finished the [[2008 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 3 tries.\n\nHalatau was a member of the [[2008 Rugby League World Cup squads#New Zealand|New Zealand]] team which defeated Australia 34\u201320 in the [[2008 Rugby League World Cup|2008 World Cup]] Final at Suncorp Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Wilson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/nov/22/new-zealand-rugby-league-world-cup|title=Rugby league World Cup final: New Zealand end Australia invincibility with 34\u201320 win|publisher=The Guardian|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\nHalatau played in the 2009 ANZAC Test at Suncorp Stadium in the Kiwis 38\u201310 loss.<ref>{{cite news| work= Daily Telegraph| title=Australia beats New Zealand 38\u201310 in Anzac Test in Brisbane| first = Andrew| last = Webster| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/australia-beats-new-zealand-38-10-in-anzac-test-in-brisbane/story-e6freuy9-1225710449082|accessdate=9 May 2015|date=8 May 2009}}</ref> On 14 August, Halatau signed a 3-year deal with the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]] commencing in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/bulldogs-sign-west-tigers-forward-dene-halatau-to-a-three-year-contract/story-fn2mcuj6-1225761677340|title=Bulldogs sign West Tigers forward Dene Halatau to a three-year contract|publisher=Fox Sports|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| work=Courier Mail| title=Bulldogs sign Dene Halatau| url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/bulldogs-sign-halatau/story-e6frep5x-1225761610414|accessdate=9 May 2015|date=14 August 2009}}</ref> Halatau finished the [[2009 NRL season|season]] with him playing in 18 matches and scoring 2 tries.\n\n===2010===\nIn Round 3 against the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]], Halatau made his club debut for the Bulldogs in the smashing 60\u201314 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/canterbury-bulldogs-score-12-tries-in-60-14-victory-over-sydney-roosters/story-e6frexnr-1225846541888|title=Bulldogs Score 12 Tries in 60\u201314 Victory Over Roosters|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Halatau played in 8 matches for the Bulldogs in an injury interrupted [[2010 NRL season|season]].\n\n===2011===\n[[File:DENE HALATAU (5483493966).jpg|thumb|Halatau in 2012|170px]]\nIn Round 23 against the Sharks at [[Remondis Stadium]], Halatau scored his first try as a Bulldog before succumbing to a season ending ankle injury.<ref>{{cite news| work=Daily Telegraph| title=Canterbury Bulldogs beat Cronulla Sharks in NRL round 23| first =Christian| last = Nicolussi| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/live-coverage-bulldogs-v-sharks/story-e6frexnr-1226115402279|accessdate=23 April 2011|date=16 August 2011}}</ref> He finished the [[2011 NRL season|season]] with one try from 19 appearances.\n\n===2012===\nIn 2012, Halatau was playing second-row in the starting team. He injured his knee in round 19 and was unable to return to first grade.<ref>{{cite news|author=|work=Daily Telegraph|title= Canterbury Bulldogs backrower Dene Halatau ruled out for eight weeks with knee injury|url= http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/canterbury-bulldogs-backrower-dene-halatau-ruled-out-for-eight-weeks-with-knee-injury/story-e6frexnr-1226427923729|accessdate=23 September 2013|date=17 July 2012}}</ref> Halatau was named 18th man for the Bulldogs [[2012 NRL Grand Final]] team against the [[Melbourne Storm]] with the Bulldogs losing 14\u20134. He finished the [[2012 NRL season|season]] with him playing 17 matches and scoring a try.\n\n===2013===\nOn 28 July, it was announced that Halatau would be returning to his previous club [[Wests Tigers]] on a two-year contract from 2014. CEO Grant Meyer said, \"His experience and leadership as a senior player is going to be invaluable for some of our younger players. We have been very clear that we are investing very heavily in our juniors and a player like Dene will provide leadership and mentoring for the group.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=|work=ABC News|title=Dene Halatau snapped up as Wests Tigers add four players to 2014 roster|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-07-29/tigers-sign-halatau-on-two-year-deal/4850168|accessdate=23 September 2013|date=29 July 2013}}</ref> Halatau played exclusively from the interchange bench in 2013, but made appearances in all 25 of the Bulldogs matches and scored 2 tries.\n\n===2014===\nAfter breaking his left ankle in a pre-season trial, Halatau was ruled out for at least four months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nrl.com/halatau-injured-as-tigers-surprise-panthers/tabid/10874/newsid/76187/default.aspx|title=Halatau injured as Tigers surprise Panthers|publisher=nrl.com|date=8 February 2014|accessdate=9 May 2015|author=Matt Encarnacion}}</ref> He played his return match in Round 14 against the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] off the interchange bench in the Tigers 32\u201310 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jun/13/south-sydney-rabbitohs-west-tigers-nrl|title=South Sydney Rabbitohs 32\u201310 Wests Tigers|publisher=The Guardian|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> In Round 18 against the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] at [[Brookvale Oval]], Halatau played in his 200th NRL match in the Tigers 40\u20138 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroar.com.au/2014/07/12/foran-steers-manly-tigers-thrashing/|title=Foran steers Manly in Tigers thrashing|publisher=The Roar|date=12 July 2014|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> He finished his return year to the Tigers with him playing in 7 matches.\n\nWith the introduction of concussion rules to the NRL in 2014, Halatau saw his value as a utility rise. [[Peter Mulholland]] said, \"Every team is going to need someone on the bench who can play half a dozen positions. Dene Halatau is the perfect player- someone who can play 1, 7 or 9\"\n<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| title=An exercise in UTILITIES| author=Brad Walter| url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=dene+halatau&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH14031510ITO5AUQ97|accessdate=30 August 2016|date=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nBetter luck with injuries saw Halatau play in 22 matches and score 4 tries in the [[2015 NRL season]], equaling his best season tally for the Tigers since the 2005 season. Halatau made his debut as captain in Round 11 against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]] in the Tigers 8\u20130 loss at [[Campbelltown Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/north-queensland-cowboys-outlast-wests-tigers-with-points-at-a-premium-20150523-gh89ek.html|title=North Queensland Cowboys outlast Wests Tigers with points at a premium|website=Smh.com.au|date=27 January 2016|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> He captained the team a further 2 times while [[Robbie Farah]] and [[Aaron Woods]] were away on State of Origin duties, including a surprise 34\u20136 upset victory over the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] in Round 14.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Pengilly|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/jason-taylor-hails-hardnosed-wests-tigers-cubs-after-drubbing-south-sydney-20150612-ghn1eb.html|title=Jason Taylor hails hard-nosed Wests Tigers cubs after drubbing South Sydney|website=Smh.com.au|date=27 January 2016|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> In Round 19 against the [[Brisbane Broncos]], Halatau played his 150th club match for the Tigers in the 42\u201316 loss at Suncorp Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Zemek|url=http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-sport/halatau-to-savour-150th-for-tigers-in-nrl-20150714-3za03.html|title=Halatau to savour 150th for Tigers in NRL|website=Smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/ladder-leading-broncos-trounce-tigers/tabid/10874/newsid/88142/default.aspx|title=Ladder-leading Broncos trounce Tigers|website=NRL.com|date=19 July 2015|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> The Wests Tigers failed to win any of the games Halatau was absent for the season.\n\nAt season's end, Halatau signed with the Wests Tigers for a further season. Speaking of his career beyond 2016, Halatau said, \"I'm 32 now and I've played longer than I thought I would have played. I feel like I'm still offering a bit to the team. I\u2019m open ended next year, if they want to extend it another year. If they don\u2019t want to and there\u2019s nothing else out there, then I\u2019m prepared to step into life after football.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Daily Telegraph| title=Clubs want rejects, young star eyes extension, veteran\u2019s swan song \u2014 NRL Market Watch| author=Nathan Ryan| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/clubs-want-rejects-young-star-eyes-extension-veterans-swan-song-nrl-market-watch/story-fnp0lyn3-1227646244116|accessdate=16 December 2015|date=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nWith Robbie Farah injured, playing State of Origin, and then dropped to reserve grade, Halatau was the first choice as hooker for the majority of the season. On 18 July 2016, Halatau announced he would retire at the end of the year. He said, \"I was grateful to the club, [[Jason Taylor (rugby league)|JT]] and the coaching staff for giving me this year. While I'm still feeling okay I think it's the right time to hang the boots up.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| publisher = Fairfax| title=Dene Halatau announces NRL retirement| url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/dene-halatau-announces-nrl-retirement-20160717-gq7unc.html|accessdate=28 August 2016|date=18 July 2016}}</ref> [[Phil Gould (rugby league)|Phil Gould]] said, \"He has always been one of those quiet achievers in our game. A real team man, he has been admired by his peers. They value his toughness and his outstanding work ethic. His tremendous versatility has also been an asset.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| publisher = Fairfax| title=NRL class of 2016: Time to farewell a Wonderful Bunch| first = Phil| last = Gould| url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/nrl-class-of-2016-time-to-farewell-a-wonderful-bunch-20160827-gr2mt0.html|accessdate=28 August 2016|date=28 August 2016}}</ref> Halatau finished his last year in the NRL with him playing in 23 matches for the Tigers in the [[2016 NRL season]].\n\n==Post-playing career==\nHalatau was made an NRL ambassador in 2017.<ref>{{cite web| work= nrl.com | title=2017 NRL Ambassadors announced | url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2017/01/25/2017-nrl-ambassadors-announced/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dene Halatau}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160229073141/http://www.weststigers.com.au/team/profiles/dene_halatau.html 2016 Wests Tigers profile]\n\n{{Wests Tigers squad 2005 NRL premiership}}\n{{New Zealand 2004 Rugby League Tri Nations squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2006 Rugby League Tri Nations squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2008 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{Wests Tigers Life Members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halatau, Dean}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Niuean descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Niue national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Wests Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league second-rows]]\n[[Category:Rugby league locks]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Invercargill]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Dene Halatau\n|fullname       = Dene La Halatau\n|nickname       = \n|image = DENE HALATAU (11915694236).jpg\n|caption        = <small>Halatau in 2014</small> \n|position       = {{rlp|SR|LK|HK|CE}}\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|1|27}}\n|birth_place   = [[Invercargill, New Zealand]]\n|height         = {{convert|178|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|95|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|retired = no\n|club1          = [[Wests Tigers]]\n|year1start     = 2003\n|year1end       = 09 \n|appearances1   = 128\n|tries1         = 17 \n|goals1         = 0 \n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 68\n|club2          = [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury Bulldogs]]\n|year2start     = 2010\n|year2end       = 13\n|appearances2   = 69\n|tries2         = 4\n|goals2         = 0 \n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 16\n|club3          = [[Wests Tigers]]\n|year3start     = 2014\n|year3end       = 16\n|appearances3   = 52\n|tries3         = 4\n|goals3         = 0 \n|fieldgoals3    = 0\n|points3        = 16\n|teamA          = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearAstart     = 2004\n|yearAend       = 09 \n|appearancesA   = 15\n|triesA         = 0 \n|goalsA         = 0 \n|fieldgoalsA    = 0 \n|pointsA        = 0\n|updated        = 1 August 2015\n|source         =<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/dene-halatau/summary.html|title=Dene Halatau \u2013 Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Dene Halatau''' (born 27 January 1983) is a New Zealand former professional [[rugby league]] footballer who previously played for the [[Wests Tigers]] and the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]] of the [[National Rugby League]]. Halatau was part of the Wests Tigers team that won the [[2005 NRL Premiership]]. Halatau is [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand national]] representative who was part of their [[2008 Rugby League World Cup]] winning squad.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Invercargill, New Zealand]], Halatau moved to Australia as a 4-year-old and played his junior rugby league for the Merrylands Rams and North Ryde Hawks before being signed by the Wests Tigers. Halatau was educated at [[Westfields Sports High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://westfieldsports.nsw.edu.au/PAGES/hnrspg2.html|title=Westfields Sports High School, Australia's First Sports High School|publisher=Westfieldsports.nsw.edu.au|date=16 July 2002|accessdate=9 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125014953/http://westfieldsports.nsw.edu.au/PAGES/hnrspg2.html|archivedate=25 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He is of Niuean descent.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=5905| work=League Unlimited| title=Anderson expects a lot from his players| date=10 November 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225121608/http://leagueunlimited.com/article.php?newsid=5905|archive-date=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===2003===\nIn Round 13 of the [[2003 NRL season]], Halatau made his [[NRL]] debut for the [[Wests Tigers]] against the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] at [[Leichhardt Oval]] off the interchange bench in the Tigers 38\u201330 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2003-06-08/sea-eagles-edge-tigers/1867068|title=Sea Eagles edge Tigers|publisher=abc.net.au|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> In Halatau's third match in Round 18 against the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]] at Leichhardt Oval, he scored his first and second tries in the 44\u201312 win.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Mascord|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/07/13/1058034882776.html|title=Tigers find something to play for as Sharks sink to new low|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 July 2003|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> He finished his debut year in the NRL with him playing in 9 matches and scoring 3 tries.\n\n===2004===\nHalatau finished the [[2004 NRL season|year]] with 22 matches and 4 tries. In November, he was selected for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team]] making his test debut at {{rlp|hk}} against [[France national rugby league team|France]] in the 24\u201320 win at [[Stade d'Albert Domec]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/11/12/1100131165356.html?from=storylhs|title=Plucky French give Kiwis a scare \u2013 League|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=12 November 2004|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2005===\n[[File:Dene Halatau.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Halatau at the [[RLWC]] in 2008]]\nHalatau played off the interchange bench for New Zealand in the 2005 ANZAC Test at [[Suncorp Stadium]], as the Kiwis lost 32\u201316.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/League/Its-a-runaway-success/2005/04/22/1114152329006.html|title=It's a runaway success \u2013 League|author=Steve Mascord|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau said, \"I've grown up going to Australian schools and most of my friends are Aussies, but I've always held my New Zealand passport and I've never got Australian citizenship. I don't know why, but other than my immediate family, all of my other relatives live in New Zealand.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| title=Tiger cubs have bloodlines to be star Kiwis| author=Brad Walter| url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=dene+halatau&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH050413NE4T51VP6I4|accessdate=30 August 2016|date=13 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nLater in the season Halatau was moved from the interchange bench to {{rlp|lk}} forward for the finals campaign. Halatau was awarded the Man of the Match for his two try effort against [[St George Illawarra Dragons]] in the Preliminary Final 20\u201312 victory <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/league/dragons-dream-over-as-tigers-roll-on/2005/09/24/1126982272190.html|title=Dragons dream over as Tigers roll on|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=24 September 2005|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> and a week later in the [[2005 NRL Grand Final]], he played at lock in the Wests Tigers 30\u201316 win over the [[North Queensland Cowboys]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/league/fairytale-for-wests-tigers/2005/10/02/1128191609599.html|title=Fairytale for Wests Tigers|author=Greg Prichard|publisher=The Age|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau finished the [[2005 NRL season|year]] with 4 tries from 22 matches.\n\n===2006===\nPlaying in 14 NRL matches in [[2006 NRL season|2006]], Halatau also played 3 matches at hooker for New Zealand in the [[2006 Rugby League Tri-Nations|Tri-Nations]].\n\n===2007===\nHalatau was selected to play for New Zealand at hooker in the 2007 [[ANZAC Test]] in the Kiwis 30\u20136 loss at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Steven|url=http://leagueunlimited.com/news/australia-win-anzac-test-in-late-blitz|title=Australia win Anzac Test in late blitz|publisher=League Unlimited|date=20 April 2007|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau finished [[2007 NRL season|2007]] with one try from 21 matches. He also went on the [[2007 All Golds tour]], playing at hooker in all the 5 matches.\n[[File:Dene Halatau (26 October 2008).jpg|thumb|left|150px|Halatau playing for New Zealand at the 2008 RLWC.]]\n\n===2008===\nIn Round 15 against the [[Brisbane Broncos]] at Suncorp Stadium, Halatau played his 100th NRL career match and scored a try in the Tigers 19\u201318 loss.<ref>{{cite news| work= Fox Sports| title=Broncos hold off fighting Tigers| author= Wayne Heming| url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/broncos-hold-off-fighting-tigers/story-e6frf3pc-1111116694074|accessdate=23 April 2011|date=9 May 2015}}</ref> Halatau finished the [[2008 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 3 tries.\n\nHalatau was a member of the [[2008 Rugby League World Cup squads#New Zealand|New Zealand]] team which defeated Australia 34\u201320 in the [[2008 Rugby League World Cup|2008 World Cup]] Final at Suncorp Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Wilson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/nov/22/new-zealand-rugby-league-world-cup|title=Rugby league World Cup final: New Zealand end Australia invincibility with 34\u201320 win|publisher=The Guardian|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\nHalatau played in the 2009 ANZAC Test at Suncorp Stadium in the Kiwis 38\u201310 loss.<ref>{{cite news| work= Daily Telegraph| title=Australia beats New Zealand 38\u201310 in Anzac Test in Brisbane| first = Andrew| last = Webster| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/australia-beats-new-zealand-38-10-in-anzac-test-in-brisbane/story-e6freuy9-1225710449082|accessdate=9 May 2015|date=8 May 2009}}</ref> On 14 August, Halatau signed a 3-year deal with the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]] commencing in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/bulldogs-sign-west-tigers-forward-dene-halatau-to-a-three-year-contract/story-fn2mcuj6-1225761677340|title=Bulldogs sign West Tigers forward Dene Halatau to a three-year contract|publisher=Fox Sports|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| work=Courier Mail| title=Bulldogs sign Dene Halatau| url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/bulldogs-sign-halatau/story-e6frep5x-1225761610414|accessdate=9 May 2015|date=14 August 2009}}</ref> Halatau finished the [[2009 NRL season|season]] with him playing in 18 matches and scoring 2 tries.\n\n===2010===\nIn Round 3 against the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]], Halatau made his club debut for the Bulldogs in the smashing 60\u201314 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/canterbury-bulldogs-score-12-tries-in-60-14-victory-over-sydney-roosters/story-e6frexnr-1225846541888|title=Bulldogs Score 12 Tries in 60\u201314 Victory Over Roosters|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Halatau played in 8 matches for the Bulldogs in an injury interrupted [[2010 NRL season|season]].\n\n===2011===\n[[File:DENE HALATAU (5483493966).jpg|thumb|Halatau in 2012|170px]]\nIn Round 23 against the Sharks at [[Remondis Stadium]], Halatau scored his first try as a Bulldog before succumbing to a season ending ankle injury.<ref>{{cite news| work=Daily Telegraph| title=Canterbury Bulldogs beat Cronulla Sharks in NRL round 23| first =Christian| last = Nicolussi| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/live-coverage-bulldogs-v-sharks/story-e6frexnr-1226115402279|accessdate=23 April 2011|date=16 August 2011}}</ref> He finished the [[2011 NRL season|season]] with one try from 19 appearances.\n\n===2012===\nIn 2012, Halatau was playing second-row in the starting team. He injured his knee in round 19 and was unable to return to first grade.<ref>{{cite news|author=|work=Daily Telegraph|title= Canterbury Bulldogs backrower Dene Halatau ruled out for eight weeks with knee injury|url= http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/canterbury-bulldogs-backrower-dene-halatau-ruled-out-for-eight-weeks-with-knee-injury/story-e6frexnr-1226427923729|accessdate=23 September 2013|date=17 July 2012}}</ref> Halatau was named 18th man for the Bulldogs [[2012 NRL Grand Final]] team against the [[Melbourne Storm]] with the Bulldogs losing 14\u20134. He finished the [[2012 NRL season|season]] with him playing 17 matches and scoring a try.\n\n===2013===\nOn 28 July, it was announced that Halatau would be returning to his previous club [[Wests Tigers]] on a two-year contract from 2014. CEO Grant Meyer said, \"His experience and leadership as a senior player is going to be invaluable for some of our younger players. We have been very clear that we are investing very heavily in our juniors and a player like Dene will provide leadership and mentoring for the group.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=|work=ABC News|title=Dene Halatau snapped up as Wests Tigers add four players to 2014 roster|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-07-29/tigers-sign-halatau-on-two-year-deal/4850168|accessdate=23 September 2013|date=29 July 2013}}</ref> Halatau played exclusively from the interchange bench in 2013, but made appearances in all 25 of the Bulldogs matches and scored 2 tries.\n\n===2014===\nAfter breaking his left ankle in a pre-season trial, Halatau was ruled out for at least four months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nrl.com/halatau-injured-as-tigers-surprise-panthers/tabid/10874/newsid/76187/default.aspx|title=Halatau injured as Tigers surprise Panthers|publisher=nrl.com|date=8 February 2014|accessdate=9 May 2015|author=Matt Encarnacion}}</ref> He played his return match in Round 14 against the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] off the interchange bench in the Tigers 32\u201310 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jun/13/south-sydney-rabbitohs-west-tigers-nrl|title=South Sydney Rabbitohs 32\u201310 Wests Tigers|publisher=The Guardian|date=|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> In Round 18 against the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] at [[Brookvale Oval]], Halatau played in his 200th NRL match in the Tigers 40\u20138 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroar.com.au/2014/07/12/foran-steers-manly-tigers-thrashing/|title=Foran steers Manly in Tigers thrashing|publisher=The Roar|date=12 July 2014|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> He finished his return year to the Tigers with him playing in 7 matches.\n\nWith the introduction of concussion rules to the NRL in 2014, Halatau saw his value as a utility rise. [[Peter Mulholland]] said, \"Every team is going to need someone on the bench who can play half a dozen positions. Dene Halatau is the perfect player- someone who can play 1, 7 or 9\"\n<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| title=An exercise in UTILITIES| author=Brad Walter| url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=dene+halatau&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH14031510ITO5AUQ97|accessdate=30 August 2016|date=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nBetter luck with injuries saw Halatau play in 22 matches and score 4 tries in the [[2015 NRL season]], equaling his best season tally for the Tigers since the 2005 season. Halatau made his debut as captain in Round 11 against the [[North Queensland Cowboys]] in the Tigers 8\u20130 loss at [[Campbelltown Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-match-report/north-queensland-cowboys-outlast-wests-tigers-with-points-at-a-premium-20150523-gh89ek.html|title=North Queensland Cowboys outlast Wests Tigers with points at a premium|website=Smh.com.au|date=27 January 2016|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> He captained the team a further 2 times while [[Robbie Farah]] and [[Aaron Woods]] were away on State of Origin duties, including a surprise 34\u20136 upset victory over the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] in Round 14.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Pengilly|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/jason-taylor-hails-hardnosed-wests-tigers-cubs-after-drubbing-south-sydney-20150612-ghn1eb.html|title=Jason Taylor hails hard-nosed Wests Tigers cubs after drubbing South Sydney|website=Smh.com.au|date=27 January 2016|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> In Round 19 against the [[Brisbane Broncos]], Halatau played his 150th club match for the Tigers in the 42\u201316 loss at Suncorp Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Zemek|url=http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-sport/halatau-to-savour-150th-for-tigers-in-nrl-20150714-3za03.html|title=Halatau to savour 150th for Tigers in NRL|website=Smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/ladder-leading-broncos-trounce-tigers/tabid/10874/newsid/88142/default.aspx|title=Ladder-leading Broncos trounce Tigers|website=NRL.com|date=19 July 2015|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> The Wests Tigers failed to win any of the games Halatau was absent for the season.\n\nAt season's end, Halatau signed with the Wests Tigers for a further season. Speaking of his career beyond 2016, Halatau said, \"I'm 32 now and I've played longer than I thought I would have played. I feel like I'm still offering a bit to the team. I\u2019m open ended next year, if they want to extend it another year. If they don\u2019t want to and there\u2019s nothing else out there, then I\u2019m prepared to step into life after football.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Daily Telegraph| title=Clubs want rejects, young star eyes extension, veteran\u2019s swan song \u2014 NRL Market Watch| author=Nathan Ryan| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/clubs-want-rejects-young-star-eyes-extension-veterans-swan-song-nrl-market-watch/story-fnp0lyn3-1227646244116|accessdate=16 December 2015|date=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nWith Robbie Farah injured, playing State of Origin, and then dropped to reserve grade, Halatau was the first choice as hooker for the majority of the season. On 18 July 2016, Halatau announced he would retire at the end of the year. He said, \"I was grateful to the club, [[Jason Taylor (rugby league)|JT]] and the coaching staff for giving me this year. While I'm still feeling okay I think it's the right time to hang the boots up.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| publisher = Fairfax| title=Dene Halatau announces NRL retirement| url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/dene-halatau-announces-nrl-retirement-20160717-gq7unc.html|accessdate=28 August 2016|date=18 July 2016}}</ref> [[Phil Gould]] said, \"He has always been one of those quiet achievers in our game. A real team man, he has been admired by his peers. They value his toughness and his outstanding work ethic. His tremendous versatility has also been an asset.\"<ref>{{cite news| work= Sydney Morning Herald| publisher = Fairfax| title=NRL class of 2016: Time to farewell a Wonderful Bunch| first = Phil| last = Gould| url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/nrl-class-of-2016-time-to-farewell-a-wonderful-bunch-20160827-gr2mt0.html|accessdate=28 August 2016|date=28 August 2016}}</ref> Halatau finished his last year in the NRL with him playing in 23 matches for the Tigers in the [[2016 NRL season]].\n\n==Post-playing career==\nHalatau was made an NRL ambassador in 2017.<ref>{{cite web| work= nrl.com | title=2017 NRL Ambassadors announced | url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2017/01/25/2017-nrl-ambassadors-announced/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dene Halatau}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160229073141/http://www.weststigers.com.au/team/profiles/dene_halatau.html 2016 Wests Tigers profile]\n\n{{Wests Tigers squad 2005 NRL premiership}}\n{{New Zealand 2004 Rugby League Tri Nations squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2006 Rugby League Tri Nations squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2008 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{Wests Tigers Life Members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halatau, Dean}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Niuean descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Niue national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Wests Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league second-rows]]\n[[Category:Rugby league locks]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Invercargill]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toPhilip Gould (disambiguation)(link changed toPhil Gould (rugby league)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dene_Halatau"}
{"title_page": "Dil Dhadakne Do", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 film by Zoya Akhtar}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dil Dhadakne Do\n| image          = Dil Dhadakne Do poster.jpg\n| alt            = Dil Dhadakne Do poster featuring the lead actors.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Zoya Akhtar]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Ritesh Sidhwani]]\n*[[Farhan Akhtar]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Reema Kagti]]\n*Zoya Akhtar\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Anil Kapoor]]\n*[[Shefali Shah]]\n*[[Priyanka Chopra]]\n*[[Ranveer Singh]]\n*[[Anushka Sharma]]\n*[[Farhan Akhtar]]\n}}\n| narrator       = [[Aamir Khan]]\n| music          = [[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]]\n| cinematography = Carlos Catalan\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n*Anand Subaya\n*Manan Mehta\n}}\n| studio         = [[Excel Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Eros International]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2015|06|05}}\n| runtime        = 173 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/dil-dhadakne-do-film |title=''Dil Dhadakne Do'' (2015) |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928050116/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/dil-dhadakne-do-film |archive-date=28 September 2015 |access-date=27 September 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}830&nbsp;million<ref name=\"boi\" />\n| gross          = {{INR}}1.45&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"boi\" />\n}}\n'''''Dil Dhadakne Do''''' ({{translation|Let the heart beat}}) is a 2015 Indian [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Zoya Akhtar]], and produced by [[Ritesh Sidhwani]] and [[Farhan Akhtar]]. The film features an [[ensemble cast]] of [[Anil Kapoor]], [[Shefali Shah]], [[Priyanka Chopra]], [[Ranveer Singh]], [[Anushka Sharma]] and [[Farhan Akhtar]], with a voice-over performance by [[Aamir Khan]] as the family dog Pluto, the narrator of the film. The supporting cast also includes [[Rahul Bose]], [[Zarina Wahab]], [[Vikrant Massey]], [[Pawan Chopra]], [[Parmeet Sethi]], [[Dolly Minhas|Dolly Mattdo]] and [[Manoj Pahwa]]. The film tells the story of the Mehras, a dysfunctional [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] family who invite their family and friends on a cruise trip to celebrate the parents' 30th wedding anniversary and later reconcile.\n\nAkhtar conceived the film as a family drama centred on a brother-sister relationship. She wanted to depict a more realistic sibling relationship in contrast to the dubious and over-the-top portrayal for which [[Bollywood]] is known. Akhtar later co-wrote the screenplay with her friend and longtime collaborator [[Reema Kagti]]. Much of the [[principal photography]] was done on [[Pullmantur Cruises]]' ship [[MS Sovereign|MS ''Sovereign'']] while sailing across the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] and [[Europe]], and on land in France, Spain, Tunisia, Turkey and Italy.\n\nThe soundtrack was composed by the trio [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]], with lyrics by [[Javed Akhtar]]. The film was released worldwide on 5 June 2015 to positive reviews from critics, who praised the performances of Kapoor, Shah, Chopra and Singh, who portrayed the members of the Mehra family, as well as Akhtar's direction, cinematography and costumes. The film grossed {{INR}}1.45 billion at the box office against a budget of {{INR}}830&nbsp;million, and earned a [[List of accolades received by Dil Dhadakne Do|number of accolades]]. It received five [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare]] nominations, winning [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor. ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' also received nine nominations at the 2016 [[Screen Awards]], including [[Screen Award for Best Film|Best Film]], and won two, [[Screen Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor and [[Screen Awards|Best Ensemble Cast]].\n\n== Plot ==\n\nKamal Mehra is a millionaire businessman who owns AyKa, a company on the verge of bankruptcy. He has a troubled relationship with his wife Neelam, daughter Ayesha and son Kabir. The Mehra family also includes their pet dog, Pluto. Ayesha owns a successful business but is unhappy with her marriage to Manav Sangha, a controlling, narcissistic husband who, together with his mother Smita hates Ayesha's family. Kabir, who yearns to become a pilot, unwillingly participates in the family business. Kamal and Neelam invite their family and friends for a ten-day cruise across the Mediterranean to celebrate their 30th wedding anniversary. Their guests include the Sood family, consisting of businessman Lalit Sood, his wife Naina and their daughter Noori. Kamal and Neelam plan to get Kabir married to Noori in exchange for Lalit investing in AyKa.\n\nThe Mehra family and all of their guests board the cruise ship in Italy. Kabir meets Farah, a dancer, and begins a relationship with her. Noori is in love with Rana Khanna, the son of Vinod and Vandana. The Khannas, however, are sworn enemies of the Soods, so Kabir and Noori decide to manipulate their parents into believing they are dating each other while continuing with their respective relationships. Ayesha considers divorcing her husband, whom she believes is incompatible with her. Her parents are staunchly against it, believing it will dishonour the family. Meanwhile, Sunny Gill, the son of Kamal's manager Amrish, arrives on the ship. Sunny and Ayesha dated each other as teenagers. Kamal, who was unhappy with their relationship, arranged and paid for Sunny's [[Yale University]] tuition to separate him from Ayesha. Ayesha realises that she still harbours feelings for Sunny, now a successful journalist. Unlike Manav, Sunny appreciates Ayesha's strong personality and believes in female empowerment.\n\nNeelam sees Kamal flirting with one of the female guests and wonders why she did not divorce him despite his past infidelities. Ayesha confronts Sunny about his sudden departure and kisses him, which she later regrets because she is married. Meanwhile, Farah hears that Kabir is planning to marry Noori and ends their relationship. Elsewhere, Kamal sees Noori making out with Rana and has a fit, after which he is rushed to the onboard emergency room. At the clinic, Kamal tells Kabir he saw Noori with Rana and asks him to end his relationship with her. Kabir tells his family he knew about the couple's relationship and that he is in love with Farah. He also tells them he intends to leave the family business and asks them to consider Ayesha, who is actually interested in business. He also tries to persuade them to let her proceed with her divorce as she is unhappy with the marriage, but Kamal and Neelam still refuse, believing marriages are lifelong commitments. Infuriated, Kabir tells Kamal that he, Neelam and Ayesha were all aware of his adultery and that Neelam has been bearing his infidelities and suffering silently to save the family. Kamal asks Neelam why she had not divorced him; she reveals she had no choice because her family would not accept her back due to their fear of dishonour. Kamal realises his mistake, asks for Neelam's forgiveness and consoles her. Later, while trying to reconcile Manav and Ayesha, Kamal sees how Manav mistreats his daughter and asks him and Smita to leave. He agrees to the divorce and asks Ayesha for forgiveness.\n\nKabir tries to persuade Farah to forgive him for lying to her, but she is dismissed from her job for being involved with a passenger and is told to leave the ship. Kabir learns about her dismissal after the ship has set sail from the port where it had docked for some time. Seeing no other option, Kabir, aided by Sunny, jumps off the ship, hoping his family will rescue him and help him get ashore. Kamal, Neelam, Ayesha, and Pluto eventually find a lifeboat to rescue him. While leaving, Ayesha asks Sunny if he would wait for her, to which he replies \"forever\". The family rescue Kabir and head towards the shore while being chased by the ship's crew. The Mehra family is seen happy in each other's presence for the first time.\n\n== Cast ==\nThe cast is listed below:<ref name=\"cast&crew\" />\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Anil Kapoor]] as Kamal Mehra\n* [[Shefali Shah]] as Neelam Mehra\n* [[Priyanka Chopra]] as Ayesha Sangha\n* [[Ranveer Singh]] as Kabir Mehra\n* [[Anushka Sharma]] as Farah Ali\n* [[Farhan Akhtar]] as Sunny Gill\n* [[Aamir Khan]] in a [[voice-over]] as Pluto Mehra/[[Narrator]]\n* [[Rahul Bose]] as Manav Sangha\n* [[Zarina Wahab]] as Smita Sangha\n* [[Vikrant Massey]] as Ranjeev \"Rana\" Khanna\n* Ridhima Sud as Noorie Sood\n* [[Pawan Chopra]] as Prem Mehra\n* Ayesha Raza Mishra as Indu Mehra\n* [[Parmeet Sethi]] as Lalit Sood\n* [[Dolly Minhas]] as Naina Sood\n* [[Manoj Pahwa]] as Vinod Khanna\n* Preeti Mamgain as Vandana Khanna\n* Shireesh Sharma as Jamaal Hashmi\n* [[Divya Seth]] as Saira Hashmi\n* Ikhlaque Khan as Amrish Gill\n* Vandana Sajnani as Anju Chopra\n* Sarah Hashmi as Divya Mehra\n* [[Khushi Dubey]] as Putlu Mehra\n* [[Ivan Sylvester Rodrigues]] as Dharmapala Sr.\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Zoya at audio release of Talaash.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of Zoya Akhtar smiling, looking towards the camera|[[Zoya Akhtar]] had always intended to make a family drama with a brother-sister relationship as its core narrative]]\n\nWhen [[Excel Entertainment]] announced its upcoming films in March 2012, one of them was Zoya Akhtar's next film following ''[[Zindagi Na Milegi Dobara]]'' (2011). It was reported that she was working on a script and that filming was due to start in December 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/1423876 |title=Farhan and Ritesh announce Excel's line-up |date=20 March 2012 |publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519185814/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/1423876 |archive-date=19 May 2016 |access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> Akhtar dismissed the reports, saying she was yet to start writing her next script.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/yet-to-write-my-next-film-so-not-decided-about-cast-zoya-akhtar/925991/ |title=Yet to write my next film, so not decided about cast: Zoya Akhtar |date=20 March 2012 |website=[[The Indian Express]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502204821/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/yet-to-write-my-next-film-so-not-decided-about-cast-zoya-akhtar/925991/ |archive-date=2 May 2016 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May that year, media reports suggested Akhtar was already writing her next film.<ref name=\"castingnews1\" /> That July, it was reported the script was about siblings partially based on Akhtar and her brother Farhan Akhtar.<ref name=\"castingnews2\" /> Farhan Akhtar later denied reports of the film being autobiographical, saying it had nothing to do with their real life relationship and that it is entirely a work of fiction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/zoya-s-film-has-nothing-to-do-with-our-real-life-farhan-interview-113120900878_1.html |title=Zoya's film has nothing to do with our real life: Farhan (Interview) |last=[[Indo-Asian News Service]] |date=9 December 2013 |website=[[Business Standard]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519194413/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/zoya-s-film-has-nothing-to-do-with-our-real-life-farhan-interview-113120900878_1.html |archive-date=19 May 2016 |access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> In November 2012, Akhtar said she was still writing the script and that the film was a family drama.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/zoya-akhtar-is-scripting-a-family-drama-now-522611.html |title=Zoya Akhtar is scripting a family drama now |date=20 November 2012 |publisher=[[CNN-News18]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821004112/http://www.news18.com/news/india/zoya-akhtar-is-scripting-a-family-drama-now-522611.html |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar co-wrote the screenplay with her long-time friend and collaborator [[Reema Kagti]].<ref name=\"sibling1\" /> Akhtar had always aspired to make a family drama with a brother-sister relationship at its core.<ref name=\"sibling2\" /> She felt such topics not been well represented in Indian films,<ref name=\"sibling2\" /> and that the brother-sister relationship bond has always been shown \"wrapped in rituals\" and never portrayed as it really is. She believed the theme of brother-sister relationships \"generally have cheesy representations. They are never at ease. This is one of the most important relationships in the world because nobody else shares your parents. I wanted to show that relationship in ''Dil Dhadakne Do''\".<ref name=\"sibling1\" /><ref name=\"sibling2\" /> Akhtar also wanted to showcase the quirkiness of a dysfunctional family, with different layers to each family member, saying, \"the beauty of families lies in their flaws\".<ref name=\"different\" /><ref name=\"device\" />\n\nWhen asked whether the film had any similarities with her own life and family, she said it had none and that the only thing common to herself and the film's characters was the bond between her and her brother; all their problems and conflicts were unalike.<ref name=\"different\" /> Akhtar said the film was a partly fictionalised version of people around her, such as her friends and their families, and her observations from literature and news articles.<ref name=\"fc\" /><ref name=\"rich\" /> Kagti and Akhtar revealed that some of their material came from observing people of [[Delhi]] during their friends' back-to-back, elite-class wedding parties as they were finishing the script; they made notes about people's behaviour and demeanor, and incorporated these into their script.<ref name=\"fc\" /> After finalising the characters, they felt something was missing, so they added Pluto, the family dog, as an observer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/why-aamir-khan-was-chosen-for-the-voice-of-pluto-in-dil-dhadakne-do/article7298285.ece |title=A voice from afar |last=Devi Dundoo, Sangeetha |date=9 June 2015 |website=[[The Hindu]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113074052/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/why-aamir-khan-was-chosen-for-the-voice-of-pluto-in-dil-dhadakne-do/article7298285.ece |archive-date=13 January 2018 |access-date=20 August 2017}}</ref> The completed film has 25 characters and a dog.<ref name=\"rich\" />\n\nWhen asked about interweaving travel in the narrative, Akhtar said she and Kagti wanted a device to bring all the characters\u2014the entire family\u2014together.<ref name=\"device\" /> She said the film could have been set anywhere, such as a hill station, but they chose to set it on a cruise ship because the characters would not be able to leave.<ref name=\"device\" /><ref name=\"metaphor\" /> Akhtar called it a metaphor for the bigger journey that every family undertakes; the characters are stuck together on a ship in the middle of an ocean and could not leave if they wanted to.<ref name=\"metaphor\" /> The film's title ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' was chosen because Akhtar wanted a catchy, easily identifiable title.<ref name=\"metaphor\" />\n\n=== Casting and characters ===\nDuring the initial scripting phase, in May 2012, media reports suggested cousins [[Kareena Kapoor]] and [[Ranbir Kapoor]] had been approached to play the siblings and had accepted the parts.<ref name=\"castingnews1\" /><ref name=\"castingnews2\" /> In late December 2012, [[Hrithik Roshan]] and [[Katrina Kaif]] joined the cast to play the Kapoors' characters' love interests respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hrithik-kareena-katrina-and-ranveer-to-star-in-zoya-akhtars-next-film-464762 |title=Hrithik, Kareena, Katrina and Ranveer to Star in Zoya Akhtar's Next Film? |date=6 May 2013 |website=[[International Business Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825233411/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hrithik-kareena-katrina-and-ranveer-to-star-in-zoya-akhtars-next-film-464762 |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In June 2013, Ranbir Kapoor dropped out of the film due to scheduling conflicts with his other projects; he was replaced by [[Ranveer Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ranveer-singh-set-to-replace-ranbir-kapoor/story-MFVgr8dEtYf5adLJYWZqEI.html |title=Ranveer Singh set to replace Ranbir Kapoor? |last=Singh, Prashant |date=8 June 2013 |website=Hindustan Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825232507/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ranveer-singh-set-to-replace-ranbir-kapoor/story-MFVgr8dEtYf5adLJYWZqEI.html |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was then reported that after her cousin dropped out, Kareena Kapoor was having second thoughts about appearing in the film; the opportunity to act alongside her cousin had been the main attraction for her.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Kareena-Hrithik-and-Ranbir-Katrina-in-Zoyas-next-film/articleshow/17791145.cms |title=Kareena-Hrithik and Ranbir-Katrina in Zoya's next film |last=Thakkar, Mehul S |date=28 December 2012 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171509/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Kareena-Hrithik-and-Ranbir-Katrina-in-Zoyas-next-film/articleshow/17791145.cms |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> She left the production later that month, saying she could not leave her family for the required three months and calling her decision \"her loss\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kareena-kapoor-zoya-akhtar-dil-dhadakne-do-singham-returns/1/373891.html |title=Not doing Zoya's film is my loss, says Kareena Kapoor |date=24 July 2014 |website=India Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113074059/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/kareena-kapoor-zoya-akhtar-dil-dhadakne-do-singham-returns-201554-2014-07-24 |archive-date=13 January 2018 |access-date=25 August 2017}}</ref> In late June 2013, Akhtar approached [[Priyanka Chopra]] to part that role, and Chopra accepted.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/priyanka-chopra-to-play-ranveer-singhs-elder-sister_137376.html |title=Priyanka Chopra to play Ranveer Singh's elder sister? |date=22 June 2013 |publisher=[[Zee News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825225618/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/priyanka-chopra-to-play-ranveer-singhs-elder-sister_137376.html |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October, [[Anil Kapoor]] was confirmed to play the role of Chopra and Singh's father in the film. It was also reported that [[Dimple Kapadia]] could possibly play his wife, but this was not to be,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/videos/anil-kapoor-to-portray-father-to-grown-up-children-293049 |title=Anil Kapoor to portray father to grown up children |date=3 October 2013 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827130920/http://movies.ndtv.com/videos/anil-kapoor-to-portray-father-to-grown-up-children-293049 |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Farhan Akhtar confirmed he was playing a crucial role in his sister's film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/2267291 |title=Farhan Akhtar in sister Zoya's film |date=3 December 2013 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208045904/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/2267291 |archive-date=8 December 2013 |access-date=23 February 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2014, [[Anushka Sharma]] was cast for the role of Singh's love interest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-anushka-to-romance-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next_150059.html |title=Ranveer, Anushka to romance in Zoya Akhtar's next? |date=31 January 2014 |publisher=Zee News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825232744/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-anushka-to-romance-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next_150059.html |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Madhuri Dixit]], [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]] and [[Raveena Tandon]] were all approached to play Chopra and Singh's mother in the film; although they liked the part, all of them turned down the role because they did not want to play a mother.<ref name=\"mother\" /> Akhtar later approached [[Shefali Shah]] for the part, which she accepted.<ref name=\"mother\" /> Newcomer Ridhima Sud joined the cast in June 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-to-launch-newbie-ridhima-sud-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Zoya Akhtar to launch newbie Ridhima Sud in Dil Dhadakne Do |date=19 June 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827173923/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-to-launch-newbie-ridhima-sud-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A few days later, [[Rahul Bose]] was cast to play the role of Manav (Chopra's husband) in the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/rahul-bose-joins-the-starcast-of-zoyas-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Rahul Bose joins the starcast of Zoya's Dil Dhadakne Do |date=21 June 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827174046/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/rahul-bose-joins-the-starcast-of-zoyas-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Zarina Wahab]] joined the cast to play Chopra's mother-in-law.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zarina-wahab-plays-priyankas-mother-in-law-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Zarina Wahab plays Priyanka's mother-in-law in Dil Dhadakne Do |date=23 July 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827173339/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zarina-wahab-plays-priyankas-mother-in-law-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Parmeet Sethi]] was later cast in an important role.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-signs-parmeet-sethi-for-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Zoya Akhtar signs Parmeet Sethi for Dil Dhadakne Do |date=2 August 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827173855/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-signs-parmeet-sethi-for-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough meant for a surprise, the details about [[Aamir Khan]]'s voiceover performance as the family dog Pluto was leaked before the film's release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/AK-turns-bullmastiff-for-Zoya/articleshow/47467604.cms |title=AK turns bullmastiff for Zoya |last=Pathak, Ankur |date=29 May 2015 |website=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827205938/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/AK-turns-bullmastiff-for-Zoya/articleshow/47467604.cms |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Javed Akhtar]] had initially provided the voiceover for Pluto. After watching the film weeks before the release, however, Akhtar asked Aamir to do the voiceover and the actor accepted, saying, \"I had loved the film so much that I was just happy to be a part of it&nbsp;...&nbsp;I think it is a great film to be part of\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/didnt-think-twice-before-playing-pluto-the-dog-aamir-khan/ |title=Didn't think twice before playing Pluto the dog: Aamir Khan |last=Indo-Asian News Service |date=8 June 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827172411/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/didnt-think-twice-before-playing-pluto-the-dog-aamir-khan/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCompared with the rest of the cast, Akhtar spent a whole year persuading Anil Kapoor to sign up for the film.<ref name=\"convince\" /> Akhtar's brother Farhan and father Javed Akhtar also spoke to him about the role. However, when Aamir Khan approached him on Akhtar's behalf, he finally accepted the part.<ref name=\"convince\" /> Kapoor described his role of Kamal Mehra as a \"manipulative patriarch\" and a businessman who \"has no qualms about manipulating people, even his own family members, to achieve his goal\".<ref name=\"manipulative\" /> He said, \"Kamal is a [[self-made man]] and does not want to lose [his business empire] and will do anything to save it\".<ref name=\"manipulative\" /> Kapoor found playing his character very exciting, being completely opposite to his real self; a patriarch whose company, rather than his family, comes first.<ref name=\"manipulative\" />\n\nShah called her character, Neelam Mehra, a \"Delhi elite society queen bee\" with multiple layers, saying, \"It looks like nothing can put a chink in her armour, but inside, she is a vulnerable and lost person\".<ref name=\"amother\" /> She said her character shows an artificial side about her marriage while facing the world, opposed to her behaviour in their home: \"It's not one of the best marriages. She hates what\u2019s happened to both of them. But when they come in front of the world, she will stand by her husband\".<ref name=\"amother\" /> Her character discriminates between her son and her daughter; she said, \"She is evidently partial to her son. With her daughter, she displays a mentality typical of many Indian mothers. Even though her daughter is in a bad marriage as well, she discourages her from taking a divorce.\"<ref name=\"amother\" /> Shah said accepted the part because it \"was one of the best scripts I had read in a very long time. It was sharp, wicked, and emotional, without being melodramatic.\"<ref name=\"screen\" /> To prepare for her role, she formed an outline of her character by forming Neelam's history and personality.<ref name=\"screen\" />\n\nChopra has described her character, Ayesha Mehra, as strong but also feminine and gentle, noting her inner strength.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/priyanka-i-am-very-greedy-about-my-work/20150601.htm |title=Priyanka: I am very greedy about my work |last=N, Patcy |date=1 June 2015 |publisher=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224054822/http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/priyanka-i-am-very-greedy-about-my-work/20150601.htm |archive-date=24 December 2016 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> She said Ayesha has complicated emotions, and that she \"has no idea what she wants and she keeps changing her mind, probably like most women&nbsp;...&nbsp;that is exactly what Ayesha does. She doesn't know which direction to go in. She actually has no opinion on love or marriage, but just wants to be able to feel that she can be loved.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/priyanka-chopra-and-ranveer-singh-on-the-bittersweet-comedy-dil-dhadakne-do-1.98438 |title=Priyanka Chopra and Ranveer Singh on the bittersweet comedy Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Khan, Ujala Ali |date=2 June 2015 |website=The National |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827212536/https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/priyanka-chopra-and-ranveer-singh-on-the-bittersweet-comedy-dil-dhadakne-do-1.98438 |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Chopra had to shed the muscle weight she gained for playing the boxer in ''[[Mary Kom (film)|Mary Kom]]'' (2014). She said, \"I was not muscular but had acquired bulked-up physique. I had to be in right shape as I was playing a girly role. I had to&nbsp;...&nbsp;go on a crash diet and lose shape.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/post-mary-kom-priyanka-chopra-had-to-tone-down-for-girly-role-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Post 'Mary Kom', Priyanka Chopra had to tone down for 'girly role' in 'Dil Dhadakne Do' |last=[[Press Trust of India]] |date=24 July 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828011206/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/post-mary-kom-priyanka-chopra-had-to-tone-down-for-girly-role-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=28 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Singh called his character, Kabir Mehra, a privileged, \"born with a silver spoon\" kind of person who wants to pursue different things other than inherit his father's fortune.<ref name=\"reveal\" /> He said, \"Ever since his childhood, he was raised to take over his father's company. But this isn't what he wants to do. He loves planes, he wants to be a pilot. Because of this miscommunication he is in a lot of pain.\"<ref name=\"reveal\" /> Khan described Pluto as a \"very philosophical\" dog who is \"really into observing human nature and has a take on everything\".<ref name=\"convince\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Pullmantur Cruises Sovereign 04 IMO 8512281 @chesi.JPG|thumb|upright=1.4|alt=A photograph of MS Sovereign|The film was extensively filmed on the [[MS Sovereign|MS ''Sovereign'']]]]\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on 17 May 2014 on the [[Pullmantur Cruises]] ship [[MS Sovereign|MS ''Sovereign'']] throughout the Mediterranean Sea and onshore in France, Spain, Tunisia, Turkey and Italy.<ref name=\"bts\" /><ref name=\"filming\" /> Filming on the ship was done over a non-consecutive period of five weeks; the cast and crew members would board the ship at [[Barcelona]] and would film the scenes while en route to different destinations; five different places in five weeks, where the cast and crew would shoot the onshore scenes.<ref name=\"bts\" /> Onshore filming took two months, finishing on 18 July 2014.<ref name=\"bts\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/a-pleasant-surprise-for-priyanka-chopra/15457163 |title=A birthday surprise for Priyanka Chopra |date=18 July 2014 |website=Mid Day |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729004310/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/a-pleasant-surprise-for-priyanka-chopra/15457163 |archive-date=29 July 2014 |access-date=20 July 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Filming took ninety days, finishing in early August 2014.<ref name=\"filming\" /> The second and final schedule began in mid-August 2014 in [[Mumbai]], and was completed on 23 September 2014.<ref name=\"filming\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/its-a-wrap-for-dil-dhadakne-do-exes-ranveer-anushka-party-with-director-zoya/2/ |title=It's a wrap for Dil Dhadakne Do \u2013 exes Ranveer, Anushka party with director Zoya |date=24 September 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106223212/http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/its-a-wrap-for-dil-dhadakne-do-exes-ranveer-anushka-party-with-director-zoya/2/ |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFilming also took place in several locations in Turkey, such as [[Antalya]], [[Cappadocia]] and [[Istanbul]].<ref name=\"visual\" /> For one scene set in Istanbul's [[Hagia Sophia|Sophia Museum]], tourists and museum staff were used as extras for the sequence, which took six hours to film.<ref name=\"facts\" /> For a sequence featuring Chopra and Bose's characters playing [[Squash (sport)|squash]], Chopra, helped by Bose, had to learn the sport on set.<ref name=\"facts\" /> The pre-production work was a challenge for the makers, who had to plan everything in detail; Akhtar and her team reconnoitred to find perfect places to shoot the film.<ref name=\"visual\" /> Akhtar found the filming unforgettable, saying, \"Can you imagine the whole crew is in a new country everyday! That is what it is like to be on a cruise ship in the Mediterranean. It was logistically insane, visually gorgeous and emotionally cathartic.\"<ref name=\"visual\" />\n\nNeil Patel handled the [[production design]]. Akhtar's frequent collaborator Carlos Catalan provided the cinematography, and Anand Subaya and Manan Mehta edited the film.<ref name=\"cast&crew\" /> [[Arjun Bhasin]] designed all of the film's costumes. [[Bosco\u2013Caesar]] choreographed the songs;<ref name=\"cast&crew\" /> The entire song \"Gallan Goodiyaan\" was shot in a single five-minute take.<ref name=\"onetake\" /> It required detailed planning and choreography, which the cast rehearsed before filming it.<ref name=\"onetake\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Dil Dhadakne Do\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n| cover      =\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2015|05|2}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 21:37\n| language   = [[Hindi]]\n| label      = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Kill Dil]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Katti Batti]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n}}\n''Dil Dhadakne Do''{{'s}} soundtrack was composed by the trio [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] and [[Javed Akhtar]] wrote the lyrics. The album consists of five original songs.<ref name=\"bh\" /> The vocals are performed by Priyanka Chopra, Farhan Akhtar, Sukriti Kakar, Siddharth Mahadevan, Shankar Mahadevan, Yashita Sharma, Manish Kumar Tipu, Sukhwinder Singh, Sunidhi Chauhan, Vishal Dadlani, [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]] and Alyssa Mendonsa. It was released on 2 May 2015 by [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]].<ref name=\"bh\" />\n\nThe soundtrack received generally positive reviews from critics, who labelled it more narrative-based than a chartbuster. Chopra's singing on the first fully-Hindi song she had recorded was also lauded by critics.<ref name=\"bh\" /> Joginder Tuteja of [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave a rating of 3.5 out of 5, describing it as \"a classy soundtrack [that] is unadulterated when it comes to quintessential Bollywood scheme of things\".<ref name=\"bh\" /> ''[[The Times of India]]'' also gave it a rating of 3.5 out of 5, calling the compositions \"foot-tapping and swingy\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47373373.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Fernandes, Kasmin |date=22 May 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818232524/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47373373.cms |archive-date=18 August 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In another positive review, ''[[Filmfare]]'' said the composers had \"done a good job despite the hurdles\", noting the limiting setting of the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/music-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9267.html |title=Music Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Sharma, Devesh |date=22 May 2015 |website=[[Filmfare]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812213528/https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/music-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9267.html |archive-date=12 August 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Koimoi]] rated it 2.5 out of 5, terming it a mixed bag. However, it praised the songs \"Dil Dhadakne Do\" and \"Pehli Baar\", noting them as standouts. The reviewer wrote that Chopra particularly \"impresses with her vocals\" in the former song.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-music-review/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Music Review |last=Redkar, Surabhi |date=30 May 2015 |publisher=[[Koimoi]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528195425/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-music-review/ |archive-date=28 May 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline            = Track listing<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dil-dhadakne-do-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-ep/id1071191851 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |publisher=[[iTunes]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171509/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dil-dhadakne-do-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-ep/id1071191851 |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| total_length = 21:37\n| extra_column        = Artist(s)\n| title1              = Dil Dhadakne Do\n| extra1              = [[Priyanka Chopra]], [[Farhan Akhtar]]\n| length1             = 03:48\n| title2              = Pehli Baar\n| extra2              = Sukriti Kakar, [[Siddharth Mahadevan]]\n| length2             = 04:23\n| title3              = Gallan Goodiyaan\n| extra3              = [[Shankar Mahadevan]], Yashita Sharma, Manish Kumar Tipu, Farhan Akhtar, [[Sukhwinder Singh]]\n| length3             = 04:56\n| title4              = Girls Like To Swing\n| extra4              = [[Sunidhi Chauhan]]\n| length4             = 04:03\n| title5              = Phir Bhi Yeh Zindagi\n| extra5              = Farhan Akhtar, [[Vishal Dadlani]], [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]], [[Alyssa Mendonsa]]\n| length5             = 04:27\n}}\n\n== Release ==\n''Dil Dhadakne Do'' was one of the most highly anticipated films of 2015 owing to its star cast and the success of Akhtar's previous film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Hindi/Bollywood/News/Zoya-Akhtars-friends-eagerly-awaiting-Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer/articleshow/46723840.cms |title=Zoya Akhtar's friends eagerly awaiting 'Dil Dhadakne Do' trailer |last=Kotwani, Hiren |date=28 March 2017 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171509/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Hindi/Bollywood/News/Zoya-Akhtars-friends-eagerly-awaiting-Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer/articleshow/46723840.cms |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/here-s-why-zoya-akhtar-is-secretive-about-dil-dhadakne-do-trailer/story-ABYfcLyPnAaEtlbK7U6etI.html |title=Here's why Zoya Akhtar is secretive about Dil Dhadakne Do trailer |last=Mangaokar, Shalvi |date=27 March 2015 |website=Hindustan Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819190820/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/here-s-why-zoya-akhtar-is-secretive-about-dil-dhadakne-do-trailer/story-ABYfcLyPnAaEtlbK7U6etI.html |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first-look teaser poster, photographed from behind the six pivotal characters and a dog sunbathing on a cruise deck was released on 21 July 2014, almost a year before the scheduled release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/first-look-ranveer-priyanka-anushka-farhan-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=First look: Ranveer, Priyanka, Anushka, Farhan in 'Dil Dhadakne Do' |last=Divya, Goyal |date=21 July 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819231625/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/first-look-ranveer-priyanka-anushka-farhan-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The poster did not reveal the actors' looks, instead making the audience puzzle about the actors from behind.<ref name=\"guess\" /> A few days later, the first full poster revealing the position of the actors photographed from the front was revealed.<ref name=\"guess\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/dil-dhadakne-do-first-look-poster-out/ |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' First Look Poster Out |date=24 July 2014 |publisher=Koimoi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819190514/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/dil-dhadakne-do-first-look-poster-out/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2015, seven character posters, including one for the family dog Pluto, were released. The poster releases generated much hype for the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/dil-dhadakne-do-storyline-first-look-ranveer-anushka-starrer-revealed-photos-628874 |title='Dil Dhadakne Do': Meet Pluto, New Member of Mehra Family [PHOTOS] |last=Goswami, Parismita |date=11 April 2015 |website=International Business Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819190446/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/dil-dhadakne-do-storyline-first-look-ranveer-anushka-starrer-revealed-photos-628874 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The trailer release was highly anticipated in the media because the plot was kept secret.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/farhan-akhtar-watches-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer-but-cant-show-it-to-anybody/ |title=Farhan Akhtar watches 'Dil Dhadakne Do's trailer, but can't show it to anybody |date=9 April 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233049/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/farhan-akhtar-watches-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer-but-cant-show-it-to-anybody/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nEmphasising the theme of the film, Akhtar and Kapoor hosted a private screening of the trailer for their friends and family.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/anil-kapoor-hosted-a-screening-for-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer/ |title=Anil Kapoor Hosted A Screening For Dil Dhadakne Do's Trailer |date=14 April 2015 |publisher=Koimoi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622011038/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/anil-kapoor-hosted-a-screening-for-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer/ |archive-date=22 June 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-crew-planning-private-trailer-screening/ |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' crew planning private trailer screening |last=Indo-Asian News Service |date=11 April 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233254/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-crew-planning-private-trailer-screening/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The official theatrical release posters were released before the trailer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-countdown-mehras-embark-on-epic-journey-in-brand-new-posters-755238 |title=Mehras 'Embark on Epic Journey' in Brand New Dil Dhadakne Do Poster |last=Prashar, Chandni |date=15 April 2015 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819231927/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-countdown-mehras-embark-on-epic-journey-in-brand-new-posters-755238 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The almost-three-minute official trailer was released on 15 April 2015, garnering over one million views in less than 24 hours.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2015/04/15/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer_n_7070640.html |title=Watch: Star-Studded 'Dil Dhadakne Do' Trailer Features Generous Helpings Of Family Dysfunction |last=Chatterjee, Suprateek |date=15 April 2015 |website=[[HuffPost]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819232558/http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2015/04/15/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer_n_7070640.html |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"trailer\" /> The trailer was well received by the media, who deemed it promising.<ref name=\"trailer\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer-Anushka-Sharma-Ranveer-Singh-Priyanka-Chopra-steal-the-show/articleshow/46937819.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do trailer: Anushka Sharma, Ranveer Singh, Priyanka Chopra steal the show |last=Kaushal, Ruchi |date=15 April 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423145053/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer-Anushka-Sharma-Ranveer-Singh-Priyanka-Chopra-steal-the-show/articleshow/46937819.cms |archive-date=23 April 2015 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Alaka Sahani of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' called it \"overwhelming\" and wrote, \"The top-view of the cruise line with expansive ocean as the backdrop, stunning foreign locales and beautiful people in their stylish best make for compelling visuals. But scratch the surface, and you find a dysfunctional family trying hard to act normal to the world.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer-feel-the-heartbeat/ |title=Watch Priyanka, Ranveer, Anushka's 'Dil Dhadakne Do' trailer: Feel the heartbeat |last=Sahani, Alaka |date=15 April 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233231/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer-feel-the-heartbeat/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was released on 5 June 2015 in 2,300 screens worldwide on a budget of {{INR}}830&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"boi\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/todays-big-release-dil-dhadakne-do-768897 |title=Today's Big Release: Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Prashar, Chandni |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819232943/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/todays-big-release-dil-dhadakne-do-768897 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to an analysis by [[Box Office India]], the film was likely to perform better in [[Metropolitan cities of India|major Indian cities]] than in smaller centres, but predicted it would perform much better overseas due to its niche content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1340 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Looking Good For Big Metros |date=4 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820073745/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1340 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Distributed by [[Reliance Entertainment|Big Home Entertainment]], it was released on [[DVD]] in all [[DVD region code|regions]] on 30 August 2015 as a two-disc pack in [[NTSC]] widescreen format; bonus content included the making of the film and deleted scenes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.in/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Ranveer-Singh/dp/B013E4EYNC |title=Dil Dhadakne Do DVD |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820034156/http://www.amazon.in/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Ranveer-Singh/dp/B013E4EYNC |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A [[VCD]] version was released at the same time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Blu-ray/138254/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Blu-ray |publisher=Blu-ray |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820073746/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Blu-ray/138254/ |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film's Blu-ray version was released on 5 September 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.induna.com/1000021199-productdetails/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do VCD |publisher=[[Induna.com|Induna]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160210091133/http://www.induna.com/1000021199-productdetails/ |archive-date=10 February 2016 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' had its Indian television premiere on 24 October 2015 on [[Zee Cinema]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-to-have-a-grand-world-television-premiere/articleshow/49507077.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do to have a grand world television premiere |date=24 October 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827092024/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-to-have-a-grand-world-television-premiere/articleshow/49507077.cms |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe film received positive reviews, receiving praise for the cast performances, humour, cinematography, costumes and direction, but it received criticism for its running time and climax.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmfare.com/news/dil-dhadakne-do-has-a-fantastic-weekend-9445.html |title=Dil Dhadakne Do has a fantastic weekend |date=8 June 2015 |website=Filmfare |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701155819/http://www.filmfare.com/news/dil-dhadakne-do-has-a-fantastic-weekend-9445.html |archive-date=1 July 2017 |access-date=27 October 2017}}</ref> In a 4-star review for ''[[Mumbai Mirror]]'', critic Kunal Guha described the film as an \"emotional roller-coaster\", comparing Akhtar's direction to that of [[Woody Allen]] and [[Wes Anderson]], and complimented the performances of the cast.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guha |first=Kunal |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Film-review-Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47547376.cms |title=Film Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |date=5 June 2015 |work=Mumbai Mirror |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606131650/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Film-review-Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47547376.cms |archive-date=6 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rajiv Vijayakar from ''India-West'' gave a rating of 4 stars, describing it as \"entertaining with stellar performances\", praising Akhtar's direction and writing, \"Zoya gets the emotions right by making the entertainment riveting and the experience full of many perceptive insights into basic relationships\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/movie_reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-movie-review-inspiring-story-entertains-with-stellar/article_8bb3e204-0bab-11e5-90c1-7b85c1453b2e.html |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' Movie Review: Inspiring Story Entertains with Stellar Performances |last=Vijayakar, Rajive |date=5 June 2015 |website=India-West |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712015040/http://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/movie_reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-movie-review-inspiring-story-entertains-with-stellar/article_8bb3e204-0bab-11e5-90c1-7b85c1453b2e.html |archive-date=12 July 2015 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Srijana Mitra Das of ''[[The Times of India]]'' gave the film 4 stars, praising the performances of the lead actors and writing, \"On this ship, a few bolts could be tighter. But these are fleeting clouds on an otherwise beautiful sea, hosting a cruise&nbsp;...&nbsp;while searching beyond Bollywood's emotional Botox for a family's warts&nbsp;- and its heart.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mitra Das, Srijana |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/movie-review/47536090.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Movie Review |date=4 June 2015 |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605041934/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/movie-review/47536090.cms |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shubha Shetty-Saha of ''[[Mid-Day]]'' gave the film 4 stars and complimented the story, stating, \"If this film looks like an entertaining, escapist film at the outset, it is, but it is also much deeper than that\".<ref name=\"midday\" /> She also appreciated the performances, especially Chopra's and Singh's, writing, \"These two blazing talents are magical when they come together sharing what perhaps could be one of the best sibling chemistry in Hindi films\".<ref name=\"midday\" />\n\nThe reviewer from [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave the film 3.5 stars, praising Akhtar's direction for \"[pulling] off such a magnificent film with such utmost ease\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/732336 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Review |date=4 June 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607173837/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/732336 |archive-date=7 June 2015 |access-date=4 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', film critic [[Anupama Chopra]] rated the film 3.5 stars, commending the performances&nbsp;- particularly those of Kapoor, Shah and Chopra&nbsp;- and the high production value, writing, \"There are soaring top shots of the ship, of gorgeous towns in Turkey and Greece, and of staggering fashions\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-review-by-anupama-chopra-a-flawed-family/story-MrcouizWr8HnfacmV6j8JM.html |title=Dil Dhadakne Do review by Anupama Chopra: A flawed family |last=Chopra, Anupama |date=8 June 2015 |website=Hindustan Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820201631/http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-review-by-anupama-chopra-a-flawed-family/story-MrcouizWr8HnfacmV6j8JM.html |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rachit Gupta of ''Filmfare'' described the film as a \"spunky comedy, straight from the heart\", attributing the performances of the lead actors as the prime reason for the film's success.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gupta |first=Rachit |url=https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9417.html |title=Movie Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |date=5 June 2015 |work=Filmfare |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606204643/http://www.filmfare.com/reviews/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9417.html |archive-date=6 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sonia Chopra from [[Sify]] also gave 3.5 stars, calling ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' a film with a \"robust heartbeat\", admiring Akhtar's ability to create \"real and interesting\" characters and writing, \"Zoya Akhtar brings in several delightful elements of her filmmaking style&nbsp;- there's the gorgeous cast playing interesting characters, the overt and covert equations between them, the hints at societal hypocrisy and sexism, the romance, the gorgeous locales, and the measured pace\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-this-one-has-a-robust-heartbeat-review-bollywood-pgfluOgdbdajb.html |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' review: This one has a robust heartbeat! |last=Chopra, Sonia |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720141746/http://www.sify.com/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-this-one-has-a-robust-heartbeat-review-bollywood-pgfluOgdbdajb.html |archive-date=20 July 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFilm critic [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-News18]] gave 3 stars, appreciating the performances of the lead actors&nbsp;- especially that of Kapoor and Shah&nbsp;- calling them \"absolutely riveting\". He praised the humour in the screenplay and concluded that the film is \"easy and breezy, and packed with terrific actors who appear to be enjoying themselves\", although he criticised the pacing and climax of the film, calling it \"silly\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-its-easy-and-breezy-and-packed-with-terrific-actors-1002090.html |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' review: It's easy and breezy, and packed with terrific actors |last=Masand |first=Rajeev |date=6 June 2015 |publisher=CNN-News18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607175850/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-its-easy-and-breezy-and-packed-with-terrific-actors-1002090.html |archive-date=7 June 2015 |access-date=6 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a 3 star review, film critic [[Mayank Shekhar]] of [[ABP News]] said that \"patiently drawing out emotions from every character\" made the film \"horrendously long [and] too languidly paced\", although he called the film \"\"intensely real, intrinsically adult, with several sharp observations about relationships and life\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abplive.in/author/mayankshekhar/2015/06/05/article609308.ece/FILM-REVIEW---Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Long-languid-but-intensely-real--likeable |title=Film review: Dil Dhadakne Do: Long, languid, but intensely real & likeable |last=Shekhar |first=Mayank |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=[[ABP News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606033318/http://www.abplive.in/author/mayankshekhar/2015/06/05/article609308.ece/FILM-REVIEW---Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Long-languid-but-intensely-real--likeable |archive-date=6 June 2015 |access-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Scoring the film 3 stars, Sukanya Verma of [[Rediff.com]] wrote that ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' \"unravels like an entire season of soap opera condensed into a nearly three-hour movie\", but found it \"too facile to rise above the charming fluff\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-charming-fluff/20150605.htm |title=Review: Dil Dhadakne Do is charming fluff |last=Verma |first=Sukanya |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606080845/http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-charming-fluff/20150605.htm |archive-date=6 June 2015 |access-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRitika Bhatia of ''[[Business Standard]]'' wrote that the film \"does have its enjoyable moments, but with a three-hour runtime, it fails to sail the high seas\", and termed the film \"ambitious\" but \"meandering\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bhatia |first=Ritika |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-a-meandering-tale-of-luxe-angst-115060500612_1.html |title=Movie Review: Dil Dhadakne Do is a meandering tale of luxe angst |date=5 June 2015 |work=Business Standard |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605233716/http://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-a-meandering-tale-of-luxe-angst-115060500612_1.html |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shilpa Jamkhandikar of [[Reuters]] called it \"Akhtar's weakest film yet, because she tries to tell too many stories at once and tells none entirely\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2015/06/05/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Movie Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Jamkhandikar |first=Shilpa |date=5 June 2015 |website=[[Reuters]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809031115/http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2015/06/05/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=9 August 2016 |access-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sarita A. Tanwar of ''[[Daily News and Analysis]]'' gave the film 2.5 stars, and said it would have \"been a lot of fun [if] had it been shorter, crisper and less indulgent\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tanwar |first=Sarita A |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-dil-dhadakne-do-review-would-have-been-more-fun-had-it-been-shorter-crisper-and-less-indulgent-2092582 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do review: Would have been more fun had it been shorter, crisper and less indulgent |date=5 June 2015 |work=Daily News and Analysis |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605233259/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-dil-dhadakne-do-review-would-have-been-more-fun-had-it-been-shorter-crisper-and-less-indulgent-2092582 |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Box office ==\n''Dil Dhadakne Do'' had a decent opening, with collections of {{INR}}100&nbsp;million on its opening day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1348 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do First Day Business |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820073749/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1348 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Collections rose 20% on its second day, collecting {{INR}}120 million, and another 20% on its third day, with collections of {{INR}}140 million for the opening domestic weekend of {{INR}}360&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1353 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do First Weekend Business |date=8 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820033155/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1353 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Upon its release, the film recorded the highest overseas opening of the year for an Indian film, collecting {{INR}}195&nbsp;million in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1356 |title=Top Overseas Openings \u2013 Dil Dhadakne Do Tops |date=8 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074003/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1356 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNotably, the film debuted at number 9 at the U.K. Box Office, where it earned $330,000 in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-empire-strikes-801505 |title=U.K. Box Office: 'Empire Strikes Back' Returns to Top 10 |last=Alex Ritman |date=June 10, 2015 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610132619/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-empire-strikes-801505 |archive-date=10 June 2015 |access-date=June 10, 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The total worldwide opening weekend collections stood at {{INR}}675&nbsp;million, making it the top worldwide opener among Indian films at the time of its release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1355 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Is Top Worldwide Opener of 2015 |date=8 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074334/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1355 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On its first Monday, the film's collections dropped 40%, earning another {{INR}}57.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1359 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do First Monday Business |date=9 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820033154/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1359 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It earned {{INR}}550 million in its first week at the domestic box office and over {{INR}}980&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"second\" /> In its second weekend, ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' earned {{INR}}100&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"second\" /> During its theatrical run, the film grossed over {{INR}}1 billion in India and a further {{INR}}450 million worldwide, for a worldwide total of {{INR}}1.45&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"boi\" />\n\n== Accolades ==\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Dil Dhadakne Do}}\n''Dil Dhadakne Do'' received a number of accolades, particularly for the actors. It earned five [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare]] nominations, winning [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/nominations-for-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11809.html |title=Nominations for the 61st Britannia Filmfare Awards |date=11 January 2016 |work=Filmfare |access-date=11 January 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6gO32fdDO?url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/nominations-for-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11809.html |archive-date=30 March 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/full-list-of-winners-of-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11841.html |title=Full list of winners of the 61st Britannia Filmfare Awards |date=15 January 2016 |work=Filmfare |access-date=16 January 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316165017/http://www.filmfare.com/news/full-list-of-winners-of-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11841.html |archive-date=16 March 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was nominated in nine categories at the 2016 [[Screen Awards]], including [[Screen Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[Screen Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Akhtar and [[Screen Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Chopra. It went on to win two; [[Screen Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor and the [[Screen Awards|Best Ensemble Cast]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9544 |title=Winners of 22nd Annual Star Screen Awards 2015 |date=8 January 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330050107/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9544 |archive-date=30 March 2016 |access-date=10 January 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hotstar.com/tv/star-screen-awards/7050/main-awards-ceremony/1000082990 |title=22 Star Screen Awards |publisher=[[Hotstar]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317213510/http://www.hotstar.com/tv/star-screen-awards/7050/main-awards-ceremony/1000082990 |archive-date=17 March 2016 |access-date=26 January 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the 2015 [[Stardust Awards]], the film garnered five nominations, including [[Stardust Award for Star of the Year \u2013 Female|Actor of the Year \u2013 Female]] for Chopra and [[Stardust Award for Star of the Year \u2013 Male|Actor of the Year \u2013 Male]] for Singh, winning three awards: [[Stardust Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor, [[Stardust Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for Shah and Best Costume Design.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9423 |title=Nominations for Stardust Awards 2015 |date=15 December 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330050312/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9423 |archive-date=30 March 2016 |access-date=20 December 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ghosh, Raya |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/stardust-awards-2016-complete-list-of-winners-1257753 |title=Stardust Awards 2016: Complete List of Winners |date=22 December 2016 |access-date=11 February 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125200252/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/stardust-awards-2016-complete-list-of-winners-1257753 |archive-date=25 January 2016 |publisher=NDTV |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"boi\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=2879 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615001344/http://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=2879 |archive-date=15 June 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cast&crew\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/dil-dhadakne-do/cast/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Cast & Crew |publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828233747/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/dil-dhadakne-do/cast/ |archive-date=28 August 2017 |access-date=28 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"castingnews1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/kareena-ranbir-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next/story-uUAKLDAq1Dx4F5KUHQEJlK.html |title=Kareena, Ranbir in Zoya Akhtar's next |date=8 May 2012 |website=[[Hindustan Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821003247/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/kareena-ranbir-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next/story-uUAKLDAq1Dx4F5KUHQEJlK.html |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 20