ate=15 April 2015 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819232853/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer-praised-by-stars-special-mention-for-anil-kapoor-755428 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"midday\">{{Cite news |last=Shetty-Saha |first=Shubha |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/dil-dhadakne-do---movie-review/16265195 |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' \u2013 Movie Review |date=4 June 2015 |work=Mid Day |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605142508/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/dil-dhadakne-do---movie-review/16265195 |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"second\">{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1375 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Second Weekend Business |date=15 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074332/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1375 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|4110568|Dil Dhadkane Do}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|dil_dhadakne_do}}\n* {{Mojo title|dildhadaknedo}}\n\n{{Zoya Akhtar}}\n{{Farhan Akhtar}}\n{{Ritesh Sidhwani}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Seafaring films]]\n[[Category:Films about vacationing]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about couples]]\n[[Category:Films set on ships]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Zoya Akhtar]]\n[[Category:Reliance Entertainment films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2015 film by Zoya Akhtar}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dil Dhadakne Do\n| image          = Dil Dhadakne Do poster.jpg\n| alt            = Dil Dhadakne Do poster featuring the lead actors.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Zoya Akhtar]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Ritesh Sidhwani]]\n*[[Farhan Akhtar]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Reema Kagti]]\n*Zoya Akhtar\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Anil Kapoor]]\n*[[Shefali Shah]]\n*[[Priyanka Chopra]]\n*[[Ranveer Singh]]\n*[[Anushka Sharma]]\n*[[Farhan Akhtar]]\n}}\n| narrator       = [[Aamir Khan]]\n| music          = [[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]]\n| cinematography = Carlos Catalan\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n*Anand Subaya\n*Manan Mehta\n}}\n| studio         = [[Excel Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Eros International]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2015|06|05}}\n| runtime        = 173 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/dil-dhadakne-do-film |title=''Dil Dhadakne Do'' (2015) |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928050116/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/dil-dhadakne-do-film |archive-date=28 September 2015 |access-date=27 September 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}830&nbsp;million<ref name=\"boi\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=2879 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615001344/http://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=2879 |archive-date=15 June 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{INR}}1.45&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"boi\" />\n}}\n'''''Dil Dhadakne Do''''' ({{translation|Let the heart beat}}) is a 2015 Indian [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Zoya Akhtar]], and produced by [[Ritesh Sidhwani]] and [[Farhan Akhtar]]. The film features an [[ensemble cast]] of [[Anil Kapoor]], [[Shefali Shah]], [[Priyanka Chopra]], [[Ranveer Singh]], [[Anushka Sharma]] and [[Farhan Akhtar]], with a voice-over performance by [[Aamir Khan]] as the family dog Pluto, the narrator of the film. The supporting cast also includes [[Rahul Bose]], [[Zarina Wahab]], [[Vikrant Massey]], [[Pawan Chopra]], [[Parmeet Sethi]], [[Dolly Minhas|Dolly Mattdo]] and [[Manoj Pahwa]]. The film tells the story of the Mehras, a dysfunctional [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] family who invite their family and friends on a cruise trip to celebrate the parents' 30th wedding anniversary and later reconcile.\n\nAkhtar conceived the film as a family drama centred on a brother-sister relationship. She wanted to depict a more realistic sibling relationship in contrast to the dubious and over-the-top portrayal for which [[Bollywood]] is known. Akhtar later co-wrote the screenplay with her friend and longtime collaborator [[Reema Kagti]]. Much of the [[principal photography]] was done on [[Pullmantur Cruises]]' ship [[MS Sovereign|MS ''Sovereign'']] while sailing across the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] and [[Europe]], and on land in France, Spain, Tunisia, Turkey and Italy.\n\nThe soundtrack was composed by the trio [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]], with lyrics by [[Javed Akhtar]]. The film was released worldwide on 5 June 2015 to positive reviews from critics, who praised the performances of Kapoor, Shah, Chopra and Singh, who portrayed the members of the Mehra family, as well as Akhtar's direction, cinematography and costumes. The film grossed {{INR}}1.45 billion at the box office against a budget of {{INR}}830&nbsp;million, and earned a [[List of accolades received by Dil Dhadakne Do|number of accolades]]. It received five [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare]] nominations, winning [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor. ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' also received nine nominations at the 2016 [[Screen Awards]], including [[Screen Award for Best Film|Best Film]], and won two, [[Screen Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor and [[Screen Awards|Best Ensemble Cast]].\n\n== Plot ==\n\nKamal Mehra is a millionaire businessman who owns AyKa, a company on the verge of bankruptcy. He has a troubled relationship with his wife Neelam, daughter Ayesha and son Kabir. The Mehra family also includes their pet dog, Pluto. Ayesha owns a successful business but is unhappy with her marriage to Manav Sangha, a controlling, narcissistic husband who, together with his mother Smita hates Ayesha's family. Kabir, who yearns to become a pilot, unwillingly participates in the family business. Kamal and Neelam invite their family and friends for a ten-day cruise across the Mediterranean to celebrate their 30th wedding anniversary. Their guests include the Sood family, consisting of businessman Lalit Sood, his wife Naina and their daughter Noori. Kamal and Neelam plan to get Kabir married to Noori in exchange for Lalit investing in AyKa.\n\nThe Mehra family and all of their guests board the cruise ship in Italy. Kabir meets Farah, a dancer, and begins a relationship with her. Noori is in love with Rana Khanna, the son of Vinod and Vandana. The Khannas, however, are sworn enemies of the Soods, so Kabir and Noori decide to manipulate their parents into believing they are dating each other while continuing with their respective relationships. Ayesha considers divorcing her husband, whom she believes is incompatible with her. Her parents are staunchly against it, believing it will dishonour the family. Meanwhile, Sunny Gill, the son of Kamal's manager Amrish, arrives on the ship. Sunny and Ayesha dated each other as teenagers. Kamal, who was unhappy with their relationship, arranged and paid for Sunny's [[Yale University]] tuition to separate him from Ayesha. Ayesha realises that she still harbours feelings for Sunny, now a successful journalist. Unlike Manav, Sunny appreciates Ayesha's strong personality and believes in female empowerment.\n\nNeelam sees Kamal flirting with one of the female guests and wonders why she did not divorce him despite his past infidelities. Ayesha confronts Sunny about his sudden departure and kisses him, which she later regrets because she is married. Meanwhile, Farah hears that Kabir is planning to marry Noori and ends their relationship. Elsewhere, Kamal sees Noori making out with Rana and has a fit, after which he is rushed to the onboard emergency room. At the clinic, Kamal tells Kabir he saw Noori with Rana and asks him to end his relationship with her. Kabir tells his family he knew about the couple's relationship and that he is in love with Farah. He also tells them he intends to leave the family business and asks them to consider Ayesha, who is actually interested in business. He also tries to persuade them to let her proceed with her divorce as she is unhappy with the marriage, but Kamal and Neelam still refuse, believing marriages are lifelong commitments. Infuriated, Kabir tells Kamal that he, Neelam and Ayesha were all aware of his adultery and that Neelam has been bearing his infidelities and suffering silently to save the family. Kamal asks Neelam why she had not divorced him; she reveals she had no choice because her family would not accept her back due to their fear of dishonour. Kamal realises his mistake, asks for Neelam's forgiveness and consoles her. Later, while trying to reconcile Manav and Ayesha, Kamal sees how Manav mistreats his daughter and asks him and Smita to leave. He agrees to the divorce and asks Ayesha for forgiveness.\n\nKabir tries to persuade Farah to forgive him for lying to her, but she is dismissed from her job for being involved with a passenger and is told to leave the ship. Kabir learns about her dismissal after the ship has set sail from the port where it had docked for some time. Seeing no other option, Kabir, aided by Sunny, jumps off the ship, hoping his family will rescue him and help him get ashore. Kamal, Neelam, Ayesha, and Pluto eventually find a lifeboat to rescue him. While leaving, Ayesha asks Sunny if he would wait for her, to which he replies \"forever\". The family rescue Kabir and head towards the shore while being chased by the ship's crew. The Mehra family is seen happy in each other's presence for the first time.\n\n== Cast ==\nThe cast is listed below:<ref name=\"cast&crew\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/dil-dhadakne-do/cast/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Cast & Crew |publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828233747/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/dil-dhadakne-do/cast/ |archive-date=28 August 2017 |access-date=28 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Anil Kapoor]] as Kamal Mehra\n* [[Shefali Shah]] as Neelam Mehra\n* [[Priyanka Chopra]] as Ayesha Sangha\n* [[Ranveer Singh]] as Kabir Mehra\n* [[Anushka Sharma]] as Farah Ali\n* [[Farhan Akhtar]] as Sunny Gill\n* [[Aamir Khan]] in a [[voice-over]] as Pluto Mehra/[[Narrator]]\n* [[Rahul Bose]] as Manav Sangha\n* [[Zarina Wahab]] as Smita Sangha\n* [[Vikrant Massey]] as Ranjeev \"Rana\" Khanna\n* Ridhima Sud as Noorie Sood\n* [[Pawan Chopra]] as Prem Mehra\n* Ayesha Raza Mishra as Indu Mehra\n* [[Parmeet Sethi]] as Lalit Sood\n* [[Dolly Minhas]] as Naina Sood\n* [[Manoj Pahwa]] as Vinod Khanna\n* Preeti Mamgain as Vandana Khanna\n* Shireesh Sharma as Jamaal Hashmi\n* [[Divya Seth]] as Saira Hashmi\n* Ikhlaque Khan as Amrish Gill\n* Vandana Sajnani as Anju Chopra\n* Sarah Hashmi as Divya Mehra\n* [[Khushi Dubey]] as Putlu Mehra\n* [[Ivan Sylvester Rodrigues]] as Dharmapala Sr.\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Zoya at audio release of Talaash.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of Zoya Akhtar smiling, looking towards the camera|[[Zoya Akhtar]] had always intended to make a family drama with a brother-sister relationship as its core narrative]]\n\nWhen [[Excel Entertainment]] announced its upcoming films in March 2012, one of them was Zoya Akhtar's next film following ''[[Zindagi Na Milegi Dobara]]'' (2011). It was reported that she was working on a script and that filming was due to start in December 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/1423876 |title=Farhan and Ritesh announce Excel's line-up |date=20 March 2012 |publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519185814/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/1423876 |archive-date=19 May 2016 |access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> Akhtar dismissed the reports, saying she was yet to start writing her next script.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/yet-to-write-my-next-film-so-not-decided-about-cast-zoya-akhtar/925991/ |title=Yet to write my next film, so not decided about cast: Zoya Akhtar |date=20 March 2012 |website=[[The Indian Express]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502204821/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/yet-to-write-my-next-film-so-not-decided-about-cast-zoya-akhtar/925991/ |archive-date=2 May 2016 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May that year, media reports suggested Akhtar was already writing her next film.<ref name=\"castingnews1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/kareena-ranbir-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next/story-uUAKLDAq1Dx4F5KUHQEJlK.html |title=Kareena, Ranbir in Zoya Akhtar's next |date=8 May 2012 |website=[[Hindustan Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821003247/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/kareena-ranbir-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next/story-uUAKLDAq1Dx4F5KUHQEJlK.html |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017}}</ref> That July, it was reported the script was about siblings partially based on Akhtar and her brother Farhan Akhtar.<ref name=\"castingnews2\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Kareena-Ranbir-to-play-reel-life-brother-and-sister/articleshow/15140463.cms |title=Kareena & Ranbir to play reel-life brother and siste |last=Iyer, Meena |date=26 July 2012 |website=[[The Times of India]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519193219/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Kareena-Ranbir-to-play-reel-life-brother-and-sister/articleshow/15140463.cms |archive-date=19 May 2016 |access-date=19 May 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Farhan Akhtar later denied reports of the film being autobiographical, saying it had nothing to do with their real life relationship and that it is entirely a work of fiction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/zoya-s-film-has-nothing-to-do-with-our-real-life-farhan-interview-113120900878_1.html |title=Zoya's film has nothing to do with our real life: Farhan (Interview) |last=[[Indo-Asian News Service]] |date=9 December 2013 |website=[[Business Standard]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519194413/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/zoya-s-film-has-nothing-to-do-with-our-real-life-farhan-interview-113120900878_1.html |archive-date=19 May 2016 |access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> In November 2012, Akhtar said she was still writing the script and that the film was a family drama.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/zoya-akhtar-is-scripting-a-family-drama-now-522611.html |title=Zoya Akhtar is scripting a family drama now |date=20 November 2012 |publisher=[[CNN-News18]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821004112/http://www.news18.com/news/india/zoya-akhtar-is-scripting-a-family-drama-now-522611.html |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar co-wrote the screenplay with her long-time friend and collaborator [[Reema Kagti]].<ref name=\"sibling1\">{{Cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/brother-sister-bond-not-represented-well-in-bollywood-zoya-akhtar/articleshow/47574456.cms |title=Brother-sister bond not represented well in Bollywood: Zoya Akhtar |last=[[Press Trust of India]] |date=7 June 2015 |website=[[The Economic Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519181747/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/brother-sister-bond-not-represented-well-in-bollywood-zoya-akhtar/articleshow/47574456.cms |archive-date=19 May 2016 |access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> Akhtar had always aspired to make a family drama with a brother-sister relationship at its core.<ref name=\"sibling2\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-wanted-to-show-brother-sister-relationship-in-dil-dhadakne-do-769508 |title=Zoya Akhtar: Wanted to Show Brother-Sister Relationship in Dil Dhadakne Do |last=[[Indo-Asian News Service]] |date=7 June 2015 |publisher=[[NDTV]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519182151/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-wanted-to-show-brother-sister-relationship-in-dil-dhadakne-do-769508 |archive-date=19 May 2016 |access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> She felt such topics not been well represented in Indian films,<ref name=\"sibling2\" /> and that the brother-sister relationship bond has always been shown \"wrapped in rituals\" and never portrayed as it really is. She believed the theme of brother-sister relationships \"generally have cheesy representations. They are never at ease. This is one of the most important relationships in the world because nobody else shares your parents. I wanted to show that relationship in ''Dil Dhadakne Do''\".<ref name=\"sibling1\" /><ref name=\"sibling2\" /> Akhtar also wanted to showcase the quirkiness of a dysfunctional family, with different layers to each family member, saying, \"the beauty of families lies in their flaws\".<ref name=\"different\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/The-Mehras-are-very-different-than-the-Akhtars-Zoya-Akhtar/articleshow/47386105.cms |title=The Mehras are very different than the Akhtars: Zoya Akhtar |last=Gupta, Priya |date=23 May 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827195440/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/The-Mehras-are-very-different-than-the-Akhtars-Zoya-Akhtar/articleshow/47386105.cms |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"device\">{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/i-dont-think-any-family-is-normal-says-dil-dhadakne-do-director-zoya-akhtar/ |title=I don't think any family is normal, says 'Dil Dhadakne Do' director Zoya Akhtar |last=Sahani, Alaska |date=7 June 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821003127/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/i-dont-think-any-family-is-normal-says-dil-dhadakne-do-director-zoya-akhtar/ |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked whether the film had any similarities with her own life and family, she said it had none and that the only thing common to herself and the film's characters was the bond between her and her brother; all their problems and conflicts were unalike.<ref name=\"different\" /> Akhtar said the film was a partly fictionalised version of people around her, such as her friends and their families, and her observations from literature and news articles.<ref name=\"fc\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmcompanion.in/article/zoya-akhtar-and-reema-kagti-dil-dhadakne-do-post-mortem |title=Zoya Akhtar & Reema Kagti \u2013 Dil Dhadakne Do \u2013 FC Post Mortem |last=Chopra, Anupama |date=15 June 2015 |publisher=Film Companion |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821005950/http://www.filmcompanion.in/article/zoya-akhtar-and-reema-kagti-dil-dhadakne-do-post-mortem |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"rich\">{{Cite web |url=https://scroll.in/article/731293/the-zoya-akhtar-interview-are-my-movies-about-rich-people-what-does-that-mean |title=The Zoya Akhtar interview: 'Are my movies about rich people? What does that mean?' |last=Pal, Chandrima |date=1 June 2015 |publisher=Scroll.in |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602214309/http://scroll.in/article/731293/the-zoya-akhtar-interview-are-my-movies-about-rich-people-what-does-that-mean |archive-date=2 June 2015 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Kagti and Akhtar revealed that some of their material came from observing people of [[Delhi]] during their friends' back-to-back, elite-class wedding parties as they were finishing the script; they made notes about people's behaviour and demeanor, and incorporated these into their script.<ref name=\"fc\" /> After finalising the characters, they felt something was missing, so they added Pluto, the family dog, as an observer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/why-aamir-khan-was-chosen-for-the-voice-of-pluto-in-dil-dhadakne-do/article7298285.ece |title=A voice from afar |last=Devi Dundoo, Sangeetha |date=9 June 2015 |website=[[The Hindu]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113074052/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/why-aamir-khan-was-chosen-for-the-voice-of-pluto-in-dil-dhadakne-do/article7298285.ece |archive-date=13 January 2018 |access-date=20 August 2017}}</ref> The completed film has 25 characters and a dog.<ref name=\"rich\" />\n\nWhen asked about interweaving travel in the narrative, Akhtar said she and Kagti wanted a device to bring all the characters\u2014the entire family\u2014together.<ref name=\"device\" /> She said the film could have been set anywhere, such as a hill station, but they chose to set it on a cruise ship because the characters would not be able to leave.<ref name=\"device\" /><ref name=\"metaphor\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/it-took-aamir-khan-to-go-and-convince-anil-kapoor-for-dil-dhadakne-do-zoya-akhtar/ |title=\"It took Aamir Khan to go and convince Anil Kapoor for Dil Dhadakne Do\" \u2013 Zoya Akhtar |last=Jha, Subhash K. |date=1 June 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821004536/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/it-took-aamir-khan-to-go-and-convince-anil-kapoor-for-dil-dhadakne-do-zoya-akhtar/ |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Akhtar called it a metaphor for the bigger journey that every family undertakes; the characters are stuck together on a ship in the middle of an ocean and could not leave if they wanted to.<ref name=\"metaphor\" /> The film's title ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' was chosen because Akhtar wanted a catchy, easily identifiable title.<ref name=\"metaphor\" />\n\n=== Casting and characters ===\nDuring the initial scripting phase, in May 2012, media reports suggested cousins [[Kareena Kapoor]] and [[Ranbir Kapoor]] had been approached to play the siblings and had accepted the parts.<ref name=castingnews1 /><ref name=\"castingnews2\" /> In late December 2012, [[Hrithik Roshan]] and [[Katrina Kaif]] joined the cast to play the Kapoors' characters' love interests respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hrithik-kareena-katrina-and-ranveer-to-star-in-zoya-akhtars-next-film-464762 |title=Hrithik, Kareena, Katrina and Ranveer to Star in Zoya Akhtar's Next Film? |date=6 May 2013 |website=[[International Business Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825233411/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hrithik-kareena-katrina-and-ranveer-to-star-in-zoya-akhtars-next-film-464762 |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In June 2013, Ranbir Kapoor dropped out of the film due to scheduling conflicts with his other projects; he was replaced by [[Ranveer Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ranveer-singh-set-to-replace-ranbir-kapoor/story-MFVgr8dEtYf5adLJYWZqEI.html |title=Ranveer Singh set to replace Ranbir Kapoor? |last=Singh, Prashant |date=8 June 2013 |website=Hindustan Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825232507/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ranveer-singh-set-to-replace-ranbir-kapoor/story-MFVgr8dEtYf5adLJYWZqEI.html |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was then reported that after her cousin dropped out, Kareena Kapoor was having second thoughts about appearing in the film; the opportunity to act alongside her cousin had been the main attraction for her.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Kareena-Hrithik-and-Ranbir-Katrina-in-Zoyas-next-film/articleshow/17791145.cms |title=Kareena-Hrithik and Ranbir-Katrina in Zoya's next film |last=Thakkar, Mehul S |date=28 December 2012 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171509/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Kareena-Hrithik-and-Ranbir-Katrina-in-Zoyas-next-film/articleshow/17791145.cms |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> She left the production later that month, saying she could not leave her family for the required three months and calling her decision \"her loss\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kareena-kapoor-zoya-akhtar-dil-dhadakne-do-singham-returns/1/373891.html |title=Not doing Zoya's film is my loss, says Kareena Kapoor |date=24 July 2014 |website=India Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113074059/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/kareena-kapoor-zoya-akhtar-dil-dhadakne-do-singham-returns-201554-2014-07-24 |archive-date=13 January 2018 |access-date=25 August 2017}}</ref> In late June 2013, Akhtar approached [[Priyanka Chopra]] to part that role, and Chopra accepted.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/priyanka-chopra-to-play-ranveer-singhs-elder-sister_137376.html |title=Priyanka Chopra to play Ranveer Singh's elder sister? |date=22 June 2013 |publisher=[[Zee News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825225618/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/priyanka-chopra-to-play-ranveer-singhs-elder-sister_137376.html |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October, [[Anil Kapoor]] was confirmed to play the role of Chopra and Singh's father in the film. It was also reported that [[Dimple Kapadia]] could possibly play his wife, but this was not to be,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/videos/anil-kapoor-to-portray-father-to-grown-up-children-293049 |title=Anil Kapoor to portray father to grown up children |date=3 October 2013 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827130920/http://movies.ndtv.com/videos/anil-kapoor-to-portray-father-to-grown-up-children-293049 |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Farhan Akhtar confirmed he was playing a crucial role in his sister's film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/2267291 |title=Farhan Akhtar in sister Zoya's film |date=3 December 2013 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208045904/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/news/type/view/id/2267291 |archive-date=8 December 2013 |access-date=23 February 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2014, [[Anushka Sharma]] was cast for the role of Singh's love interest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-anushka-to-romance-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next_150059.html |title=Ranveer, Anushka to romance in Zoya Akhtar's next? |date=31 January 2014 |publisher=Zee News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825232744/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-anushka-to-romance-in-zoya-akhtar-s-next_150059.html |archive-date=25 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Madhuri Dixit]], [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]] and [[Raveena Tandon]] were all approached to play Chopra and Singh's mother in the film; although they liked the part, all of them turned down the role because they did not want to play a mother.<ref name=\"mother\">{{Cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/raveena-tandon-ranveer-singh-dil-dhadakane-do-zoya-akhtar/1/361800.html |title=When Raveena Tandon refused to play Ranveer Singh's mother |date=14 May 2014 |website=India Today |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517030656/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/raveena-tandon-ranveer-singh-dil-dhadakane-do-zoya-akhtar/1/361800.html |archive-date=17 May 2014 |access-date=31 May 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Akhtar later approached [[Shefali Shah]] for the part, which she accepted.<ref name=\"mother\" /> Newcomer Ridhima Sud joined the cast in June 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-to-launch-newbie-ridhima-sud-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Zoya Akhtar to launch newbie Ridhima Sud in Dil Dhadakne Do |date=19 June 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827173923/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-to-launch-newbie-ridhima-sud-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A few days later, [[Rahul Bose]] was cast to play the role of Manav (Chopra's husband) in the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/rahul-bose-joins-the-starcast-of-zoyas-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Rahul Bose joins the starcast of Zoya's Dil Dhadakne Do |date=21 June 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827174046/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/rahul-bose-joins-the-starcast-of-zoyas-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Zarina Wahab]] joined the cast to play Chopra's mother-in-law.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zarina-wahab-plays-priyankas-mother-in-law-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Zarina Wahab plays Priyanka's mother-in-law in Dil Dhadakne Do |date=23 July 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827173339/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zarina-wahab-plays-priyankas-mother-in-law-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Parmeet Sethi]] was later cast in an important role.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-signs-parmeet-sethi-for-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Zoya Akhtar signs Parmeet Sethi for Dil Dhadakne Do |date=2 August 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827173855/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/zoya-akhtar-signs-parmeet-sethi-for-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough meant for a surprise, the details about [[Aamir Khan]]'s voiceover performance as the family dog Pluto was leaked before the film's release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/AK-turns-bullmastiff-for-Zoya/articleshow/47467604.cms |title=AK turns bullmastiff for Zoya |last=Pathak, Ankur |date=29 May 2015 |website=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827205938/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/AK-turns-bullmastiff-for-Zoya/articleshow/47467604.cms |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Javed Akhtar]] had initially provided the voiceover for Pluto. After watching the film weeks before the release, however, Akhtar asked Aamir to do the voiceover and the actor accepted, saying, \"I had loved the film so much that I was just happy to be a part of it&nbsp;...&nbsp;I think it is a great film to be part of\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/didnt-think-twice-before-playing-pluto-the-dog-aamir-khan/ |title=Didn't think twice before playing Pluto the dog: Aamir Khan |last=Indo-Asian News Service |date=8 June 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827172411/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/didnt-think-twice-before-playing-pluto-the-dog-aamir-khan/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCompared with the rest of the cast, Akhtar spent a whole year persuading Anil Kapoor to sign up for the film.<ref name=\"convince\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/it-took-aamir-khan-to-go-and-convince-anil-kapoor-for-dil-dhadakne-do-zoya-akhtar/ |title=\"It took Aamir Khan to go and convince Anil Kapoor for Dil Dhadakne Do\" \u2013 Zoya Akhtar |last=Jha, Subhash K. |date=1 June 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821004536/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/it-took-aamir-khan-to-go-and-convince-anil-kapoor-for-dil-dhadakne-do-zoya-akhtar/ |archive-date=21 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017}}</ref> Akhtar's brother Farhan and father Javed Akhtar also spoke to him about the role. However, when Aamir Khan approached him on Akhtar's behalf, he finally accepted the part.<ref name=convince /> Kapoor described his role of Kamal Mehra as a \"manipulative patriarch\" and a businessman who \"has no qualms about manipulating people, even his own family members, to achieve his goal\".<ref name=\"manipulative\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/anil-kapoor-on-playing-a-manipulative-patriarch-in-dil-dhadakne-do-1.105956 |title=Anil Kapoor on playing a manipulative patriarch in Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Khan, Ujala Ali |date=2 Jun 2015 |website=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828010613/https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/anil-kapoor-on-playing-a-manipulative-patriarch-in-dil-dhadakne-do-1.105956 |archive-date=28 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> He said, \"Kamal is a [[self-made man]] and does not want to lose [his business empire] and will do anything to save it\".<ref name=\"manipulative\" /> Kapoor found playing his character very exciting, being completely opposite to his real self; a patriarch whose company, rather than his family, comes first.<ref name=\"manipulative\" />\n\nShah called her character, Neelam Mehra, a \"Delhi elite society queen bee\" with multiple layers, saying, \"It looks like nothing can put a chink in her armour, but inside, she is a vulnerable and lost person\".<ref name=\"amother\">{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shefali-shah-i-was-21-when-i-played-a-mother/ |title=Shefali Shah: I was 21 when I played a mother |last=Ghosh, Sankhayan |date=13 June 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827172422/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/shefali-shah-i-was-21-when-i-played-a-mother/ |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> She said her character shows an artificial side about her marriage while facing the world, opposed to her behaviour in their home: \"It's not one of the best marriages. She hates what\u2019s happened to both of them. But when they come in front of the world, she will stand by her husband\".<ref name=\"amother\" /> Her character discriminates between her son and her daughter; she said, \"She is evidently partial to her son. With her daughter, she displays a mentality typical of many Indian mothers. Even though her daughter is in a bad marriage as well, she discourages her from taking a divorce.\"<ref name=\"amother\" /> Shah said accepted the part because it \"was one of the best scripts I had read in a very long time. It was sharp, wicked, and emotional, without being melodramatic.\"<ref name=\"screen\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/i-hate-myself-on-screen/20150604.htm |title=I hate myself on screen |last=N, Patcy |date=4 June 2015 |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827171406/http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/i-hate-myself-on-screen/20150604.htm |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> To prepare for her role, she formed an outline of her character by forming Neelam's history and personality.<ref name=\"screen\" />\n\nChopra has described her character, Ayesha Mehra, as strong but also feminine and gentle, noting her inner strength.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/priyanka-i-am-very-greedy-about-my-work/20150601.htm |title=Priyanka: I am very greedy about my work |last=N, Patcy |date=1 June 2015 |publisher=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224054822/http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/priyanka-i-am-very-greedy-about-my-work/20150601.htm |archive-date=24 December 2016 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> She said Ayesha has complicated emotions, and that she \"has no idea what she wants and she keeps changing her mind, probably like most women&nbsp;...&nbsp;that is exactly what Ayesha does. She doesn't know which direction to go in. She actually has no opinion on love or marriage, but just wants to be able to feel that she can be loved.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/priyanka-chopra-and-ranveer-singh-on-the-bittersweet-comedy-dil-dhadakne-do-1.98438 |title=Priyanka Chopra and Ranveer Singh on the bittersweet comedy Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Khan, Ujala Ali |date=2 June 2015 |website=The National |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827212536/https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/priyanka-chopra-and-ranveer-singh-on-the-bittersweet-comedy-dil-dhadakne-do-1.98438 |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Chopra had to shed the muscle weight she gained for playing the boxer in ''[[Mary Kom (film)|Mary Kom]]'' (2014). She said, \"I was not muscular but had acquired bulked-up physique. I had to be in right shape as I was playing a girly role. I had to&nbsp;...&nbsp;go on a crash diet and lose shape.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/post-mary-kom-priyanka-chopra-had-to-tone-down-for-girly-role-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Post 'Mary Kom', Priyanka Chopra had to tone down for 'girly role' in 'Dil Dhadakne Do' |last=[[Press Trust of India]] |date=24 July 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828011206/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/post-mary-kom-priyanka-chopra-had-to-tone-down-for-girly-role-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=28 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Singh called his character, Kabir Mehra, a privileged, \"born with a silver spoon\" kind of person who wants to pursue different things other than inherit his father's fortune.<ref name=\"reveal\">{{Cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ranveer-singh-dil-dhadakne-do-zoya-akhtar-turkey-interview-hurriyet/1/372526.html |title=Did Ranveer Singh reveal the plot of Dil Dhadakne Do? |date=15 July 2014 |website=India Today |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171510/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ranveer-singh-dil-dhadakne-do-zoya-akhtar-turkey-interview-hurriyet/1/372526.html |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> He said, \"Ever since his childhood, he was raised to take over his father's company. But this isn't what he wants to do. He loves planes, he wants to be a pilot. Because of this miscommunication he is in a lot of pain.\"<ref name=\"reveal\" /> Khan described Pluto as a \"very philosophical\" dog who is \"really into observing human nature and has a take on everything\".<ref name=convince />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Pullmantur Cruises Sovereign 04 IMO 8512281 @chesi.JPG|thumb|upright=1.4|alt=A photograph of MS Sovereign|The film was extensively filmed on the [[MS Sovereign|MS ''Sovereign'']]]]\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on 17 May 2014 on the [[Pullmantur Cruises]] ship [[MS Sovereign|MS ''Sovereign'']] throughout the Mediterranean Sea and onshore in France, Spain, Tunisia, Turkey and Italy.<ref name=\"bts\">{{Cite web |url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/ENT-BOW-behind-the-scenes-what-happened-when-dil-dhadakne-do-ship-pullmantur-broke-down-5012393-PHO.html |title=Behind The Scenes: What happened when Dil Dhadakne Do ship Pullmantur broke down? |last=Kulkarni, Onkar |date=4 June 2015 |website=[[Dainik Bhaskar]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171509/http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/ENT-BOW-behind-the-scenes-what-happened-when-dil-dhadakne-do-ship-pullmantur-broke-down-5012393-PHO.html |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"filming\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/dil-dhadakne-do-cast-begin-shooting-in-mumbai/15538190 |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' cast begin shooting in Mumbai |date=18 August 2014 |website=[[Mid Day]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106140122/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/dil-dhadakne-do-cast-begin-shooting-in-mumbai/15538190 |archive-date=6 January 2015 |access-date=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Filming on the ship was done over a non-consecutive period of five weeks; the cast and crew members would board the ship at [[Barcelona]] and would film the scenes while en route to different destinations; five different places in five weeks, where the cast and crew would shoot the onshore scenes.<ref name=\"bts\" /> Onshore filming took two months, finishing on 18 July 2014.<ref name=\"bts\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/a-pleasant-surprise-for-priyanka-chopra/15457163 |title=A birthday surprise for Priyanka Chopra |date=18 July 2014 |website=Mid Day |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729004310/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/a-pleasant-surprise-for-priyanka-chopra/15457163 |archive-date=29 July 2014 |access-date=20 July 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Filming took ninety days, finishing in early August 2014.<ref name=\"filming\" /> The second and final schedule began in mid-August 2014 in [[Mumbai]], and was completed on 23 September 2014.<ref name=\"filming\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/its-a-wrap-for-dil-dhadakne-do-exes-ranveer-anushka-party-with-director-zoya/2/ |title=It's a wrap for Dil Dhadakne Do \u2013 exes Ranveer, Anushka party with director Zoya |date=24 September 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106223212/http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/its-a-wrap-for-dil-dhadakne-do-exes-ranveer-anushka-party-with-director-zoya/2/ |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFilming also took place in several locations in Turkey, such as [[Antalya]], [[Cappadocia]] and [[Istanbul]].<ref name=\"visual\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-dil-dhadakne-do-was-logistically-insane-visually-gorgeous-and-emotionally-cathartic-zoya-akhtar-2086979 |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' was logistically insane, visually gorgeous and emotionally cathartic: Zoya Akhtar |date=18 May 2015 |website=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723004416/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-dil-dhadakne-do-was-logistically-insane-visually-gorgeous-and-emotionally-cathartic-zoya-akhtar-2086979 |archive-date=23 July 2015 |access-date=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> For one scene set in Istanbul's [[Hagia Sophia|Sophia Museum]], tourists and museum staff were used as extras for the sequence, which took six hours to film.<ref name=\"facts\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Some-interesting-facts-from-the-sets-of-Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47573828.cms |title=Some interesting facts from the sets of 'Dil Dhadakne Do' |date=7 June 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010162435/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Some-interesting-facts-from-the-sets-of-Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47573828.cms |archive-date=10 October 2016 |access-date=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> For a sequence featuring Chopra and Bose's characters playing [[Squash (sport)|squash]], Chopra, helped by Bose, had to learn the sport on set.<ref name=\"facts\" /> The pre-production work was a challenge for the makers, who had to plan everything in detail; Akhtar and her team reconnoitred to find perfect places to shoot the film.<ref name=\"visual\" /> Akhtar found the filming unforgettable, saying, \"Can you imagine the whole crew is in a new country everyday! That is what it is like to be on a cruise ship in the Mediterranean. It was logistically insane, visually gorgeous and emotionally cathartic.\"<ref name=\"visual\" />\n\nNeil Patel handled the [[production design]]. Akhtar's frequent collaborator Carlos Catalan provided the cinematography, and Anand Subaya and Manan Mehta edited the film.<ref name=\"cast&crew\" /> [[Arjun Bhasin]] designed all of the film's costumes. [[Bosco\u2013Caesar]] choreographed the songs;<ref name=\"cast&crew\" /> The entire song \"Gallan Goodiyaan\" was shot in a single five-minute take.<ref name=\"onetake\">{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/gallan-goodiyaan-song-from-dil-dhadakne-do-was-shot-in-5-minutes/ |title='Gallan Goodiyaan' song from 'Dil Dhadakne Do' was shot in 5 minutes |date=4 May 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220154525/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/gallan-goodiyaan-song-from-dil-dhadakne-do-was-shot-in-5-minutes/ |archive-date=20 February 2017 |access-date=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It required detailed planning and choreography, which the cast rehearsed before filming it.<ref name=\"onetake\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Dil Dhadakne Do\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n| cover      =\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2015|05|2}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 21:37\n| language   = [[Hindi]]\n| label      = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Kill Dil]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Katti Batti]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n}}\n''Dil Dhadakne Do''{{'s}} soundtrack was composed by the trio [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] and [[Javed Akhtar]] wrote the lyrics. The album consists of five original songs.<ref name=\"bh\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/dil-dhadakne-do/songs/music-critic-review/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Music Review |last=Tuteja, Joginder |date=4 May 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812214131/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/dil-dhadakne-do/songs/music-critic-review/ |archive-date=12 August 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The vocals are performed by Priyanka Chopra, Farhan Akhtar, Sukriti Kakar, Siddharth Mahadevan, Shankar Mahadevan, Yashita Sharma, Manish Kumar Tipu, Sukhwinder Singh, Sunidhi Chauhan, Vishal Dadlani, [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]] and Alyssa Mendonsa. It was released on 2 May 2015 by [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]].<ref name=\"bh\" />\n\nThe soundtrack received generally positive reviews from critics, who labelled it more narrative-based than a chartbuster. Chopra's singing on the first fully-Hindi song she had recorded was also lauded by critics.<ref name=\"bh\" /> Joginder Tuteja of [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave a rating of 3.5 out of 5, describing it as \"a classy soundtrack [that] is unadulterated when it comes to quintessential Bollywood scheme of things\".<ref name=\"bh\" /> ''[[The Times of India]]'' also gave it a rating of 3.5 out of 5, calling the compositions \"foot-tapping and swingy\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47373373.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Fernandes, Kasmin |date=22 May 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818232524/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47373373.cms |archive-date=18 August 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In another positive review, ''[[Filmfare]]'' said the composers had \"done a good job despite the hurdles\", noting the limiting setting of the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/music-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9267.html |title=Music Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Sharma, Devesh |date=22 May 2015 |website=[[Filmfare]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812213528/https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/music-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9267.html |archive-date=12 August 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Koimoi]] rated it 2.5 out of 5, terming it a mixed bag. However, it praised the songs \"Dil Dhadakne Do\" and \"Pehli Baar\", noting them as standouts. The reviewer wrote that Chopra particularly \"impresses with her vocals\" in the former song.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-music-review/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Music Review |last=Redkar, Surabhi |date=30 May 2015 |publisher=[[Koimoi]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528195425/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-movies/music-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-music-review/ |archive-date=28 May 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline            = Track listing<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dil-dhadakne-do-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-ep/id1071191851 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |publisher=[[iTunes]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171509/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dil-dhadakne-do-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-ep/id1071191851 |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| total_length = 21:37\n| extra_column        = Artist(s)\n| title1              = Dil Dhadakne Do\n| extra1              = [[Priyanka Chopra]], [[Farhan Akhtar]]\n| length1             = 03:48\n| title2              = Pehli Baar\n| extra2              = Sukriti Kakar, [[Siddharth Mahadevan]]\n| length2             = 04:23\n| title3              = Gallan Goodiyaan\n| extra3              = [[Shankar Mahadevan]], Yashita Sharma, Manish Kumar Tipu, Farhan Akhtar, [[Sukhwinder Singh]]\n| length3             = 04:56\n| title4              = Girls Like To Swing\n| extra4              = [[Sunidhi Chauhan]]\n| length4             = 04:03\n| title5              = Phir Bhi Yeh Zindagi\n| extra5              = Farhan Akhtar, [[Vishal Dadlani]], [[Divya Kumar (singer)|Divya Kumar]], [[Alyssa Mendonsa]]\n| length5             = 04:27\n}}\n\n== Release ==\n''Dil Dhadakne Do'' was one of the most highly anticipated films of 2015 owing to its star cast and the success of Akhtar's previous film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Hindi/Bollywood/News/Zoya-Akhtars-friends-eagerly-awaiting-Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer/articleshow/46723840.cms |title=Zoya Akhtar's friends eagerly awaiting 'Dil Dhadakne Do' trailer |last=Kotwani, Hiren |date=28 March 2017 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829171509/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Hindi/Bollywood/News/Zoya-Akhtars-friends-eagerly-awaiting-Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer/articleshow/46723840.cms |archive-date=29 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/here-s-why-zoya-akhtar-is-secretive-about-dil-dhadakne-do-trailer/story-ABYfcLyPnAaEtlbK7U6etI.html |title=Here's why Zoya Akhtar is secretive about Dil Dhadakne Do trailer |last=Mangaokar, Shalvi |date=27 March 2015 |website=Hindustan Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819190820/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/here-s-why-zoya-akhtar-is-secretive-about-dil-dhadakne-do-trailer/story-ABYfcLyPnAaEtlbK7U6etI.html |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first-look teaser poster, photographed from behind the six pivotal characters and a dog sunbathing on a cruise deck was released on 21 July 2014, almost a year before the scheduled release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/first-look-ranveer-priyanka-anushka-farhan-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=First look: Ranveer, Priyanka, Anushka, Farhan in 'Dil Dhadakne Do' |last=Divya, Goyal |date=21 July 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819231625/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/first-look-ranveer-priyanka-anushka-farhan-in-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The poster did not reveal the actors' looks, instead making the audience puzzle about the actors from behind.<ref name=\"guess\">{{Cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dil-dhadakne-do-second-poster-ranveer-singh-priyanka-chopra-zoya-akhtar-farhan-akhtar/1/373811.html |title=Dil Dhadakne Do second poster out: Meet the 'pagal parivar' |date=24 July 2014 |website=India Today |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201090304/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dil-dhadakne-do-second-poster-ranveer-singh-priyanka-chopra-zoya-akhtar-farhan-akhtar/1/373811.html |archive-date=1 December 2015 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A few days later, the first full poster revealing the position of the actors photographed from the front was revealed.<ref name=\"guess\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/dil-dhadakne-do-first-look-poster-out/ |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' First Look Poster Out |date=24 July 2014 |publisher=Koimoi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819190514/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/dil-dhadakne-do-first-look-poster-out/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2015, seven character posters, including one for the family dog Pluto, were released. The poster releases generated much hype for the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/dil-dhadakne-do-storyline-first-look-ranveer-anushka-starrer-revealed-photos-628874 |title='Dil Dhadakne Do': Meet Pluto, New Member of Mehra Family [PHOTOS] |last=Goswami, Parismita |date=11 April 2015 |website=International Business Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819190446/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/dil-dhadakne-do-storyline-first-look-ranveer-anushka-starrer-revealed-photos-628874 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The trailer release was highly anticipated in the media because the plot was kept secret.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/farhan-akhtar-watches-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer-but-cant-show-it-to-anybody/ |title=Farhan Akhtar watches 'Dil Dhadakne Do's trailer, but can't show it to anybody |date=9 April 2014 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233049/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/farhan-akhtar-watches-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer-but-cant-show-it-to-anybody/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nEmphasising the theme of the film, Akhtar and Kapoor hosted a private screening of the trailer for their friends and family.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/anil-kapoor-hosted-a-screening-for-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer/ |title=Anil Kapoor Hosted A Screening For Dil Dhadakne Do's Trailer |date=14 April 2015 |publisher=Koimoi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622011038/http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-popular/anil-kapoor-hosted-a-screening-for-dil-dhadakne-dos-trailer/ |archive-date=22 June 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-crew-planning-private-trailer-screening/ |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' crew planning private trailer screening |last=Indo-Asian News Service |date=11 April 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233254/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-crew-planning-private-trailer-screening/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The official theatrical release posters were released before the trailer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-countdown-mehras-embark-on-epic-journey-in-brand-new-posters-755238 |title=Mehras 'Embark on Epic Journey' in Brand New Dil Dhadakne Do Poster |last=Prashar, Chandni |date=15 April 2015 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819231927/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-countdown-mehras-embark-on-epic-journey-in-brand-new-posters-755238 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The almost-three-minute official trailer was released on 15 April 2015, garnering over one million views in less than 24 hours.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2015/04/15/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer_n_7070640.html |title=Watch: Star-Studded 'Dil Dhadakne Do' Trailer Features Generous Helpings Of Family Dysfunction |last=Chatterjee, Suprateek |date=15 April 2015 |website=[[HuffPost]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819232558/http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2015/04/15/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer_n_7070640.html |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"trailer\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer-praised-by-stars-special-mention-for-anil-kapoor-755428 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Trailer Praised by Stars; Special Mention For Anil Kapoor |last=Press Trust of India |date=15 April 2015 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819232853/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer-praised-by-stars-special-mention-for-anil-kapoor-755428 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The trailer was well received by the media, who deemed it promising.<ref name=\"trailer\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer-Anushka-Sharma-Ranveer-Singh-Priyanka-Chopra-steal-the-show/articleshow/46937819.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do trailer: Anushka Sharma, Ranveer Singh, Priyanka Chopra steal the show |last=Kaushal, Ruchi |date=15 April 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423145053/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-trailer-Anushka-Sharma-Ranveer-Singh-Priyanka-Chopra-steal-the-show/articleshow/46937819.cms |archive-date=23 April 2015 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Alaka Sahani of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' called it \"overwhelming\" and wrote, \"The top-view of the cruise line with expansive ocean as the backdrop, stunning foreign locales and beautiful people in their stylish best make for compelling visuals. But scratch the surface, and you find a dysfunctional family trying hard to act normal to the world.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer-feel-the-heartbeat/ |title=Watch Priyanka, Ranveer, Anushka's 'Dil Dhadakne Do' trailer: Feel the heartbeat |last=Sahani, Alaka |date=15 April 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819233231/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/dil-dhadakne-do-trailer-feel-the-heartbeat/ |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was released on 5 June 2015 in 2,300 screens worldwide on a budget of {{INR}}830&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"boi\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/todays-big-release-dil-dhadakne-do-768897 |title=Today's Big Release: Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Prashar, Chandni |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819232943/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/todays-big-release-dil-dhadakne-do-768897 |archive-date=19 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to an analysis by [[Box Office India]], the film was likely to perform better in [[Metropolitan cities of India|major Indian cities]] than in smaller centres, but predicted it would perform much better overseas due to its niche content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1340 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Looking Good For Big Metros |date=4 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820073745/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1340 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Distributed by [[Reliance Entertainment|Big Home Entertainment]], it was released on [[DVD]] in all [[DVD region code|regions]] on 30 August 2015 as a two-disc pack in [[NTSC]] widescreen format; bonus content included the making of the film and deleted scenes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.in/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Ranveer-Singh/dp/B013E4EYNC |title=Dil Dhadakne Do DVD |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820034156/http://www.amazon.in/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Ranveer-Singh/dp/B013E4EYNC |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A [[VCD]] version was released at the same time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Blu-ray/138254/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Blu-ray |publisher=Blu-ray |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820073746/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Blu-ray/138254/ |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film's Blu-ray version was released on 5 September 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.induna.com/1000021199-productdetails/ |title=Dil Dhadakne Do VCD |publisher=[[Induna.com|Induna]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160210091133/http://www.induna.com/1000021199-productdetails/ |archive-date=10 February 2016 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' had its Indian television premiere on 24 October 2015 on [[Zee Cinema]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-to-have-a-grand-world-television-premiere/articleshow/49507077.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do to have a grand world television premiere |date=24 October 2015 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827092024/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Dil-Dhadakne-Do-to-have-a-grand-world-television-premiere/articleshow/49507077.cms |archive-date=27 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe film received positive reviews, receiving praise for the cast performances, humour, cinematography, costumes and direction, but it received criticism for its running time and climax.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmfare.com/news/dil-dhadakne-do-has-a-fantastic-weekend-9445.html |title=Dil Dhadakne Do has a fantastic weekend |date=8 June 2015 |website=Filmfare |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701155819/http://www.filmfare.com/news/dil-dhadakne-do-has-a-fantastic-weekend-9445.html |archive-date=1 July 2017 |access-date=27 October 2017}}</ref> In a 4-star review for ''[[Mumbai Mirror]]'', critic Kunal Guha described the film as an \"emotional roller-coaster\", comparing Akhtar's direction to that of [[Woody Allen]] and [[Wes Anderson]], and complimented the performances of the cast.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guha |first=Kunal |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Film-review-Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47547376.cms |title=Film Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |date=5 June 2015 |work=Mumbai Mirror |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606131650/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Film-review-Dil-Dhadakne-Do/articleshow/47547376.cms |archive-date=6 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rajiv Vijayakar from ''India-West'' gave a rating of 4 stars, describing it as \"entertaining with stellar performances\", praising Akhtar's direction and writing, \"Zoya gets the emotions right by making the entertainment riveting and the experience full of many perceptive insights into basic relationships\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/movie_reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-movie-review-inspiring-story-entertains-with-stellar/article_8bb3e204-0bab-11e5-90c1-7b85c1453b2e.html |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' Movie Review: Inspiring Story Entertains with Stellar Performances |last=Vijayakar, Rajive |date=5 June 2015 |website=India-West |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712015040/http://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/movie_reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-movie-review-inspiring-story-entertains-with-stellar/article_8bb3e204-0bab-11e5-90c1-7b85c1453b2e.html |archive-date=12 July 2015 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Srijana Mitra Das of ''[[The Times of India]]'' gave the film 4 stars, praising the performances of the lead actors and writing, \"On this ship, a few bolts could be tighter. But these are fleeting clouds on an otherwise beautiful sea, hosting a cruise&nbsp;...&nbsp;while searching beyond Bollywood's emotional Botox for a family's warts&nbsp;- and its heart.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mitra Das, Srijana |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/movie-review/47536090.cms |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Movie Review |date=4 June 2015 |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605041934/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Dil-Dhadakne-Do/movie-review/47536090.cms |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shubha Shetty-Saha of ''[[Mid-Day]]'' gave the film 4 stars and complimented the story, stating, \"If this film looks like an entertaining, escapist film at the outset, it is, but it is also much deeper than that\".<ref name=\"midday\">{{Cite news |last=Shetty-Saha |first=Shubha |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/dil-dhadakne-do---movie-review/16265195 |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' \u2013 Movie Review |date=4 June 2015 |work=Mid Day |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605142508/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/dil-dhadakne-do---movie-review/16265195 |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> She also appreciated the performances, especially Chopra's and Singh's, writing, \"These two blazing talents are magical when they come together sharing what perhaps could be one of the best sibling chemistry in Hindi films\".<ref name=\"midday\" />\n\nThe reviewer from [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave the film 3.5 stars, praising Akhtar's direction for \"[pulling] off such a magnificent film with such utmost ease\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/732336 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Review |date=4 June 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607173837/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/732336 |archive-date=7 June 2015 |access-date=4 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', film critic [[Anupama Chopra]] rated the film 3.5 stars, commending the performances&nbsp;- particularly those of Kapoor, Shah and Chopra&nbsp;- and the high production value, writing, \"There are soaring top shots of the ship, of gorgeous towns in Turkey and Greece, and of staggering fashions\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-review-by-anupama-chopra-a-flawed-family/story-MrcouizWr8HnfacmV6j8JM.html |title=Dil Dhadakne Do review by Anupama Chopra: A flawed family |last=Chopra, Anupama |date=8 June 2015 |website=Hindustan Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820201631/http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/dil-dhadakne-do-review-by-anupama-chopra-a-flawed-family/story-MrcouizWr8HnfacmV6j8JM.html |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rachit Gupta of ''Filmfare'' described the film as a \"spunky comedy, straight from the heart\", attributing the performances of the lead actors as the prime reason for the film's success.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gupta |first=Rachit |url=https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9417.html |title=Movie Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |date=5 June 2015 |work=Filmfare |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606204643/http://www.filmfare.com/reviews/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-9417.html |archive-date=6 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sonia Chopra from [[Sify]] also gave 3.5 stars, calling ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' a film with a \"robust heartbeat\", admiring Akhtar's ability to create \"real and interesting\" characters and writing, \"Zoya Akhtar brings in several delightful elements of her filmmaking style&nbsp;- there's the gorgeous cast playing interesting characters, the overt and covert equations between them, the hints at societal hypocrisy and sexism, the romance, the gorgeous locales, and the measured pace\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-this-one-has-a-robust-heartbeat-review-bollywood-pgfluOgdbdajb.html |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' review: This one has a robust heartbeat! |last=Chopra, Sonia |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720141746/http://www.sify.com/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-this-one-has-a-robust-heartbeat-review-bollywood-pgfluOgdbdajb.html |archive-date=20 July 2017 |access-date=20 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFilm critic [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-News18]] gave 3 stars, appreciating the performances of the lead actors&nbsp;- especially that of Kapoor and Shah&nbsp;- calling them \"absolutely riveting\". He praised the humour in the screenplay and concluded that the film is \"easy and breezy, and packed with terrific actors who appear to be enjoying themselves\", although he criticised the pacing and climax of the film, calling it \"silly\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-its-easy-and-breezy-and-packed-with-terrific-actors-1002090.html |title='Dil Dhadakne Do' review: It's easy and breezy, and packed with terrific actors |last=Masand |first=Rajeev |date=6 June 2015 |publisher=CNN-News18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607175850/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/dil-dhadakne-do-review-its-easy-and-breezy-and-packed-with-terrific-actors-1002090.html |archive-date=7 June 2015 |access-date=6 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a 3 star review, film critic [[Mayank Shekhar]] of [[ABP News]] said that \"patiently drawing out emotions from every character\" made the film \"horrendously long [and] too languidly paced\", although he called the film \"\"intensely real, intrinsically adult, with several sharp observations about relationships and life\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abplive.in/author/mayankshekhar/2015/06/05/article609308.ece/FILM-REVIEW---Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Long-languid-but-intensely-real--likeable |title=Film review: Dil Dhadakne Do: Long, languid, but intensely real & likeable |last=Shekhar |first=Mayank |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=[[ABP News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606033318/http://www.abplive.in/author/mayankshekhar/2015/06/05/article609308.ece/FILM-REVIEW---Dil-Dhadakne-Do-Long-languid-but-intensely-real--likeable |archive-date=6 June 2015 |access-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Scoring the film 3 stars, Sukanya Verma of [[Rediff.com]] wrote that ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' \"unravels like an entire season of soap opera condensed into a nearly three-hour movie\", but found it \"too facile to rise above the charming fluff\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-charming-fluff/20150605.htm |title=Review: Dil Dhadakne Do is charming fluff |last=Verma |first=Sukanya |date=5 June 2015 |publisher=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606080845/http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-charming-fluff/20150605.htm |archive-date=6 June 2015 |access-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRitika Bhatia of ''[[Business Standard]]'' wrote that the film \"does have its enjoyable moments, but with a three-hour runtime, it fails to sail the high seas\", and termed the film \"ambitious\" but \"meandering\".<ref name=\"Bhatia\">{{Cite news |last=Bhatia |first=Ritika |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-a-meandering-tale-of-luxe-angst-115060500612_1.html |title=Movie Review: Dil Dhadakne Do is a meandering tale of luxe angst |date=5 June 2015 |work=Business Standard |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605233716/http://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do-is-a-meandering-tale-of-luxe-angst-115060500612_1.html |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shilpa Jamkhandikar of [[Reuters]] called it \"Akhtar's weakest film yet, because she tries to tell too many stories at once and tells none entirely\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2015/06/05/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do/ |title=Movie Review: Dil Dhadakne Do |last=Jamkhandikar |first=Shilpa |date=5 June 2015 |website=[[Reuters]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809031115/http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2015/06/05/movie-review-dil-dhadakne-do/ |archive-date=9 August 2016 |access-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sarita A. Tanwar of ''[[Daily News and Analysis]]'' gave the film 2.5 stars, and said it would have \"been a lot of fun [if] had it been shorter, crisper and less indulgent\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tanwar |first=Sarita A |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-dil-dhadakne-do-review-would-have-been-more-fun-had-it-been-shorter-crisper-and-less-indulgent-2092582 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do review: Would have been more fun had it been shorter, crisper and less indulgent |date=5 June 2015 |work=Daily News and Analysis |access-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605233259/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-dil-dhadakne-do-review-would-have-been-more-fun-had-it-been-shorter-crisper-and-less-indulgent-2092582 |archive-date=5 June 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Box office ==\n''Dil Dhadakne Do'' had a decent opening, with collections of {{INR}}100&nbsp;million on its opening day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1348 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do First Day Business |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820073749/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1348 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Collections rose 20% on its second day, collecting {{INR}}120 million, and another 20% on its third day, with collections of {{INR}}140 million for the opening domestic weekend of {{INR}}360&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1353 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do First Weekend Business |date=8 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820033155/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1353 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Upon its release, the film recorded the highest overseas opening of the year for an Indian film, collecting {{INR}}195&nbsp;million in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1356 |title=Top Overseas Openings \u2013 Dil Dhadakne Do Tops |date=8 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074003/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1356 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNotably, the film debuted at number 9 at the U.K. Box Office, where it earned $330,000 in its opening weekend.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-empire-strikes-801505 |title=U.K. Box Office: 'Empire Strikes Back' Returns to Top 10 |last=Alex Ritman |date=June 10, 2015 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610132619/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-empire-strikes-801505 |archive-date=10 June 2015 |access-date=June 10, 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The total worldwide opening weekend collections stood at {{INR}}675&nbsp;million, making it the top worldwide opener among Indian films at the time of its release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1355 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Is Top Worldwide Opener of 2015 |date=8 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074334/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1355 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On its first Monday, the film's collections dropped 40%, earning another {{INR}}57.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1359 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do First Monday Business |date=9 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820033154/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1359 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It earned {{INR}}550 million in its first week at the domestic box office and over {{INR}}980&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"second\">{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1375 |title=Dil Dhadakne Do Second Weekend Business |date=15 June 2015 |publisher=Box Office India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820074332/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=1375 |archive-date=20 August 2017 |access-date=19 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In its second weekend, ''Dil Dhadakne Do'' earned {{INR}}100&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"second\" /> During its theatrical run, the film grossed over {{INR}}1 billion in India and a further {{INR}}450 million worldwide, for a worldwide total of {{INR}}1.45&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"boi\" />\n\n== Accolades ==\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Dil Dhadakne Do}}\n''Dil Dhadakne Do'' received a number of accolades, particularly for the actors. It earned five [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare]] nominations, winning [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/nominations-for-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11809.html |title=Nominations for the 61st Britannia Filmfare Awards |date=11 January 2016 |work=Filmfare |access-date=11 January 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6gO32fdDO?url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/nominations-for-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11809.html |archive-date=30 March 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/full-list-of-winners-of-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11841.html |title=Full list of winners of the 61st Britannia Filmfare Awards |date=15 January 2016 |work=Filmfare |access-date=16 January 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316165017/http://www.filmfare.com/news/full-list-of-winners-of-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11841.html |archive-date=16 March 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was nominated in nine categories at the 2016 [[Screen Awards]], including [[Screen Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[Screen Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Akhtar and [[Screen Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Chopra. It went on to win two; [[Screen Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor and the [[Screen Awards|Best Ensemble Cast]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9544 |title=Winners of 22nd Annual Star Screen Awards 2015 |date=8 January 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330050107/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9544 |archive-date=30 March 2016 |access-date=10 January 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hotstar.com/tv/star-screen-awards/7050/main-awards-ceremony/1000082990 |title=22 Star Screen Awards |publisher=[[Hotstar]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317213510/http://www.hotstar.com/tv/star-screen-awards/7050/main-awards-ceremony/1000082990 |archive-date=17 March 2016 |access-date=26 January 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the 2015 [[Stardust Awards]], the film garnered five nominations, including [[Stardust Award for Star of the Year \u2013 Female|Actor of the Year \u2013 Female]] for Chopra and [[Stardust Award for Star of the Year \u2013 Male|Actor of the Year \u2013 Male]] for Singh, winning three awards: [[Stardust Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Kapoor, [[Stardust Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for Shah and Best Costume Design.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9423 |title=Nominations for Stardust Awards 2015 |date=15 December 2015 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330050312/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/9423 |archive-date=30 March 2016 |access-date=20 December 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ghosh, Raya |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/stardust-awards-2016-complete-list-of-winners-1257753 |title=Stardust Awards 2016: Complete List of Winners |date=22 December 2016 |access-date=11 February 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125200252/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/stardust-awards-2016-complete-list-of-winners-1257753 |archive-date=25 January 2016 |publisher=NDTV |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|4110568|Dil Dhadkane Do}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|dil_dhadakne_do}}\n* {{Mojo title|dildhadaknedo}}\n\n{{Zoya Akhtar}}\n{{Farhan Akhtar}}\n{{Ritesh Sidhwani}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Seafaring films]]\n[[Category:Films about vacationing]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about couples]]\n[[Category:Films set on ships]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Zoya Akhtar]]\n[[Category:Reliance Entertainment films]]\n", "name_user": "Kailash29792", "label": "safe", "comment": "Arranged references withscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dil_Dhadakne_Do"}
{"title_page": "Sounds Like Sunset", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Cleanup-PR|article|date=May 2019}}\n'''Sounds Like Sunset''' are a band based in Sydney, Australia. The group formed in 1997 and as of 2019 have released 3 albums, ''Saturdays'' in 2001, ''Invisible'' in 2005 and ''We Could Leave Tonight'' in 2014 as well as various other releases on cassettes, 7\" and compilations. ''We Could Leave Tonight'' was released on vinyl 22 July 2014 through Tym Records, and on CD and digitally on 22 August 2014 through Simon Tahiti Records.\n\n==Early days==\n\nThe band formed initially as a side-project with David Challinor (guitar), David Hobson (bass) and Rohan Geddes (drums) in a recently vacated room in Challinor's moldy and more or less condemned share house in [[Pennant Hills]] in Sydney's north west in August 1997. Challinor had been mostly busy playing guitar in the Sydney indie band Sal Paradise ([[Tooth & Nail Records]]) since early 1996, and Hobson had been playing bass in Sydney punk/hardcore act Ceasefire since around 1994. Early Sounds Like Sunset tape recordings and gigs showed the band in similar sonic territory as inspiring home-recording-band influences [[Flying Saucer Attack]] and other [[Drone music|drone]]/[[Noise music|noise]]/[[post-rock]] instrumental bands of the time - however this was something the band quickly distanced themselves from in the hope of melding all the noise & feedback into more concise, hummable melodic pop arrangements.\n\n==Music==\n\nThe band are often filed under [[Shoegazing|shoegazer]] and [[Noise pop|noise-pop]] music. The group's influences and inspiration range from the Beatles, Beach Boys, The Kinks, Velvet Underground and Love, through to more recent artists [[You Am I]], [[Dinosaur Jr]], [[Sebadoh]], [[Spacemen3]], [[Stereolab]], [[Bailter Space]], [[Flying Saucer Attack]], [[Sonic Youth]], [[The Cure]], [[My_Bloody_Valentine_(band)|My Bloody Valentine]] and the [[Jesus and Mary Chain]].\n\nThe members' teenage/formative years share a collective love of [[Punk rock|punk]] & [[Death metal]] - which occasionally resurfaces, some might say at odds with the delicate melodic nature of the band's current output. Live shows are generally loud, densely layered and orchestrated guitar assaults.\n\n==PRL==\n\nUntil recently the band regularly fielded a team aptly named \"The S\u00f6unds Like Sunset Singlet\u00f6nes\" in the PRL (Pretend Rugby League) competition, formed during the early 2000s by Chief [[Robert F Cranny]] of numerous celebrated indie bands including [[Sarah Blasko]], [[Gersey]] and [[78 Saab]].  The PRL was formed from a number of the community of Sydney indie bands who rehearsed at the beloved and now defunct Troy Horse Studios in [[Alexandria,_New_South_Wales|Alexandria]]. The team's PRL career began in 2003 during an alcohol-fuelled player auction event at the [[Zetland,_New_South_Wales|Zetland]] Hotel where the mostly ambivalent Challinor/Hobson auction representatives quickly exceeded the $100 salary cap and were outrageously docked competition points before a ball had even been kicked. \n\nIts career highlight was coming Div 1 runners-up in the 2006 season, followed by a Div1 3rd place in the 2007 season with a team selected entirely by Travis Baird of cult Sydney indie instrumental band Founder. Baird was recruited to select a squad when everyone in Sounds Like Sunset once again forgot to attend the player auction. \n\nIn 2008 the band shocked the PRL community by again failing to attend the 2008 PRL player auction, a move that did not go unnoticed by the PRL hierarchy and the band were forced to relinquish their coveted spot in Div1 of the PRL altogether.\n\nThe band hope to be eligible to re-register with PRL in 2020 (after again forgetting to attend the 2019 player auction) and aim to start climbing their way back through the lower leagues until again finding PRL glory in Div1. As [[Phil Gould (rugby league)|Phil Gould]] can often be quoted saying (though perhaps not in direct reference to the Singlet\u00f6nes) \"dismiss them at your peril\".\n\n==Recent Activity==\n\nPhil Usher (drums) joined the band in late 2018. Phil has an extensive background in music performance and composition, and currently teaches percussion full time in his hometown of Brisbane. Phil also writes, sings and plays guitar in Brisbane psych act Sacred Shrines, and played the same role in his previous band [[Grand Atlantic]]. Phil is also the current drummer for the legendary Brisbane act [[Screamfeeder]]. Phil has toured the US extensively in various bands since the mid-90s, and was even at one time called upon to play drums for [[Barry Manilow]] for a live stadium performance. Phil has been a dear friend of and enthusiastic advocate of Sounds Like Sunset for many years since watching the band's first ever live performance in 1997, and has arranged numerous Brisbane shows for the band as well as regularly providing booze, smokes, general good vibes and a floor for the routinely intoxicated and/or hungover band to sleep on.\n\nTobey Doctor (drums) has played in various jazz, punk and defiantly \"unlistenable\" DIY sludge bands since the late 80s and early 90s. Tobey initially befriended the band when booking SLS for shows at The Phonenix Club, a small underground venue in Darlinghurst before joining Sounds Like Sunset after Vig kind of went missing after a while in the early 2000s. Tobey is arguably the most well known drummer of Sounds Like Sunset, and appeared on the band's second album ''Invisible'' and third album ''We Could Leave Tonight''. Tobey provided the loose, wild, energetic Keith-Moon-like wildcard element both on and off the field for what was probably the most cohesive and well-known SLS lineup of Challinor/Hobson/Fevre/Doctor, and continues to be a dear friend and collaborator even years after his departure. Originally from [[Manly,_New_South_Wales|Manly]], Tobey made a sudden decision to move from [[Bondi Beach]] to the Melbourne suburb of [[Heidelberg,_Victoria|Heidelberg]] in late 2016, and after spending a short time away from music and adjusting to life in a new city, he has recently been jamming with a number of Melbourne indie bands including the prolific artist/indie music mover & shaker JMS Harrison. \n\nJoseph Dews (drums) has played in a number of Sydney indie acts over the years including Founder, MachineMachine and The Woods Themselves, as well as his own ongoing solo projects. He currently plays guitar and sings in the band Peter Fonda, which also features current SLS member Travis Baird. \n\nAndrew Fevre (guitar) 1997 - 2008 left Sydney and spent a year traveling Europe before returning to Sydney and moving in with Tobey Doctor in Bondi Beach. Despite living with Tobey, he only rejoined SLS for a very short time before mostly abandoning music altogether and becoming a chef within the empire of celebrity chef [[Bill Granger]]. Andrew remains a dear friend of SLS. He is one of the very first childhood friends of David Hobson, and taught Hobson his first ever swear words. During Fevre's European absence the band played on with various friends dropping into the lineup for a number of shows, including: \n* Scott Meikle (guitar) of Ben Aylward's post-[[Swirl_(band)|Swirl]] band [http://www.myspace.com/beautifulworldband Beautiful World]\n* Pete Farley (guitar) of the bands [[Gelbison]] and [[Toni Collette & the Finish|Toni Collette & The Finish]], and\n* Travis Baird (guitar, keys) of the bands Founder, Melodie Nelson, El Mopa and The Woods Themselves, as well his ongoing solo project AFXJM which includes [[Patrick Matthews]] of Community Radio, [[Youth Group]] and (ex of) [[The Vines (band)|The Vines]]. \n\nCurrent band members now live in an area spread as far afield as [[Tempe,_New_South_Wales|Tempe]], [[Collaroy Plateau]], Concord (Sydney), [[Paddington,_Queensland|Paddington]] (Brisbane) and the NSW Central Coast suburb of [[Wyoming,_New_South_Wales|Wyoming]].\n\n==Band members==\n'''Current lineup''' (current as of March 2019)\n\n* David Challinor - vocals, guitar\n* David Hobson - bass\n* Ben White - guitar\n* Travis Baird - guitar\n* Phil Usher - drums\n\n'''Past Members'''\n\n* Joe Dews - drums\n* Tobey Doctor - drums (''Invisible'', ''We Could Leave Tonight'') \n* Pete Farley - guitar\n* Scott Meikle - guitar\n* Andrew Fevre - guitar\n* Matt Bonson - drums (''Saturdays'')\n* David \"Vig\" Virgilio - drums\n* Josh Thompson - guitar\n* Rohan Geddes - drums\n\n'''Recording & Mixing Engineers'''\n* [[Wayne Connolly]] (''Saturdays'', ''We Could Leave Tonight'') \n* Anthony The (''Invisible'') \n* Jon Gardner a.k.a Jonboyrock (''Invisible'') \n* Chris Townend (''Saturdays'') \n\n'''Sound Engineers'''\n* Toby Baldwin (early/mid 2000s-present)\n* Al Cousins (early-mid 2000s-present)\n* Anthony The (early-mid 2000s)\n* Jon Gardner a.k.a Jonboyrock (late 1990s-mid 2000s)\n* Clay Segelov (early-mid 2000s)\n* Dave Springer (early 2000s)\n* Pete Kelly (late 1990s)\n* Jorden Brebach (late 1990s)\n\nIt can also a curious fact that as of March 2019 none of the 7 Sounds Like Sunset drummers past or present have any biological children between them.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''We Could Leave Tonight'' LP 2014 [http://www.tym-records.com Tym records]\n* ''Invisible'' LP 2005 [http://www.architecturelabel.com Architecture Label]\n* ''Saturdays'' LP 2001 ([[Modular Recordings]])\n* ''Before it Blows/Promise Ring'' split 7\" 2000 (Quietly Suburban Recordings) - a split release with Los Angeles indie band [[The Lassie Foundation]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.soundslikesunset.com.au Sounds Like Sunset official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Australian rock music groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Cleanup-PR|article|date=May 2019}}\n'''Sounds Like Sunset''' are a band based in Sydney, Australia. The group formed in 1997 and as of 2019 have released 3 albums, ''Saturdays'' in 2001, ''Invisible'' in 2005 and ''We Could Leave Tonight'' in 2014 as well as various other releases on cassettes, 7\" and compilations. ''We Could Leave Tonight'' was released on vinyl 22 July 2014 through Tym Records, and on CD and digitally on 22 August 2014 through Simon Tahiti Records.\n\n==Early days==\n\nThe band formed initially as a side-project with David Challinor (guitar), David Hobson (bass) and Rohan Geddes (drums) in a recently vacated room in Challinor's moldy and more or less condemned share house in [[Pennant Hills]] in Sydney's north west in August 1997. Challinor had been mostly busy playing guitar in the Sydney indie band Sal Paradise ([[Tooth & Nail Records]]) since early 1996, and Hobson had been playing bass in Sydney punk/hardcore act Ceasefire since around 1994. Early Sounds Like Sunset tape recordings and gigs showed the band in similar sonic territory as inspiring home-recording-band influences [[Flying Saucer Attack]] and other [[Drone music|drone]]/[[Noise music|noise]]/[[post-rock]] instrumental bands of the time - however this was something the band quickly distanced themselves from in the hope of melding all the noise & feedback into more concise, hummable melodic pop arrangements.\n\n==Music==\n\nThe band are often filed under [[Shoegazing|shoegazer]] and [[Noise pop|noise-pop]] music. The group's influences and inspiration range from the Beatles, Beach Boys, The Kinks, Velvet Underground and Love, through to more recent artists [[You Am I]], [[Dinosaur Jr]], [[Sebadoh]], [[Spacemen3]], [[Stereolab]], [[Bailter Space]], [[Flying Saucer Attack]], [[Sonic Youth]], [[The Cure]], [[My_Bloody_Valentine_(band)|My Bloody Valentine]] and the [[Jesus and Mary Chain]].\n\nThe members' teenage/formative years share a collective love of [[Punk rock|punk]] & [[Death metal]] - which occasionally resurfaces, some might say at odds with the delicate melodic nature of the band's current output. Live shows are generally loud, densely layered and orchestrated guitar assaults.\n\n==PRL==\n\nUntil recently the band regularly fielded a team aptly named \"The S\u00f6unds Like Sunset Singlet\u00f6nes\" in the PRL (Pretend Rugby League) competition, formed during the early 2000s by Chief [[Robert F Cranny]] of numerous celebrated indie bands including [[Sarah Blasko]], [[Gersey]] and [[78 Saab]].  The PRL was formed from a number of the community of Sydney indie bands who rehearsed at the beloved and now defunct Troy Horse Studios in [[Alexandria,_New_South_Wales|Alexandria]]. The team's PRL career began in 2003 during an alcohol-fuelled player auction event at the [[Zetland,_New_South_Wales|Zetland]] Hotel where the mostly ambivalent Challinor/Hobson auction representatives quickly exceeded the $100 salary cap and were outrageously docked competition points before a ball had even been kicked. \n\nIts career highlight was coming Div 1 runners-up in the 2006 season, followed by a Div1 3rd place in the 2007 season with a team selected entirely by Travis Baird of cult Sydney indie instrumental band Founder. Baird was recruited to select a squad when everyone in Sounds Like Sunset once again forgot to attend the player auction. \n\nIn 2008 the band shocked the PRL community by again failing to attend the 2008 PRL player auction, a move that did not go unnoticed by the PRL hierarchy and the band were forced to relinquish their coveted spot in Div1 of the PRL altogether.\n\nThe band hope to be eligible to re-register with PRL in 2020 (after again forgetting to attend the 2019 player auction) and aim to start climbing their way back through the lower leagues until again finding PRL glory in Div1. As [[Phil Gould]] can often be quoted saying (though perhaps not in direct reference to the Singlet\u00f6nes) \"dismiss them at your peril\".\n\n==Recent Activity==\n\nPhil Usher (drums) joined the band in late 2018. Phil has an extensive background in music performance and composition, and currently teaches percussion full time in his hometown of Brisbane. Phil also writes, sings and plays guitar in Brisbane psych act Sacred Shrines, and played the same role in his previous band [[Grand Atlantic]]. Phil is also the current drummer for the legendary Brisbane act [[Screamfeeder]]. Phil has toured the US extensively in various bands since the mid-90s, and was even at one time called upon to play drums for [[Barry Manilow]] for a live stadium performance. Phil has been a dear friend of and enthusiastic advocate of Sounds Like Sunset for many years since watching the band's first ever live performance in 1997, and has arranged numerous Brisbane shows for the band as well as regularly providing booze, smokes, general good vibes and a floor for the routinely intoxicated and/or hungover band to sleep on.\n\nTobey Doctor (drums) has played in various jazz, punk and defiantly \"unlistenable\" DIY sludge bands since the late 80s and early 90s. Tobey initially befriended the band when booking SLS for shows at The Phonenix Club, a small underground venue in Darlinghurst before joining Sounds Like Sunset after Vig kind of went missing after a while in the early 2000s. Tobey is arguably the most well known drummer of Sounds Like Sunset, and appeared on the band's second album ''Invisible'' and third album ''We Could Leave Tonight''. Tobey provided the loose, wild, energetic Keith-Moon-like wildcard element both on and off the field for what was probably the most cohesive and well-known SLS lineup of Challinor/Hobson/Fevre/Doctor, and continues to be a dear friend and collaborator even years after his departure. Originally from [[Manly,_New_South_Wales|Manly]], Tobey made a sudden decision to move from [[Bondi Beach]] to the Melbourne suburb of [[Heidelberg,_Victoria|Heidelberg]] in late 2016, and after spending a short time away from music and adjusting to life in a new city, he has recently been jamming with a number of Melbourne indie bands including the prolific artist/indie music mover & shaker JMS Harrison. \n\nJoseph Dews (drums) has played in a number of Sydney indie acts over the years including Founder, MachineMachine and The Woods Themselves, as well as his own ongoing solo projects. He currently plays guitar and sings in the band Peter Fonda, which also features current SLS member Travis Baird. \n\nAndrew Fevre (guitar) 1997 - 2008 left Sydney and spent a year traveling Europe before returning to Sydney and moving in with Tobey Doctor in Bondi Beach. Despite living with Tobey, he only rejoined SLS for a very short time before mostly abandoning music altogether and becoming a chef within the empire of celebrity chef [[Bill Granger]]. Andrew remains a dear friend of SLS. He is one of the very first childhood friends of David Hobson, and taught Hobson his first ever swear words. During Fevre's European absence the band played on with various friends dropping into the lineup for a number of shows, including: \n* Scott Meikle (guitar) of Ben Aylward's post-[[Swirl_(band)|Swirl]] band [http://www.myspace.com/beautifulworldband Beautiful World]\n* Pete Farley (guitar) of the bands [[Gelbison]] and [[Toni Collette & the Finish|Toni Collette & The Finish]], and\n* Travis Baird (guitar, keys) of the bands Founder, Melodie Nelson, El Mopa and The Woods Themselves, as well his ongoing solo project AFXJM which includes [[Patrick Matthews]] of Community Radio, [[Youth Group]] and (ex of) [[The Vines (band)|The Vines]]. \n\nCurrent band members now live in an area spread as far afield as [[Tempe,_New_South_Wales|Tempe]], [[Collaroy Plateau]], Concord (Sydney), [[Paddington,_Queensland|Paddington]] (Brisbane) and the NSW Central Coast suburb of [[Wyoming,_New_South_Wales|Wyoming]].\n\n==Band members==\n'''Current lineup''' (current as of March 2019)\n\n* David Challinor - vocals, guitar\n* David Hobson - bass\n* Ben White - guitar\n* Travis Baird - guitar\n* Phil Usher - drums\n\n'''Past Members'''\n\n* Joe Dews - drums\n* Tobey Doctor - drums (''Invisible'', ''We Could Leave Tonight'') \n* Pete Farley - guitar\n* Scott Meikle - guitar\n* Andrew Fevre - guitar\n* Matt Bonson - drums (''Saturdays'')\n* David \"Vig\" Virgilio - drums\n* Josh Thompson - guitar\n* Rohan Geddes - drums\n\n'''Recording & Mixing Engineers'''\n* [[Wayne Connolly]] (''Saturdays'', ''We Could Leave Tonight'') \n* Anthony The (''Invisible'') \n* Jon Gardner a.k.a Jonboyrock (''Invisible'') \n* Chris Townend (''Saturdays'') \n\n'''Sound Engineers'''\n* Toby Baldwin (early/mid 2000s-present)\n* Al Cousins (early-mid 2000s-present)\n* Anthony The (early-mid 2000s)\n* Jon Gardner a.k.a Jonboyrock (late 1990s-mid 2000s)\n* Clay Segelov (early-mid 2000s)\n* Dave Springer (early 2000s)\n* Pete Kelly (late 1990s)\n* Jorden Brebach (late 1990s)\n\nIt can also a curious fact that as of March 2019 none of the 7 Sounds Like Sunset drummers past or present have any biological children between them.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''We Could Leave Tonight'' LP 2014 [http://www.tym-records.com Tym records]\n* ''Invisible'' LP 2005 [http://www.architecturelabel.com Architecture Label]\n* ''Saturdays'' LP 2001 ([[Modular Recordings]])\n* ''Before it Blows/Promise Ring'' split 7\" 2000 (Quietly Suburban Recordings) - a split release with Los Angeles indie band [[The Lassie Foundation]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.soundslikesunset.com.au Sounds Like Sunset official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Australian rock music groups]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toPhilip Gould (disambiguation)(link changed toPhil Gould (rugby league)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sounds_Like_Sunset"}
{"title_page": "Haltoun House", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:Haltoun House.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Haltoun House c1900]]\n'''Haltoun House''', or '''Hatton House''', was a [[Scottish baronial]] mansion set in a park, with extensive estates in the vicinity of [[Ratho]], in the west of [[Edinburgh]] City Council area, Scotland. It was formerly in [[Midlothian]], and it was extensively photographed by ''[[Country Life (magazine)|Country Life]]'' in September 1911.<ref>Ref:Country Life. Sept 16 1911. pp408-415.</ref>\n\n==Proprietors==\nThe earliest known proprietor John de Haltoun sold the property on 26 July 1377 when [[Robert II of Scotland|Robert II]] confirmed it upon a court [[favourite]], Alan de Lawedre of [[Whitslaid Tower|Whitslaid]], [[Berwickshire]].<ref>''Register of The [[Great Seal of Scotland]]'', no. 724</ref> Alan and his first wife, Alicia, daughter of Sir Colin Campbell of Lochawe, already owned (1371) the adjoining lands of Norton.<ref>Robertson, ''Index of Records of Charters granted by Sovereigns of Scotland between 1309 and 1413'' (Edinburgh, 1798).</ref><ref>[[James Balfour Paul|Balfour Paul, Sir James]], ''The Scots' Peerage'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1904), 'Argyll', p. 326.</ref> [[George de Lawedre of Haltoun]], [[Lord Provost of Edinburgh|Provost of Edinburgh]], Alan's second son by his second wife, Elizabeth, was put in fee of Haltoun in 1393. He died in 1430 and left only daughters as co-heirs. His brother, Sir Alexander Lauder became the ancestor of the Haltoun cadet branch.<ref>Lauder-Frost, Gregory, ''Lauder Arms'', in ''The Double Tressure'' (Edinburgh, 2007), The [[Heraldry Society of Scotland]], pp. 25-6, {{ISSN|0141-237X}}</ref> The first laird of Haltoun is sometimes said to be Sir George de Lawedre who married Helen Douglas, a sister of Lord Douglas, daughter of [[Archibald the Grim|Archibald Douglas, 3rd Earl of Douglas]], 'The Grim' (d. 1400).<ref>J. Stewart Smith (1898).</ref> Sir Alexander's great-grandson, another Sir George Lauder of Haltoun, fell at the [[Battle of Flodden]]<ref>Douglas, Sir Robert, ''The Baronage of Scotland'', Edinburgh, 1798, p.549.</ref> with two of his brothers, James Lauder of Norton, and Sir [[Alexander Lauder of Blyth]]<ref>Finlay, ''Hatton House'', Edinburgh, 1875: Burnett, George, [[Lord Lyon]] King of Arms & A.E.J.G.Mackay, editors,''The [[Exchequer Rolls of Scotland]]: 1508-1513'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh 1891), , p.clxxxviii: Douglas, Sir Robert, ''The Baronage of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1798), p.549.</ref>\n\n[[James VI of Scotland]] stayed at Hatton using it as a hunting lodge in April 1589, but returned to Edinburgh over fears for his safety from disaffected lords.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 6, 34.</ref>\n\n[[File:Richard Lauder.jpg|thumb|260px|The Much Hon. Richard Lauder, Laird of Haltoun, painted in his 80th year, 1669.]]\nThe Haltoun/Hatton estates remained in the Lauder family until the last [[Laird]], Richard Lauder of Haltoun, settled them upon his younger daughter. Richard Lauder was a [[Justice of the Peace]], was [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Edinburghshire]] in 1621, and in 1647 and 1648 was on the Committees of War for Edinburgh. He was also Commissioner of [[Excise]] in 1661. His wife, Mary Lauder, Lady Haltoun, had been born Mary Scot.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirby|first1=Justin|title=Elizabeth Lauder, heiress of Haltoun|url=https://descentfromadam.wordpress.com/2010/11/30/elizabeth-lauder-heiress-of-haltoun/|publisher=WordPress.com weblog|accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref> Richard died in November 1675 in [[Holyrood Abbey]], Edinburgh, and was interred in [[Ratho#Parish Church (St Marys)|Ratho]] Church on the 29th.<ref>''Index to Genealogies, Birthbriefs and Funeral Escutcheons Held by the Lord Lyon of Scotland'', [[Scottish Record Society]].</ref> His portrait (right), by [[John Scougal]], hangs in [[Thirlestane Castle]].\n\nHis second daughter, Elizabeth married, in 1652, [[Charles Maitland, 3rd Earl of Lauderdale]] and carried Haltoun to him. Haltoun was much closer to Edinburgh than Thirlestane Castle, and with the loss of [[Lethington]] the Maitlands made Haltoun House their principal residence (as opposed to seat) until 1792 when the 8th Earl of Lauderdale sold the estate for \u00a384,000 to Miss Henrietta Scott of Scotstarvet, who married [[William Henry Cavendish-Scott-Bentinck, 4th Duke of Portland]]. The estate was then {{convert|2000|acre|km2}} of excellent land, the revenue at the time: \u00a33000 per annum. Her trustees sold the estate in 1797 to James Gibson of [[Ingliston|Ingleston]], afterwards [[Sir James Gibson-Craig, 1st Baronet]] of [[Riccarton, Edinburgh|Riccarton]]. He broke up the estate into lots, of which that including Haltoun House and {{convert|500|acre|km2}} was bought by the Reverend Thomas Randall (who afterwards took the surname of Davidson). He sold Haltoun House to the [[Earl of Morton]] in 1870, whose son Lord Aberdour sold it to James McKelvie in 1898. In 1915 it was sold to William Whitelaw, chairman of the [[London and North Eastern Railway]] company.\n\n==Haltoun House==\n\nThe first Lauders built a massive Pele Tower at Haltoun before 1400, which Hannan refers to as \"an '''L'''-shaped castle with walls of a uniform thickness of about {{convert|10|ft|m}}.\" Sir William Lauder of Haltoun was a confidant of both King [[James II of Scotland|James II]] and the Earl of Douglas. In 1452 he was the King's personal messenger, sent to escort Douglas to [[Stirling Castle]] on a Royal promise of absolute safety, whereupon the Earl was murdered by the King. Haltoun Tower was subsequently besieged by King James and during that siege, Sir William Lauder died. The tower and battlements were subsequently restored to good condition by the King, at Exchequer expense.\n\nThe castle became the nucleus of the subsequent greater country house which was built onto and around it. On the east face of the south-east angle tower was a sundial with the monogram \"C.M.E.L\" for Charles Maitland & his wife Elizabeth Lauder, the monogram being divided by the date 1664, the year in which Maitland commenced dramatic new extensions to the old castle. His son John added the east front in a [[Renaissance]] style in 1696 and 1704. It was restored in 1859 and in 1870 the windows were altered.\n\nThe interiors were entered through a small entrance hall, panelled in [[oak]] brought from [[Letheringham]] Abbey, [[Suffolk]], into the main hall, {{convert|50|ft|m}} by 20, panelled also with a magnificent finely-made [[Jacobean architecture|Jacobean]] plaster ceiling. Other rooms included a morning room, situated between the library and dining room (both also panelled in oak). On the first floor the saloon and drawing rooms were fitted out with [[Klaip\u0117da|Memel]] pine panelling, greatly used in Scottish country houses at the time.  'Lord Jeffrey's study' in the tower, was a nine-sided decorative room, with much gilt. The centre of the ceiling was a painting of a man flying away with a lightly clothed female - a classical motif.\n\nHaltoun House was approached by an original avenue, half a mile long, abutted by tall [[elm]]s and [[beech]]es, [[lime tree]]s, [[hollies]], [[taxus|Yews]], and [[rhododendron]]s. The principal entrance was at the east through massive gate pillars.\n\nIn 1952 the house caught fire, and was demolished in 1955, during a period when many other country houses suffered a similar fate. All that remains are the terraces along the south side of the house with a two-story pavilion at each end.\n\nThe grounds currently support rare habitats for greater-crested newts, tree moles, bats and land puffins; all protected species.\n\nA number of structures survive on the estate. The East Avenue Gates,<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB27341|desc=Hatton Estate, East Avenue Gates|cat=A|access-date=29 March 2019}}</ref> the South Gateway<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB7355|desc=South Gateway Hatton Estate|cat=A|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> and the South Terrace Wall with pavilions and bath-house<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB27334|desc=Hatton Estate, S Terrace Wall with Pavilions and Bath-House|cat=A|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> are all category A listed buildings while the Garden Temple is Category B listed.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB27348|desc=Hatton Estate, Garden Temple|cat=B|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> The surviving garden, together with these buildings, is included in Historic Environment Scotland's Inventory of Gardens and Designed Landscapes.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=GDL00209|desc=Hatton House|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* ''The Douglas Book'', by William Douglas, CB., LL.D., vol.1, p.&nbsp;472, and vol.2, p.&nbsp;609, Edinburgh, 1885.\n* ''The Grange of St.Giles'', by J.Stewart Smith, Edinburgh,1898, p.&nbsp;251.\n* ''Famous Scottish Houses - The Lowlands'', by Thomas Hannan, MA, FSA(Scot), London, 1928, pps: 97 - 100.\n* ''Lost Houses of Scotland'' by Marcus Binney, John Harris, & Emma Winnington, published by [[SAVE Britain's Heritage]], July 1980.\n\n{{coord|55.903|-3.396|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Country houses in Midlothian]]\n[[Category:Former country houses in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Inventory of Gardens and Designed Landscapes]]\n[[Category:Scottish country houses destroyed in the 20th century]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:Haltoun House.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Haltoun House c1900]]\n'''Haltoun House''', or '''Hatton House''', was a [[Scottish baronial]] mansion set in a park, with extensive estates in the vicinity of [[Ratho]], in the west of [[Edinburgh]] City Council area, Scotland. It was formerly in [[Midlothian]], and it was extensively photographed by ''[[Country Life (magazine)|Country Life]]'' in September 1911.<ref>Ref:Country Life. Sept 16 1911. pp408-415.</ref>\n\n==Proprietors==\nThe earliest known proprietor John de Haltoun sold the property on 26 July 1377 when [[Robert II of Scotland|Robert II]] confirmed it upon a court [[favourite]], Alan de Lawedre of [[Whitslaid Tower|Whitslaid]], [[Berwickshire]].<ref>''Register of The [[Great Seal of Scotland]]'', no. 724</ref> Alan and his first wife, Alicia, daughter of Sir Colin Campbell of Lochawe, already owned (1371) the adjoining lands of Norton.<ref>Robertson, ''Index of Records of Charters granted by Sovereigns of Scotland between 1309 and 1413'' (Edinburgh, 1798).</ref><ref>[[James Balfour Paul|Balfour Paul, Sir James]], ''The Scots' Peerage'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1904), 'Argyll', p. 326.</ref> [[George de Lawedre of Haltoun]], [[Lord Provost of Edinburgh|Provost of Edinburgh]], Alan's second son by his second wife, Elizabeth, was put in fee of Haltoun in 1393. He died in 1430 and left only daughters as co-heirs. His brother, Sir Alexander Lauder became the ancestor of the Haltoun cadet branch.<ref>Lauder-Frost, Gregory, ''Lauder Arms'', in ''The Double Tressure'' (Edinburgh, 2007), The [[Heraldry Society of Scotland]], pp. 25-6, {{ISSN|0141-237X}}</ref> The first laird of Haltoun is sometimes said to be Sir George de Lawedre who married Helen Douglas, a sister of Lord Douglas, daughter of [[Archibald the Grim|Archibald Douglas, 3rd Earl of Douglas]], 'The Grim' (d. 1400).<ref>J. Stewart Smith (1898).</ref> Sir Alexander's great-grandson, another Sir George Lauder of Haltoun, fell at the [[Battle of Flodden]]<ref>Douglas, Sir Robert, ''The Baronage of Scotland'', Edinburgh, 1798, p.549.</ref> with two of his brothers, James Lauder of Norton, and Sir [[Alexander Lauder of Blyth]]<ref>Finlay, ''Hatton House'', Edinburgh, 1875: Burnett, George, [[Lord Lyon]] King of Arms & A.E.J.G.Mackay, editors,''The [[Exchequer Rolls of Scotland]]: 1508-1513'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh 1891), , p.clxxxviii: Douglas, Sir Robert, ''The Baronage of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1798), p.549.</ref></ref>\n\n[[James VI of Scotland]] stayed at Hatton using it as a hunting lodge in April 1589, but returned to Edinburgh over fears for his safety from disaffected lords.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 6, 34.</ref>\n\n[[File:Richard Lauder.jpg|thumb|260px|The Much Hon. Richard Lauder, Laird of Haltoun, painted in his 80th year, 1669.]]\nThe Haltoun/Hatton estates remained in the Lauder family until the last [[Laird]], Richard Lauder of Haltoun, settled them upon his younger daughter. Richard Lauder was a [[Justice of the Peace]], was [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Edinburghshire]] in 1621, and in 1647 and 1648 was on the Committees of War for Edinburgh. He was also Commissioner of [[Excise]] in 1661. His wife, Mary Lauder, Lady Haltoun, had been born Mary Scot.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirby|first1=Justin|title=Elizabeth Lauder, heiress of Haltoun|url=https://descentfromadam.wordpress.com/2010/11/30/elizabeth-lauder-heiress-of-haltoun/|publisher=WordPress.com weblog|accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref> Richard died in November 1675 in [[Holyrood Abbey]], Edinburgh, and was interred in [[Ratho#Parish Church (St Marys)|Ratho]] Church on the 29th.<ref>''Index to Genealogies, Birthbriefs and Funeral Escutcheons Held by the Lord Lyon of Scotland'', [[Scottish Record Society]].</ref> His portrait (right), by [[John Scougal]], hangs in [[Thirlestane Castle]].\n\nHis second daughter, Elizabeth married, in 1652, [[Charles Maitland, 3rd Earl of Lauderdale]] and carried Haltoun to him. Haltoun was much closer to Edinburgh than Thirlestane Castle, and with the loss of [[Lethington]] the Maitlands made Haltoun House their principal residence (as opposed to seat) until 1792 when the 8th Earl of Lauderdale sold the estate for \u00a384,000 to Miss Henrietta Scott of Scotstarvet, who married [[William Henry Cavendish-Scott-Bentinck, 4th Duke of Portland]]. The estate was then {{convert|2000|acre|km2}} of excellent land, the revenue at the time: \u00a33000 per annum. Her trustees sold the estate in 1797 to James Gibson of [[Ingliston|Ingleston]], afterwards [[Sir James Gibson-Craig, 1st Baronet]] of [[Riccarton, Edinburgh|Riccarton]]. He broke up the estate into lots, of which that including Haltoun House and {{convert|500|acre|km2}} was bought by the Reverend Thomas Randall (who afterwards took the surname of Davidson). He sold Haltoun House to the [[Earl of Morton]] in 1870, whose son Lord Aberdour sold it to James McKelvie in 1898. In 1915 it was sold to William Whitelaw, chairman of the [[London and North Eastern Railway]] company.\n\n==Haltoun House==\n\nThe first Lauders built a massive Pele Tower at Haltoun before 1400, which Hannan refers to as \"an '''L'''-shaped castle with walls of a uniform thickness of about {{convert|10|ft|m}}.\" Sir William Lauder of Haltoun was a confidant of both King [[James II of Scotland|James II]] and the Earl of Douglas. In 1452 he was the King's personal messenger, sent to escort Douglas to [[Stirling Castle]] on a Royal promise of absolute safety, whereupon the Earl was murdered by the King. Haltoun Tower was subsequently besieged by King James and during that siege, Sir William Lauder died. The tower and battlements were subsequently restored to good condition by the King, at Exchequer expense.\n\nThe castle became the nucleus of the subsequent greater country house which was built onto and around it. On the east face of the south-east angle tower was a sundial with the monogram \"C.M.E.L\" for Charles Maitland & his wife Elizabeth Lauder, the monogram being divided by the date 1664, the year in which Maitland commenced dramatic new extensions to the old castle. His son John added the east front in a [[Renaissance]] style in 1696 and 1704. It was restored in 1859 and in 1870 the windows were altered.\n\nThe interiors were entered through a small entrance hall, panelled in [[oak]] brought from [[Letheringham]] Abbey, [[Suffolk]], into the main hall, {{convert|50|ft|m}} by 20, panelled also with a magnificent finely-made [[Jacobean architecture|Jacobean]] plaster ceiling. Other rooms included a morning room, situated between the library and dining room (both also panelled in oak). On the first floor the saloon and drawing rooms were fitted out with [[Klaip\u0117da|Memel]] pine panelling, greatly used in Scottish country houses at the time.  'Lord Jeffrey's study' in the tower, was a nine-sided decorative room, with much gilt. The centre of the ceiling was a painting of a man flying away with a lightly clothed female - a classical motif.\n\nHaltoun House was approached by an original avenue, half a mile long, abutted by tall [[elm]]s and [[beech]]es, [[lime tree]]s, [[hollies]], [[taxus|Yews]], and [[rhododendron]]s. The principal entrance was at the east through massive gate pillars.\n\nIn 1952 the house caught fire, and was demolished in 1955, during a period when many other country houses suffered a similar fate. All that remains are the terraces along the south side of the house with a two-story pavilion at each end.\n\nThe grounds currently support rare habitats for greater-crested newts, tree moles, bats and land puffins; all protected species.\n\nA number of structures survive on the estate. The East Avenue Gates,<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB27341|desc=Hatton Estate, East Avenue Gates|cat=A|access-date=29 March 2019}}</ref> the South Gateway<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB7355|desc=South Gateway Hatton Estate|cat=A|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> and the South Terrace Wall with pavilions and bath-house<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB27334|desc=Hatton Estate, S Terrace Wall with Pavilions and Bath-House|cat=A|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> are all category A listed buildings while the Garden Temple is Category B listed.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB27348|desc=Hatton Estate, Garden Temple|cat=B|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> The surviving garden, together with these buildings, is included in Historic Environment Scotland's Inventory of Gardens and Designed Landscapes.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=GDL00209|desc=Hatton House|access-date=29 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* ''The Douglas Book'', by William Douglas, CB., LL.D., vol.1, p.&nbsp;472, and vol.2, p.&nbsp;609, Edinburgh, 1885.\n* ''The Grange of St.Giles'', by J.Stewart Smith, Edinburgh,1898, p.&nbsp;251.\n* ''Famous Scottish Houses - The Lowlands'', by Thomas Hannan, MA, FSA(Scot), London, 1928, pps: 97 - 100.\n* ''Lost Houses of Scotland'' by Marcus Binney, John Harris, & Emma Winnington, published by [[SAVE Britain's Heritage]], July 1980.\n\n{{coord|55.903|-3.396|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Country houses in Midlothian]]\n[[Category:Former country houses in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Inventory of Gardens and Designed Landscapes]]\n[[Category:Scottish country houses destroyed in the 20th century]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haltoun_House"}
{"title_page": "Wayne Pearce", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n| name = Wayne Pearce\n| fullname = Wayne John Pearce\n| image =\n| caption =\n| country =\n| position = {{rlp|LK|SR}}\n| currentclub =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|3|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Balmain, New South Wales]], Australia\n| retired = yes\n| height = {{convert|180|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|89|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n| club1 = [[Balmain Tigers]]\n| year1start = 1980\n| year1end = 90\n| appearances1 = 193\n| tries1 = 33\n| goals1 = 0\n| fieldgoals1 = 0\n| points1 = 123\n| teamA = [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n| yearAstart = 1983\n| yearAend = 88\n| appearancesA = 16\n| triesA = 3\n| goalsA = 0\n| fieldgoalsA = 0\n| pointsA = 12\n| teamB = [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]]\n| yearBstart = 1982\n| yearBend = 88\n| appearancesB = 19\n| triesB = 6\n| goalsB = 0\n| fieldgoalsB = 0\n| pointsB = 21\n| teamC = [[City New South Wales rugby league team|NSW City]]\n| yearCstart = 1983\n| yearCend = 88\n| appearancesC = 6\n| triesC = 1\n| goalsC = 0\n| fieldgoalsC = 0\n| pointsC = 4\n| coachyear1start = 1994\n| coachyear1end = 99\n| coachteam1 = [[Balmain Tigers]]\n| coachgames1 = 158\n| coachwins1 = 55\n| coachdraws1 = 1\n| coachlosses1 = 101\n| coachyear2start = 2000\n| coachyear2end =\n| coachteam2 = [[Wests Tigers]]\n| coachgames2 = 26\n| coachwins2 = 11\n| coachdraws2 = 2\n| coachlosses2 = 13\n| coachyearAstart = 1999\n| coachyearAend = 01\n| coachteamA = [[New South Wales state rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n| coachgamesA = 9\n| coachwinsA = 5\n| coachdrawsA = 1\n| coachlossesA = 3\n| source = <ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com/players/Wayne_Pearce.html RLP]</ref><ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/coaches/wayne-pearce/summary.html Rugby League Project Coaches]</ref>\n| updated = 5 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Wayne John Pearce''' [[Order of Australia|OAM]] (born 29 March 1960 in [[Balmain, New South Wales]]) is an Australian former professional [[rugby league]] footballer and coach. An athletic {{rlp|lk}} for the [[Balmain Tigers]], he was affectionately known as 'Junior'. Pearce represented [[New South Wales Rugby League team|New South Wales]] in the [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin Series]] as well as the [[Australian national rugby league team]].\n\nPearce was captain of the [[Balmain Tigers]] rugby league club from 1982\u20131990. A local junior from the Balmain Police Boys club, he made his debut in [[NSWRFL season 1980|1980]] and was quickly marked as a future star.\n\nPearce's son, [[Mitchell Pearce|Mitchell]] is a half-back previously for the [[Sydney Roosters]] and currently for the [[Newcastle Knights]]\n\n==Captaincy==\nPearce's captaincy proved critical in elevating Balmain from also-rans to a force of the 1980s, in concert with [[Steve Roach (rugby league footballer)|Steve Roach]], [[Benny Elias]] and later [[Paul Sironen]]. Along with fullback [[Garry Jack]], they drove Balmain to the semi-finals in [[NSWRFL season 1983|1983]] and every year from 1985 to Pearce's retirement. Pearce won the Rothman's Medal for the best-and-fairest player in 1985.\n\nIn 1986 Pearce captained the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales Blues]] to their first ever [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] clean-sweep, but in the following two years there was to be a rapid decline, with Queensland easily winning every match in 1988. After this, Pearce stood down from representative rugby league, despite pressure for him to return after Queensland won even more easily in 1989. In 1988 he was awarded the Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] \"for service to rugby league\".  Pearce was also the inaugural winner of the [[Ken Stephen Medal]] for Community Service by a professional [[rugby league]] footballer. {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nPearce also made an appearance the 1988 Australian television movie ''[[The First Kangaroos]]'', which depicted the [[1908\u201309 Kangaroo tour of Great Britain]].<ref>{{Cite news \n| last = John Robinson and Garrett Jones\n| title = Family fights to clear League Hero's Name\n| work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]]\n| place = Australia\n| page = 74\n| date = 8 June 1988\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eq8yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XOQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3217,6447980\n| accessdate = 20 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nPearce captained the Balmain Tigers to two successive grand finals in 1988 and 1989, both of which they lost. In 1990, Pearce could not play a full match until the seventeenth round, but for the rest of the season he was at his best, seen clearly in the play-off for fifth with Newcastle, when he scored a crucial try from a [[Bomb (kick)|bomb]] and carted the ball forward as fearlessly as ever. The following week, though, proved to be his last match as Balmain lost 0\u201316, sparking a major decline in the club's fortunes after Pearce's retirement.\n\n==Coaching career==\nPearce took over as Balmain coach in 1994 from the departing Alan Jones as the club finished with the wooden spoon at seasons end.  Pearce coached Balmain for another five seasons before they merged with the [[Western Suburbs Magpies]].  In 2000, Pearce became the inaugural coach of the [[Wests Tigers]] but stepped down after one season.  Pearce also coached New South Wales for three seasons and in 2000 led New South Wales to a clean sweep winning the series 3\u20130 with the blues winning game 3 by a then record margin of 40 points.  The match was also remembered for Bryan Fletcher's infamous hand grenade try celebration.  In 2001, Pearce coached NSW in what would prove to be his last series.  His last game in charge was the widely remembered victory by Queensland who defeated NSW 40\u201314 where [[Allan Langer]] who had been playing over in England was phoned by Maroons coach [[Wayne Bennett (rugby league)|Wayne Bennett]] in an urgent SOS call to return to Australia for the match.  The next day, Sydney newspaper The Daily Telegraph wrote the headline \"Bloody Alf\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.waynepearce.com.au/about-wayne |title = Wayne Pearce &#124; About Wayne}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/inner-west/leichhardt-oval-hill-to-be-renamed-wayne-pearce-hill-after-balmain-tigers-and-wests-tigers-legend/news-story/de3702d8a526f603298e7f46816da62e |title = Leichhardt Oval hill to be Wayne Pearce Hill|date = 29 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/the-30-greatest-controversies-in-30-years-of-state-of-origin-series/news-story/f7b60988acf3f2f35558ad120e0cfaaa?sv=eafb47fc10ea8d202789d51180f98a7d |title = Origin's great controversies|date = 22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nIn February 2008, Pearce was named in the list of Australia's [[List of Australian rugby league's 100 greatest players|''100 Greatest Players'']] (1908\u20132007) which was commissioned by the [[National Rugby League|NRL]] and [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]] to celebrate the code's centenary year in Australia.<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Cassidy|publisher=Macquarie National News|title=Controversy reigns as NRL releases top 100 players|url=http://www.livenews.com.au/Articles/2008/02/22/Controversy_reigns_as_NRL_releases_top_100_players|accessdate=23 February 2008|date=23 February 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225164807/http://www.livenews.com.au/Articles/2008/02/22/Controversy_reigns_as_NRL_releases_top_100_players|archivedate=25 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=[[National Rugby League|NRL]] & [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]]|title=Centenary of Rugby League \u2013 The Players|url=http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/the-players.aspx?cat=3&list=true|accessdate=23 February 2008|date=23 February 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226180521/http://www.centenaryofrugbyleague.com.au/site/the-players.aspx?cat=3&list=true|archivedate=26 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Post retirement==\nAfter 10 years as a rugby league commentator for Fox Sports, Pearce was appointed as one of the nine inaugural commissioners of the [[Australian Rugby League Commission]] at its reconstitution in February 2012.  A motivational speaker, he continues to run his leadership and team performance consultancy Wayne Pearce Advantage.<ref>{{Cite news \n| last = John Robinson and Garrett Jones\n| title = Family fights to clear League Hero's Name\n| work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]]\n| place = Australia\n| page = 74\n| date = 8 June 1988\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eq8yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XOQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3217,6447980\n| accessdate = 20 February 2011}}</ref> He also fronts the rock cover band ''Wayne Pearce and the Big Hitters''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Cassidy|publisher=Macquarie National News|title=Controversy reigns as NRL releases top 100 players|url=http://www.livenews.com.au/Articles/2008/02/22/Controversy_reigns_as_NRL_releases_top_100_players|accessdate=23 February 2008|date=23 February 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225164807/http://www.livenews.com.au/Articles/2008/02/22/Controversy_reigns_as_NRL_releases_top_100_players|archivedate=25 February 2008}}</ref> On Sunday 17 April 2016, before Wests Tigers Vs Melbourne Storm round 7, (26 Years after his retirement) the Hill surrounding Leichhardt Oval was named the Wayne Pearce Hill after him by the Leichhardt Municipal Council and the Wests Tigers Club.\n\n==References==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see [http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php] -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n  before = [[Alan Jones (radio broadcaster)|Alan Jones]]<br>1991\u20131993|\n  after = Joint Venture|\n