n Pearce\n| image =\n| caption =\n| country =\n| position = {{rlp|LK|SR}}\n| currentclub =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|3|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Balmain, New South Wales]], Australia\n| retired = yes\n| height = {{convert|180|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|89|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n| club1 = [[Balmain Tigers]]\n| year1start = 1980\n| year1end = 90\n| appearances1 = 193\n| tries1 = 33\n| goals1 = 0\n| fieldgoals1 = 0\n| points1 = 123\n| teamA = [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n| yearAstart = 1983\n| yearAend = 88\n| appearancesA = 16\n| triesA = 3\n| goalsA = 0\n| fieldgoalsA = 0\n| pointsA = 12\n| teamB = [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]]\n| yearBstart = 1982\n| yearBend = 88\n| appearancesB = 19\n| triesB = 6\n| goalsB = 0\n| fieldgoalsB = 0\n| pointsB = 21\n| teamC = [[City New South Wales rugby league team|NSW City]]\n| yearCstart = 1983\n| yearCend = 88\n| appearancesC = 6\n| triesC = 1\n| goalsC = 0\n| fieldgoalsC = 0\n| pointsC = 4\n| coachyear1start = 1994\n| coachyear1end = 99\n| coachteam1 = [[Balmain Tigers]]\n| coachgames1 = 158\n| coachwins1 = 55\n| coachdraws1 = 1\n| coachlosses1 = 101\n| coachyear2start = 2000\n| coachyear2end =\n| coachteam2 = [[Wests Tigers]]\n| coachgames2 = 26\n| coachwins2 = 11\n| coachdraws2 = 2\n| coachlosses2 = 13\n| coachyearAstart = 1999\n| coachyearAend = 01\n| coachteamA = [[New South Wales state rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n| coachgamesA = 9\n| coachwinsA = 5\n| coachdrawsA = 1\n| coachlossesA = 3\n| source = <ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.com/players/Wayne_Pearce.html RLP]</ref><ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/coaches/wayne-pearce/summary.html Rugby League Project Coaches]</ref>\n| updated = 5 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Wayne John Pearce''' [[Order of Australia|OAM]] (born 29 March 1960 in [[Balmain, New South Wales]]) is an Australian former professional [[rugby league]] footballer and coach. An athletic {{rlp|lk}} for the [[Balmain Tigers]], he was affectionately known as 'Junior'. Pearce represented [[New South Wales Rugby League team|New South Wales]] in the [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin Series]] as well as the [[Australian national rugby league team]].\n\nPearce was captain of the [[Balmain Tigers]] rugby league club from 1982\u20131990. A local junior from the Balmain Police Boys club, he made his debut in [[NSWRFL season 1980|1980]] and was quickly marked as a future star.\n\nPearce's son, [[Mitchell Pearce|Mitchell]] is a half-back previously for the [[Sydney Roosters]] and currently for the [[Newcastle Knights]]\n\n==Captaincy==\nPearce's captaincy proved critical in elevating Balmain from also-rans to a force of the 1980s, in concert with [[Steve Roach (rugby league footballer)|Steve Roach]], [[Benny Elias]] and later [[Paul Sironen]]. Along with fullback [[Garry Jack]], they drove Balmain to the semi-finals in [[NSWRFL season 1983|1983]] and every year from 1985 to Pearce's retirement. Pearce won the Rothman's Medal for the best-and-fairest player in 1985.\n\nIn 1986 Pearce captained the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales Blues]] to their first ever [[Rugby League State of Origin|State of Origin]] clean-sweep, but in the following two years there was to be a rapid decline, with Queensland easily winning every match in 1988. After this, Pearce stood down from representative rugby league, despite pressure for him to return after Queensland won even more easily in 1989. In 1988 he was awarded the Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] \"for service to rugby league\".  Pearce was also the inaugural winner of the [[Ken Stephen Medal]] for Community Service by a professional [[rugby league]] footballer. {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nPearce also made an appearance the 1988 Australian television movie ''[[The First Kangaroos]]'', which depicted the [[1908\u201309 Kangaroo tour of Great Britain]].<ref>{{Cite news \n| last = John Robinson and Garrett Jones\n|