{"title_page": "Andy Millen", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{ infobox football biography\n| name        = Andy Millen\n| fullname    = Andrew Frank Millen\n| height      =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1965|06|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| currentclub =  [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] (Development Squad manager)\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1 = 1986\u20131987 | caps1 = 71  | goals1 = 2  | clubs1 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]\n| years2 = 1987\u20131990 | caps2 = 111 | goals2 = 9  | clubs2 = [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]\n| years3 = 1990\u20131993 | caps3 = 119 | goals3 = 4  | clubs3 = [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]]\n| years4 = 1993\u20131995 | caps4 = 57  | goals4 = 0  | clubs4 = [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]\n| years5 = 1995      | caps5 = ?   | goals5 = 0  | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Ipswich Town]] (loan)\n| years6 = 1995\u20131997 | caps6 = 51  | goals6 = 0  | clubs6 = [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]\n| years7 = 1997      | caps7 = 18  | goals7 = 0  | clubs7 = [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n| years8 = 1997      | caps8 = 3   | goals8 = 1  | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] (loan)\n| years9 = 1997\u20131999 | caps9 = 57  | goals9 = 2  | clubs9 = [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]]\n| years10 = 1999\u20132001 | caps10 = 44  | goals10 = 0  | clubs10 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]\n| years11= 2001\u20132004 | caps11= 89  | goals11= 11 | clubs11= [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]\n| years12= 2004\u20132008 | caps12= 114 | goals12= 1  | clubs12= [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]\n| years13= 2011      | caps13= 19  | goals13= 0  | clubs13= [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]]\n| totalcaps = 753 | totalgoals = 30\n| nationalyears1 = 1994 | nationalteam1 = [[Scotland B national football team|Scotland B]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2014\u20132015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] (caretaker) \n| manageryears2 = 2015\u20132017\n| managerclubs2 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] (Development squad manager)\n| manageryears3 = 2017\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] (Development squad manager)\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Frank Millen''' (born 10 June 1965, in [[Glasgow]]) is a Scottish professional [[association football|football]] player and coach. He is currently the development squad manager at [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], after leaving a similar post at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]].\n\nDuring his long career, Millen played primarily as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]], [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]], [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]], [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]], [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]], [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]], [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] and [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]].\n\nHe continued to play for [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] in the [[Scottish Premier League]] aged 42. Millen played for [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] in the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Scottish Third Division]], aged 45.\n\n==Career==\n\nEarly in his playing career, Millen won the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] twice with [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]]. During his spell with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] he won a [[Scotland B national football team|Scotland B]] cap against [[Wales B national football team|Wales B]].<ref>[http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=528 SCOTLAND B INTERNATIONALS], [[Scottish Football Association]].</ref>\n\nMillen earned fame later in his career for continuing to play at a senior level despite his advanced professional age. When he played for [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on 5 May 2007 at [[Tannadice Park|Tannadice]], he became the oldest player to play in the [[Scottish Premier League]].<ref name = \"SPL oldest\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/6656301.stm |title=Millen confirmed as SPL's oldest |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=14 May 2007 |accessdate=9 June 2010}}</ref> He broke the record set by [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] [[goalkeeper (football)|goalkeeper]] [[Jim Leighton]], who was aged 41 years and 302 days when he last played in the SPL.<ref name = \"SPL oldest\"/> [[Gus MacPherson]] argued that Millen's record is more notable because Millen played in the more physical role of an outfield player.<ref name = \"SPL oldest\"/>\n\nMillen took control of the St Mirren team for a match against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] in November 2007, after a family bereavement prevented [[Gus MacPherson]] from attending the match, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}\n\nMillen announced his intention to retire from first team football in June 2008.<ref name = \"Millen hangs up boots\"/> During his time with St Mirren, he won the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] and the [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] in the [[2005\u201306 in Scottish football|2005\u201306 season]].<ref name = \"Millen hangs up boots\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/7470759.stm |title=Millen hangs up boots for Buddies |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=24 June 2008}}</ref> Millen's last league appearance was against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] on 15 March 2008, which meant that he set the [[Scottish Premier League#SPL records|SPL record]] for oldest player at 42 years and 279 days, almost a whole year more than the previous record.\n\nMillen continued working as assistant manager to Gus MacPherson after retiring as a player. After [[Danny Lennon]] was appointed as manager, however, Millen left the club to allow Lennon to appoint his own backroom staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/8735388.stm|work=BBC News|title=St Mirren and Millen part company|date=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nMillen was appointed as [[Billy Reid (footballer born 1963)|Billy Reid]]'s new assistant at Hamilton Academical in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hamilton_academical/8856918.stm |title=Andy Millen given Hamilton Accies assistant manager job |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref> He left the club in December due to a contract dispute.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/hamilton/2010/12/12/hamilton-u-turn-as-stuart-taylor-is-re-appointed-first-team-coach-10-days-after-leaving-club-86908-22778829/|work=[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]]|last=McDermott|first=Scott|title=Hamilton U-turn as Stuart Taylor is re-appointed first-team coach 10 days after leaving club|date=12 December 2010|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nDue to an injury to [[James Brough (footballer)|James Brough]], Millen re-registered as a player to sign for amateurs [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] in January 2011.\n\nMillen was appointed assistant manager of [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] on his 46th birthday on 10 June 2011.<ref name = \"newqos\">[http://qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=694 \"Gus is our new Manager\" www.qosfc.com 10 Jun 2011]</ref> Millen parted company with Queens on 30 April 2012, alongside MacPherson, after the club was relegated to the Scottish Second Division.<ref>http://www.qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=1236</ref> He then became assistant to [[Mark Roberts (footballer, born 1975)|Mark Roberts]] at [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] and was appointed caretaker manager in December 2014, after Roberts was sacked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30491310 |first=John |last=Barnes |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=16 December 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014 |title=Ayr United sack manager Mark Roberts}}</ref>\n\nMillen was appointed Development Squad Manager at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton-fc/articles/2015/05/25/849300-exclusive-millen-takes-morton-under-20s-role/|title=Millen takes Morton under-20s role|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=25 May 2015|accessdate=26 May 2015|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref> He left the club in May 2017 to take any opportunity elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gmfc.net/2017/05/16/andy-millen-leaves-development-squad-post/|title=Andy Millen leaves development squad post|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=16 May 2017|accessdate=22 May 2017|publisher=Greenock Morton F.C.}}</ref> It was announced that he had taken over the development squad manager's role at [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kilmarnockfc.co.uk/Article?id=5742|title=Andy Millen appointed U20 manager|publisher=Kilmarnock F.C.|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Managerial statistics===\n{{As of|2017|5|23}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United (caretaker)]]\n|{{flagicon|Scotland}} \n|align=left|December 2014\n|align=left|January 2015\n{{WDL|3|0|1|2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton (U20)]]\n|{{flagicon|Scotland}} \n|align=left|May 2015\n|align=left|May 2017\n{{WDL|46|29|11|6}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock (U20)]]\n|{{flagicon|Scotland}} \n|align=left|May 2017\n|align=left|present\n{{WDL|0|0|0|0}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n''Hamilton Academical''\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] (2): Winners 1991-92, 1992\u201393\n\n''St Mirren''\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] (3): Winners 2005-06\n*[[Scottish First Division]] (1): Champions 2005-06\n*[[Renfrewshire Cup]] (2): Winners 2006-07, 2007\u201308\n\n===Manager===\n''Morton''\n*Development League West (1): Champions 2015-16\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n* {{cite book| last=Jeffrey | first=Jim | title=The Men Who Made Hibernian F.C. since 1946 | publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd | year=2005 | isbn=0-7524-3091-2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Millen, Andy}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Academical F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kilmarnock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hibernian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Raith Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ayr United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Clyde F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Clyde F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Academical F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Queen's Park F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Kilmarnock F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{ infobox football biography\n| name        = Andy Millen\n| fullname    = Andrew Frank Millen\n| height      =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1965|06|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| currentclub =  [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] (Development squad manager)\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1 = 1986\u20131987 | caps1 = 71  | goals1 = 2  | clubs1 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]\n| years2 = 1987\u20131990 | caps2 = 111 | goals2 = 9  | clubs2 = [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]\n| years3 = 1990\u20131993 | caps3 = 119 | goals3 = 4  | clu