lloa Athletic]], [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]], [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]], [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]], [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]], [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] and [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]].\n\nHe continued to play for [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] in the [[Scottish Premier League]] aged 42. Millen played for [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] in the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Scottish Third Division]], aged 45.\n\n==Career==\n\nEarly in his playing career, Millen won the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] twice with [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]]. During his spell with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] he won a [[Scotland B national football team|Scotland B]] cap against [[Wales B national football team|Wales B]].<ref>[http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=528 SCOTLAND B INTERNATIONALS], [[Scottish Football Association]].</ref>\n\nMillen earned fame later in his career for continuing to play at a senior level despite his advanced professional age. When he played for [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on 5 May 2007 at [[Tannadice Park|Tannadice]], he became the oldest player to play in the [[Scottish Premier League]].<ref name = \"SPL oldest\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/6656301.stm |title=Millen confirmed as SPL's oldest |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=14 May 2007 |accessdate=9 June 2010}}</ref> He broke the record set by [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] [[goalkeeper (football)|goalkeeper]] [[Jim Leighton]], who was aged 41 years and 302 days when he last played in the SPL.<ref name = \"SPL oldest\"/> [[Gus MacPherson]] argued that Millen's record is more notable because Millen played in the more physical role of an outfield player.<ref name = \"SPL oldest\"/>\n\nMillen took control of the St Mirren team for a match against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] in November 2007, after a family bereavement prevented [[Gus MacPherson]] from attending the match, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}\n\nMillen announced his intention to retire from first team football in June 2008.<ref name = \"Millen hangs up boots\"/> During his time with St Mirren, he won the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] and the [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] in the [[2005\u201306 in Scottish football|2005\u201306 season]].<ref name = \"Millen hangs up boots\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/7470759.stm |title=Millen hangs up boots for Buddies |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=24 June 2008}}</ref> Millen's last league appearance was against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] on 15 March 2008, which meant that he set the [[Scottish Premier League#SPL records|SPL record]] for oldest player at 42 years and 279 days, almost a whole year more than the previous record.\n\nMillen continued working as assistant manager to Gus MacPherson after retiring as a player. After [[Danny Lennon]] was appointed as manager, however, Millen left the club to allow Lennon to appoint his own backroom staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/8735388.stm|work=BBC News|title=St Mirren and Millen part company|date=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nMillen was appointed as [[Billy Reid (footballer born 1963)|Billy Reid]]'s new assistant at Hamilton Academical in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hamilton_academical/8856918.stm |title=Andy Millen given Hamilton Accies assistant manager job |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref> He left the club in December due to a contract dispute.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/hamilton/2010/12/12/hamilton-u-turn-as-stuart-taylor-is-re-appointed-first-team-coach-10-days-after-leaving-club-86908-22778829/|work=[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]]|last=McDermott|first=Scott|title=Hamilton U-turn as Stuart Taylor is re-appointed first-team coach 10 days after leaving club|date=12 December 2010|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nDue to an injury to [[James Brough (footballer)|James Brough]], Millen re-registered as a player to sign for amateurs [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] in January 2011.\n\nMillen was appointed assistant manager of [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] on his 46th birthday on 10 June 2011.<ref name = \"newqos\">[http://qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=694 \"Gus is our new Manager\" www.qosfc.com 10 Jun 2011]</ref> Millen parted company with Queens on 30 April 2012, alongside MacPherson, after the club was relegated to the Scottish Second Division.<ref>http://www.qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=1236</ref> He then became assistant to [[Mark Roberts (footballer, born 1975)|Mark Roberts]] at [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] and was appointed caretaker manager in December 2014, after Roberts was sacked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30491310 |first=John |last=Barnes |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=16 December 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014 |title=Ayr United sack manager Mark Roberts}}</ref>\n\nMillen was appointed Development Squad Manager at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton-fc/articles/2015/05/25/849300-exclusive-millen-takes-morton-under-20s-role/|title=Millen takes Morton under-20s role|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=25 May 2015|accessdate=26 May 2015|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref> He left the club in May 2017 to take any opportunity elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gmfc.net/2017/05/16/andy-millen-leaves-development-squad-post/|title=Andy Millen leaves development squad post|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=16 May 2017|accessdate=22 May 2017|publisher=Greenock Morton F.C.}}</ref> It was announced that he had taken over the development squad manager's role at [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kilmarnockfc.co.uk/Article?id=5742|title=Andy Millen appointed U20 manager|publisher=Kilmarnock F.C.|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Managerial statistics===\n{{As of|2017|5|23}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United (caretaker)]]\n|{{flagicon|Scotland}} \n|align=left|December 2014\n|align=left|January 2015\n{{WDL|3|0|1|2}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton (U20)]]\n|{{flagicon|Scotland}} \n|align=left|May 2015\n|align=left|May 2017\n{{WDL|46|29|11|6}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock (U20)]]\n|{{flagicon|Scotland}} \n|align=left|May 2017\n|align=left|present\n{{WDL|0|0|0|0}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n''Hamilton Academical''\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] (2): Winners 1991-92, 1992\u201393\n\n''St Mirren''\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] (3): Winners 2005-06\n*[[Scottish First Division]] (1): Champions 2005-06\n*[[Renfrewshire Cup]] (2): Winners 2006-07, 2007\u201308\n\n===Manager===\n''Morton''\n*Development League West (1): Champions 2015-16\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n* {{cite book| last=Jeffrey | first=Jim | title=The Men Who Made Hibernian F.C. since 1946 | publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd | year=2005 | isbn=0-7524-3091-2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Millen, Andy}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Academical F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kilmarnock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hibernian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Raith Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ayr United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Clyde F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Clyde F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Academical F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Queen's Park F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Kilmarnock F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_Millen"}
{"title_page": "Ray Warren", "text_new": "{{For|other persons named Ray Warren|Raymond Warren (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Ray Warren\n|image         = Ray Warren.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|caption       =\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1943|6|11|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Junee]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|death_cause   =\n|nationality   = [[Australian]]\n|other_names   = Rabbits, Rabs,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Noble|first1=Freya|title=Legendary rugby league caller Ray 'Rabs' Warren to retire at the end of the NRL season \u2013 after 50 years of calling the game|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/sportsnews/article-3464998/Legendary-rugby-league-caller-Ray-Rabs-Warren-retiring-50-years.html|website=dailymail.co.uk|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd|accessdate=12 June 2016}}</ref> Rabby, The Voice of Rugby League <ref>http://www.4bc.com.au/podcast/the-voice-of-rugby-league/</ref>\n|citizenship   = Australian\n|education     =\n|alma_mater    =\n|occupation    = [[Sportscaster|Sports commentator]]\n|years active  = 1967\u2212present\n|employer      = [[Nine Network]] \n[[Triple M]]\n|home_town     =\n|salary        =\n|height        = \n|weight        =\n|title         =\n|spouse        = Cher Warren\n|partner       =\n|children      = [[Chris Warren (rugby league)|Chris Warren]] (son)<br>Holly Warren (daughter)<br>Mark Warren (son)\n|website       =\n|signature     =\n|footnotes     =\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of Australia|OAM]]\n|networth      =\n}}\n\n'''Raymond Warren''' [[Order of Australia|OAM]] (born 11 June 1943) is an [[Australia]]n sports commentator, known for his coverage of televised professional [[rugby league]] matches on the [[Nine Network. He is often called \"The Voice of Rugby League\". Warren also used to call Australian [[swimming (sport)|swimming]] team events and the FINA World Championships until Nine lost the rights to these events in 2008 and in 2012 participated in Nine's coverage of the London Olympics. \n\nOn Saturday mornings, he is a member of the panel on [[Triple M]] [[Sydney]]'s radio Saturday morning sports program [[Dead Set Legends]]. Warren's nickname is '''\"Rabbits\"''', as in a rabbit's warren.  \n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Junee, New South Wales]] on 11 June 1943,<ref name=\"smh050924\">{{cite news|first=Philip|last=Derriman|title=Warren still going full scream ahead|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/league/warren-still-going-full-scream-ahead/2005/09/23/1126982232457.html|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=2005-09-24|accessdate=2007-08-05}}</ref> Warren initially followed in the footsteps of his brother by joining the police force. He initially joined the NSW Police Cadets on 5 December 1960<ref>http://www.expolicecadets.asn.au/personality.php?id=35</ref> and then transferred to the ACT Police in Canberra in 1964.<ref>https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19627725?q&versionId=23066027</ref>  Warren stated he served a total of three years in the ACT Police during the Channel 9 broadcast of the NRL Round 23 Canberra Raiders vs Sydney Roosters match on 19 August 2018.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/08/20/full-match-replay-raiders-v-roosters---round-23-2018/</ref> It was during his stint in uniform he got a phone call as a result of all the door-knocking he had done at various radio stations as a teenager.  Ray took the job offered to him at 2LF Young, New South Wales as a sales representative, trotting commentator and rugby league commentator - a move which started his career in broadcasting.\n\nHe began commentating on television through the [[Amco Cup]] on [[Network Ten|Channel Ten]] with [[Keith Barnes]] in 1974. In 1980, Ten approached Warren to call the [[Melbourne Cup]], the first of three Cups he would call for the network.<ref>Webster, Andrew \"[http://www.insidesport.com.au/is/index?pg=adrenalin&spg=drinks/drinks_ray_warren.htm A few drinks with Ray Warren ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090920141012/http://www.insidesport.com.au/is/index?pg=adrenalin&spg=drinks%2Fdrinks_ray_warren.htm |date=20 September 2009 }}\", ''[[Inside Sport]]'' magazine, April 2004</ref> He also became Network Ten's chief Rugby League caller in 1983.<ref name=diagnosed>{{cite news|last1=AAP|title=Ray Warren diagnosed with prostate cancer|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/ray-warren-diagnosed-with-prostate-cancer-20110611-1fxtf.html|accessdate=8 September 2014|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=11 June 2011}}</ref> In 1984 he was to head up Ten's commentary for the Los Angeles Olympics but refused to take the mission. As a nervous flyer, Warren had grave reservations about the trans-Pacific haul and suddenly realised he could not get onto the plane. In 1986, Warren was fired by the network, primarily because it wanted to replace him as its chief rugby league commentator with former international player [[Rex Mossop]].<ref name=\"smh050924\"/>\n\nOver the next six years, Warren would also travel many miles to call horse races. In 1988 he was recruited by the [[Nine Network]] to commentate on the 1988 Rugby League World Cup final and the 1989 state of origin series alongside [[Darrell Eastlake]] and [[Balmain Tigers]] coach [[Warren Ryan]], 1989 Trans-Tasman test series alongside [[Darrell Eastlake]] again and [[Jack Gibson (rugby league)|Jack Gibson]] and to be part of its team to broadcast swimming at the 1990 [[Commonwealth Games]] with Norman May. The television rights for rugby league were bought by Nine for the 1991 State of Origin Series, [[1992 NSWRL season|1992 season]] and onwards and he has been calling the game for them ever since. Warren has gradually overcome his fear of flying, though he does still have some fear as evidenced by a well publicised helicopter flight to a game on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] in 2012 made necessary due to a delayed flight from Sydney to the Gold Coast. Overcoming his fear has seen him travel to [[New Zealand]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Japan]] and [[Canada]] for the network's swimming or rugby league coverage.\n\nRay Warren is known for his passionate commentary (often getting into good-natured arguments with fellow commentator [[Phil Gould (rugby league)|Phil Gould]] about a player or the rules of rugby league during games), and has often been parodied by [[The Twelfth Man]]. His voice has become synonymous with important rugby league matches in Australia, and he is renowned for his proficient ability to take over from fellow-commentators when anything interesting happens on the field.\n\nPreviously, Warren also worked on [[Sydney]] [[radio station]] [[2MMM]] on the Saturday morning sports show [[Dead Set Legends]] with [[Richard Freedman]] and Dan Ginnane, as well being a semi-regular host of 'The Rush Hour' with Dan Ginnane.\n\nWarren was the footy-tip guru with [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]]'s [[radio station]] [[NXFM]] on the [[Steve and Kim]] (& Damo!) Morning Breakfast Talk Show (until the show was cancelled on 26-Oct-2012).<ref>{{cite web|title=NXFM Says goodbye to Steve And Kim|url=http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/1116-nxfm-drop-their-breakfast-show-after-11-years.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiotoday.com.au/media/files/nx.pdf|work=NXFM Official Statement (Steve & Kim Breakfast Show)}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nWarren is also a contributor on Melbourne's Sport 927.\n\nOn 6 August 2011, a bronze statue of Warren was erected in his hometown of Junee.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Riccio|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/legendary-commentator-ray-warren-honoured-with-bronze-statue-in-junee/story-e6frfgbo-1226109941493|title=Legendary commentator Ray Warren honoured with bronze statue in Junee|work=The Sunday Telegraph|date=6 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Warren was inducted into the [[National Rugby League Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/nrl/ray-warren-hall-of-fame-induction-nine-legends-pay-tribute/307ceb35-1dcd-4f65-8be4-ba5a3ecc59a1/|title=Peter Sterling leads tributes to Hall of Fame inductee Ray Warren|website=WWOS}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRay Warren lives in the Sydney suburb of [[Castle Hill, New South Wales|Castle Hill]] with his wife, Cher, and daughter, Holly. Ray's son, [[Chris Warren (rugby league)|Chris Warren]],<ref name=fox-profile>{{cite web |title=Chris Warren is a presenter on FOX SPORTS NEWS. |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/tvguide/fox-sports-news/chris-warren/story-fn5k3wud-1225974920858?nk=1e099da73acaa0f6cc9f20dc640afc97 |website=www.foxsports.com.au |accessdate=8 September 2014 |date=2 December 2009}}</ref> was a rugby league presenter for [[Sky Sports]] in the [[United Kingdom]] and was a producer for the now defunct Setanta Sports NRL coverage in Europe. He now works for [[2GB]] Sydney on their NRL coverage and [[Fox Sports News (Australia)|Fox Sports News]]. Ray was once the chief commentator in a match that Chris participated in while he was a player for the [[Western Suburbs Magpies]] in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sygall |first=David  |title=Rabs admits: gambling cost me a better life |work=[[The Age]] |place=Australia |publisher=Fairfax Digital |date=2010-05-02\n|url=http://www.theage.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/rabs-admits-gambling-cost-me-a-better-life-20100501-u04t.html |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> \n\nHis other son Mark is the Director of the company Warren Media, a voice over artist and media buyer. <ref>http://warrenmedia.com.au/mark-warren/broadcaster/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Warren, Ray}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Swimming commentators]]\n[[Category:Triple M presenters]]\n[[Category:Nine's Wide World of Sport]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league commentators]]\n[[Category:People from Junee, New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other persons named Ray Warren|Raymond Warren (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Ray Warren\n|image         = Ray Warren.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|caption       =\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1943|6|11|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Junee]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|death_cause   =\n|nationality   = [[Australian]]\n|other_names   = Rabbits, Rabs,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Noble|first1=Freya|title=Legendary rugby league caller Ray 'Rabs' Warren to retire at the end of the NRL season \u2013 after 50 years of calling the game|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/sportsnews/article-3464998/Legendary-rugby-league-caller-Ray-Rabs-Warren-retiring-50-years.html|website=dailymail.co.uk|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd|accessdate=12 June 2016}}</ref> Rabby, The Voice of Rugby League <ref>http://www.4bc.com.au/podcast/the-voice-of-rugby-league/</ref>\n|citizenship   = Australian\n|education     =\n|alma_mater    =\n|occupation    = [[Sportscaster|Sports commentator]]\n|years active  = 1967\u2212present\n|employer      = [[Nine Network]] \n[[Triple M]]\n|home_town     =\n|salary        =\n|height        = \n|weight        =\n|title         =\n|spouse        = Cher Warren\n|partner       =\n|children      = [[Chris Warren (rugby league)|Chris Warren]] (son)<br>Holly Warren (daughter)<br>Mark Warren (son)\n|website       =\n|signature     =\n|footnotes     =\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of Australia|OAM]]\n|networth      =\n}}\n\n'''Raymond Warren''' [[Order of Australia|OAM]] (born 11 June 1943) is an [[Australia]]n sports commentator, known for his coverage of televised professional [[rugby league]] matches on the [[Nine Network. He is often called \"The Voice of Rugby League\". Warren also used to call Australian [[swimming (sport)|swimming]] team events and the FINA World Championships until Nine lost the rights to these events in 2008 and in 2012 participated in Nine's coverage of the London Olympics. \n\nOn Saturday mornings, he is a member of the panel on [[Triple M]] [[Sydney]]'s radio Saturday morning sports program [[Dead Set Legends]]. Warren's nickname is '''\"Rabbits\"''', as in a rabbit's warren.  \n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Junee, New South Wales]] on 11 June 1943,<ref name=\"smh050924\">{{cite news|first=Philip|last=Derriman|title=Warren still going full scream ahead|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/league/warren-still-going-full-scream-ahead/2005/09/23/1126982232457.html|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=2005-09-24|accessdate=2007-08-05}}</ref> Warren initially followed in the footsteps of his brother by joining the police force. He initially joined the NSW Police Cadets on 5 December 1960<ref>http://www.expolicecadets.asn.au/personality.php?id=35</ref> and then transferred to the ACT Police in Canberra in 1964.<ref>https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/19627725?q&versionId=23066027</ref>  Warren stated he served a total of three years in the ACT Police during the Channel 9 broadcast of the NRL Round 23 Canberra Raiders vs Sydney Roosters match on 19 August 2018.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/08/20/full-match-replay-raiders-v-roosters---round-23-2018/</ref> It was during his stint in uniform he got a phone call as a result of all the door-knocking he had done at various radio stations as a teenager.  Ray took the job offered to him at 2LF Young, New South Wales as a sales representative, trotting commentator and rugby league commentator - a move which started his career in broadcasting.\n\nHe began commentating on television through the [[Amco Cup]] on [[Network Ten|Channel Ten]] with [[Keith Barnes]] in 1974. In 1980, Ten approached Warren to call the [[Melbourne Cup]], the first of three Cu